Subject: Re: [sfraves] Massive or Underground

I dunno...  I have personally never been fucked with at a party,  
large or small.  But after the last time I went to a party at the  
crackhouse (And I freely stipulate that going to that one was a  
mistake.) I've pretty much been through with skeezy oakland venues,  
and all the risks that side of the bridge entails.  Basically, the  
local lowlifes decided to raid the party, steal the cashbox, and  
shoot up the place on their way out.  Fortunately, no one was hurt.   
And on our way out, the line of broken-into-cars stopped two places  
before my friend's who drove.

After that, we went back to the east bay for two parties; both at  
venues with secured, fenced-in, parking and nowhere near the  
crackhouse; haven't gone back since; and don't plan to.

Say what you want about overly candy, "fully permitted", commercial  
parties in San Francisco like Lift 2, where I went last weekend.   
Sure, it was a 2500-person "mini-massive".  But by having it at that  
venue, the promoter made sure that I could park my car somewhere  
safe, where I could be sure it'd be there and unmolested when I got  
back to it at the end of the night; and where the locals aren't a  
bunch of thugs who are going to shoot at people.  Bill Graham  
parties?  I can take MUNI there and back and never have to worry.   
The Regency?  I park across the street from the Japanese-old-folks- 
home a few blocks over.


cya,
john

At the crackhouse?! @_@ Wow, I didn't hear about that -- been in Asia for
the past 4 years so I'm pretty behind in the times. I'm glad to hear nobody
was hurt... I went to a party there back in 2001, but I can fully imagine
that happening. :( Must have been scary, your friend got pretty lucky to
have been bypassed by the car thieves!

On a similar note, back in 2002 or 2003, I attended an UG in Oakland and the
party ended prematurely around 3am when a few thugs decided to slug it out
in the middle of the dancefloor -- then after getting kicked out them and
their posse started banging loudly on the warehouse walls... An isolated
incident.

Party poopers -- meh! >_>;

peace,
Chris

Saturday 7-7-7 (SF)

WARNING: F*7K!N6 INCREDIBLE LINEUP!!!!!

Saturday, July 7th 2007 (7-7-7):
CaliGrown Events proudly presents BACK ON TRACK, featuring world-class acts 
from Belgium,
Chicago, Las Vegas, and San Francisco. Enjoy all night drink specials while 
grooving to:

CONGA SQUAD aka C-MOS (Holographic Music, Belgium)
Known to many as Conga Squad, Olivier Abbeloos also produces under names 
such as C-Mos,
Goldbumpers, Dynetic, Bio-nic, Inferno, Quadrophonia, T99, and Kretek. Over 
the past 15
years, this Disco House master has developed a signature sound that is like 
no other in
House music. His style of pumpin, steppy, driving Disco House has made 
Olivier a huge
success with many of the most influential DJ's from around the world. Not 
only a successful
music producer, Mr. Abbeloos is also a successful DJ with over 18 years of 
experience.
Olivier Abbeloos performs all over the world, and has several residencies in 
his home
country of Belgium including La Rocca. Abbeloos is also the founder & 
primary artist of
legendary House labels Holographic Music & E.P.O.S, and has released over 
fifty (50) tracks
to date! DO NOT UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCES MISS CONGA SQUAD!
MORE INFO: WWW.HOLOGRAPHICMUSIC.COM
http://www.myspace.com/abbeloosolivier

HIGH CALIBER aka BRYAN JONES & MIKE GILLENWATER (Nocturnal / Olive / Moody / 
Carizma / Nine
/ Control, Chicago)
Wrapping up his international Step Back 2007 Tour, DJ Bryan Jones joins Mike 
Gillenwater as
High Caliber, originally formed in late 2002. Both artists hail from Chicago 
where they’ve
independently established themselves as icons in the Funky House scene. Five 
years and
nearly 20 chart-busting EPs later, High Caliber is releasing their biggest 
project to date:
“Old School Sessions,” a four-part all-digital mix series that was too long 
to condense into
one album. Catch tracks from this new groundbreaking series along with other 
HC classics for
a floor-rocking experience San Francisco will surely not forget!
MORE INFO: WWW.MYSPACE.COM/HIGHCALIBERCHICAGO

JENO (WICKED,SF)
A name that needs no introduction in SF House Music, Jeno has been 
organizing legendary
underground parties and rocking dance floors around the world since the 
mid-eighties. As one
of the “Wicked” DJ’s, Jeno helped define an eclectic and soulful musical 
style that was the
original sound of San Francisco.
MORE INFO: WWW.DJJENO.COM
http://www.myspace.com/jeno

ERIC SPIRE (Silver Pearl Records / Sony Records / QUEST , Bay Area & Las 
Vegas)
The owner & founder of Silver Pearl records, world-famous DJ, and founding 
father of Quest;
Eric Spire has spent the past 7 years in the studio producing major label 
acts, television
themes, movie soundtracks, video game sound bytes, and quite of bit of Dance 
Music. Missing
the excitement of the crowd, Eric is returning to the decks to grace his 
fans with another
masterful & soul-moving set that they have been craving since 2000!
MORE INFO: WWW.SILVERPEARL.COM
http://www.myspace.com/silverprl1

WITH SPECIAL GUESTS:

THE MARIO BROS. - TAG SET (OtherWorld / Tech Funk Alliance / Midnight Sons / 
Essential
Breaks West, SF)
What can we say about these guys? They're fucking awesome! The Mario Bros. 
is made up of one
part "daniella downs", one part "Marc(O)" and a whole lot of pimp juice. 
They are best
served straight up in a highball glass...
http://www.myspace.com/the_mario_bros

THE FINGERMONSTERS - LIVE PA (SHAZBOT, ORIGAMI, ANDREW PHELAN, and CUBIK , 
SF)
The Fingermonsters create maximal floor-magnet tracks with tongue firmly in 
cheek and hands
firmly on knobs. They’ve been tearing San Francisco and the Bay Area a new 
one with a
4-person live laptop/drum machine PA assault that is not to be missed!

DJ HEADCASE - LIVE PA - CD RELEASE PARTY (CaliGrown , SF)

JAYSON KINCAID (Grooves-in-the-Park / Culture / Om Records , SF)
http://www.myspace.com/jaysonkincaid

DEAN KROH (Seedless Music, Liquid Graf-X-209)

SPACE COWBOY DJ’S:
AARON JAE (Space Cowboys/XM/Evil Breaks)

“WTF are CaliGrown Events?”

We’re a spin-off of a former Central Valley UG rave crew called Elysium from 
the
late 90’s - early 00’s. Elysium produced several events in the Central 
Valley, and
some in the Bay Area including a residence at the now infamous Hotel Ibiza 
in
2001. CaliGrown is based out of San Jose. We produce events out of love for 
the
music and the vibe its followers carry.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: BASSDROP w/ Stabilizer (UK) - Thurs June 14th, FREE

Bassdrop
Thursday, June 14th, 2007
@ Shine (1337 Mission st)
9pm-2am
FREE!!!
21+

It's our 3rd Bassdrop and once again we've got another WICKED UK
headliner. You really don't want to sleep on this one, cause it's goin
to be a bangin night.


Stabilizer
(Plastic Raygun/Boombox/Functional Breaks/Lithium Music)

As a producer Stabilizer has earned many supporters in the breaks
fraternity and beyond. A series of singles and remixes over the past
three years, on labels such as Boombox Records, Kosmo and Functional
Breaks, have gained the support of Andy Weatherall, Boy George, Annie
Nightingale (Radio 1), Hybrid, Krafty Kuts, Scanty Sandwich,
Scissorkicks, Anthony Pappa and Caspar Kedros (Headrillaz) among
others.

Stabilizer is now signed to the mighty Plastic Raygun and the first
single release, What It Takes rose to Number 5 in the DJ Mag breaks
chart as well as being described as "A Classic" by none other than
Andy Weatherall.

As well as the production, Stabilizer can be found despoiling the
world=D5s ears in a breakbeat and punky house fashion in places as
diverse as Bath, Bognor and Berlin, with a US tour planned.

Armed with a bag of records and a sampler - with an emphasis firmly on
good tunes and a good time - the Stabilizer DJ style is tight, varied
and always full of energy. With genres ranging from Hip Hip and Funk
via punky house all the way to the freshest nu-school breaks cuts.
Only two rules... it's got to be good, and it's got to be funky.


Along with:
DJ Unagi (Word of Mouth) - Special birthday set
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
Athena (Evil Breaks)

more info on this & other events: www.EvilBreaks.com

--=20

there's a great day party in oakland on Sunday.

SPRING TRAINING
Sunday, June 3rd
Woodminster Falls @ Joaquin Miller Park, Oakland
Noon-8p
Free

False Profit and Rhythm Society are putting on a day party on Sunday
June 3rd in Joaquin Miller Park which is in the Oakland Hills.
Specifically, in front of the waterfalls and pools near Woodminster
Ampitheater . We did this party last year under the name Springfest,
but will likely have a new name. It's an amazing space and rather
unique. Stephen, Brendan, myself and a few others are organizing.


Oakland, CA - Gorgeous Joaquin Miller Park will play host to this
year's Spring Training, a free "Summer Campouts for Dummies" prep
course offered to all investors of False Profit, LLC featuring...

Adam Ohana (Get Freaky) vs Laura (El Circo)
benchun (False Profit) vs Dr. Toast (False Profit)
Alxndr (DownLow, False Profit)
Neptune (Beatchurch)
EPROM (Nexus)
obi-J (False Profit)
Genji (Word of Mouth)

With the summer promising prolonged exposure to the elements and to
wide-ranging frequencies at high volumes, we want our investors to be
prepared.

Like any campout, you will need:

* Food and beverage provisions (to prevent starvation and/or dehydration)
* Sunscreen (to prevent sunburn and/or incineration by solar flares)
* Sunglasses (to prevent retinal damage due to UV rays and/or old age)
* Blankets (to prevent grass stains and/or allergic reactions to the plantlife)

This free offer expires on June 4th.

Remember...practice makes perfect.

www.google.com/maps

and here's photos from last year. :)
www.flickr.com/search/

Here's another option for Saturday....
This is gonna be a really fun night.
Just saw Baby Ford in Detroit last
weekend and he was friggin' amazing!

Hope to see some of you out!

________________________

Saturday, June 2nd, 2007

[  K  O  N  T  R  O  L  ]

TWO YEAR ANNIVERSARY

Two years in, and what better reason to celebrate than the
fact that techno is alive and well in San Francisco!  On this
momentous occasion, we couldn't be more thrilled to present
to you one of the most legendary figures in modern dance
music delivering a soul-shaking *3 HOUR SET*!


BABY FORD  ( Perlon . Trelik . Ifach . Klang Elektronik : UK )


Peter "Baby" Ford is, quite literally, one of the founders of
the UK's acid-house scene.  After experiencing global
success as a club music pioneer in the early 90's, he took
an unexpected turn towards more experimental and
minimalistic sounds.  Rather than becoming a footnote in
dance music history, nearly 20 years later he's still pushing
boundaries; still at the top of his game.

A few of us were fortunate enough to catch his fantastic
set at last weekend's Detroit Electronic Music Festival, and
rest assured...we're all in for an unforgettable night!


with resident DJs and their special guests:

Sammy D + DJ Wrong?
Craig Kuna + Sasha Braverman
Alland Byallo + Kelley B.
Nikola Baytala + Miles Egner


* We are sad to report that due to a family emergency,
Thomas Franzmann (aka Zip) was unable to make it to the
United States at this time.  We look forward to hosting
him on a future occasion and wish him and his family the best!

________________________________________________

The ENDUP
401 6th St @ Harrison, SF
10pm - 6am / 21+ / $15
http://www.theendup.com

FREE until 11pm!

____________________________________________________


Full bios, pics and FREE music:
http://www.kontrolsf.com

[KONTROL] on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/kontrolsf

[ground.KONTROL] on Western Addition Radio:
http://www.westaddradio.com/kontrol/

Flyer front:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K24F.jpg
Flyer back:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K24B.jpg
Poster:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K24P.jpg

____________________________________________________


BABY FORD

Baby Ford aka Peter Ford is one of the most recognizable names in current
dancefloor techno and was one of the founders of the U.K. acid house scene.

He's released records under a slew of pseudonyms, including Casino Classix,
El Mal, Solcyc and his most frequent, Baby Ford. His early work -- heavily
influenced by the late-'80s acid house sound, as well as Chicago producers
such as Marshall Jefferson, Ron Trent, Armando, and Larry Heard -- appeared
primarily through the Rhythm King label, and included classic cuts such as
"Oochy Koochy", "Children of the Revolution", and "Fetish".

Material has also appeared on Sire, Source, and Insumision/Transglobal. He's
released four full-length albums to date, including the debut Fordtrax (a
staple of most techno DJs) and 1997's Headphone Easyrider, one of his more
listener-friendly albums. His recent work has appeared mostly through Trelik
and Ifach, two of the U.K.'s most highly regarded experimental techno
labels, and both of which Ford has a hand in managing (Trelik together with
Eon's Ian Loveday; Ifach with Mark Broom).

He's also collaborating with Thomas Melchior as Soul Capsule and as
Sunpeople they released together the track "Check Your Buddha". With Ian
Loveday he collaborated on a number of projects (including Minimal Man),
both for Trelik. Less active as a remixer, Ford has reconfigured tracks for
Stefan Robbers' Florence project and pop techno group S'Express, among
others.


Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Baby%20Ford

The world of Baby Ford:
http://music.hyperreal.org/bford/

Review of "Sacred Machine" + an interview with Baby Ford:
http://www.themilkfactory.co.uk/music/bford.htm

there's a great day party in oakland on Sunday.

SPRING TRAINING
Sunday, June 3rd
Woodminster Falls @ Joaquin Miller Park, Oakland
Noon-8p
Free

False Profit and Rhythm Society are putting on a day party on Sunday
June 3rd in Joaquin Miller Park which is in the Oakland Hills.
Specifically, in front of the waterfalls and pools near Woodminster
Ampitheater . We did this party last year under the name Springfest,
but will likely have a new name. It's an amazing space and rather
unique. Stephen, Brendan, myself and a few others are organizing.


Oakland, CA - Gorgeous Joaquin Miller Park will play host to this
year's Spring Training, a free "Summer Campouts for Dummies" prep
course offered to all investors of False Profit, LLC featuring...

Adam Ohana (Get Freaky) vs Laura (El Circo)
benchun (False Profit) vs Dr. Toast (False Profit)
Alxndr (DownLow, False Profit)
Neptune (Beatchurch)
EPROM (Nexus)
obi-J (False Profit)
Genji (Word of Mouth)

With the summer promising prolonged exposure to the elements and to
wide-ranging frequencies at high volumes, we want our investors to be
prepared.

Like any campout, you will need:

* Food and beverage provisions (to prevent starvation and/or dehydration)
* Sunscreen (to prevent sunburn and/or incineration by solar flares)
* Sunglasses (to prevent retinal damage due to UV rays and/or old age)
* Blankets (to prevent grass stains and/or allergic reactions to the plantlife)

This free offer expires on June 4th.

Remember...practice makes perfect.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Anything good going on 6/2/07???

"hella young candy kids" have there place, it's a
change of scenary from the sf club scene 

for saturday -
 i think i'm going to end up (yes it's a cliche)
but who can beat minimal all night without having to
change spots into sunrise. 

This sentiment could be because end up is in walking
distance 

and a lot of the philosophy of minimal is that creates
the vibe more so then weather it is "underground or
massive"

real good techno / minimal, to me, transforms the
failures of the promoter. One of the best examples of
this i experienced at fat city when Fumiya Tanaka -
the venue was illing my trip, bad. I was thinking
about leaving beforre Tanaka even started playing, the
rercords shifts of the warm-up djs accidently clanged
a few times, and my over-critical state began just to
hear clanging techno (auditory death).

then Tanaka came on and cleared the dance floor.

many people left - for some reason, I stayed, srangely
interested - after an hour of dissonant noise-ish (idm
without the d) the set became dark and involved - i
was no longer at fat city, i was in the mental
interiors of Tanaka (much respect but the venue isn't
my cup of tea)

that what differentiates a resident dj from a
international dj is that a international dj should be
able to play any where. While a resident develops an
eviroment to it's maximum. i wouldn't say one is
better then the other, just international djs are more
well known. 

peace,

deanizen, mtm

Bedrock is the layer of earth under the milllions of
years of silt built up above it. In some places, the
bedrock has been smashed to the surface and is
actually visible. Some mountain ranges have been
formed when two segments of bedrock collide over
millions of years forcing one up, the other down, or
some combination of either.

I would hardly call a millions year earth movement
progressive.

Subject: [sfraves] Introduced to hyperreal

--0-2028122907-1180859167=:65426
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

I remember when i was a little younger me and one of my older sisters friends were talking about Amp Tv the show that came on like 3 in the morning on mtv. And he started talking about hard trance and happy hardcore. He played some tribal techno tape from the "trance and jungle factory" (as it was once called) and he told me about how raves were these hole in the wall parties were people used methamphetamines. He talked about some dance where you hold and imaginary ball and move it around, it turned out to be what they call liquid today. He braged about how he was cool with some promoters and knew where all the tight underground parties were and yada yada. He said if i was really interested in checking the scene out that i might want to check hyperreal out. So i did and found out about sfraves after that. But the one thing that i remeber most is when he talked about djing. He said that its better to by one turntable and collect records as a hobby instead of trying to play
 at parties. But yea thats my experience so there you have it.

Subject: [sfraves] Introduced to hyperreal


I remember when i was a little younger me and one of my older sisters friends were talking about Amp Tv the show that came on like 3 in the morning on mtv. And he started talking about hard trance and happy hardcore. He played some tribal techno tape from the "trance and jungle factory" (as it was once called) and he told me about how raves were these hole in the wall parties were people used methamphetamines. He talked about some dance where you hold and imaginary ball and move it around, it turned out to be what they call liquid today. He braged about how he was cool with some promoters and knew where all the tight underground parties were and yada yada. He said if i was really interested in checking the scene out that i might want to check hyperreal out. So i did and found out about sfraves after that. But the one thing that i remeber most is when he talked about djing. He said that its better to by one turntable and collect records as a hobby instead of trying to play
at parties. But yea thats my experience so there you have it.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Anything good going on 6/2/07???

Hey I resemble that remark!  

Being a bit older than the list average, personally I always enjoy seeing people even older than me at events.  There's a number of older gentlemen that always go to Sunset parties for example.   And I also enjoy seeing younger people having fun at events too.

I recall one time seeing Mark Farina at Snowdrift...this was a sort of crappy party at a crappy venue filled with dot.com business development and sales types.  Bleh.

For whatever reason a small group of candy kids were there and they were out on the floor smiling and dancing.  This was a lot better than the "table and bottle" crowd that was filling the place so my wife and I gravitated towards them and were dancing with them for a while.  At one point this one big kid seemed very hot and sweaty and my wife got sort of worried about him.  So we bought them a couple of bottles of cold water.  There was no creep factor, there were smiles all around and we danced together for a while longer.  When the party ended the kids saw us in the coat check line and they were like "Hey! There's the people that bought us water! Hi! Thanks!"  Ok, it was a meaningless event in reality, but one full of meaning in the moment somehow.

I really do understand the "creep" thing, but personally I think there is great value in people of all different ages getting together and dancing.  This is something that pretty much every tribe on the planet knows, but which apparently we in the "modern" world seem to have forgotten.  We keep old people and young people apart as if by doing so we can prevent aging from entering our lives.  

Maybe if instead of thinking they are just creepy, if some of the younger folks talked to some of these older people you might find out they aren't cops, they aren't scamming on underage raver chicks, maybe they just like techno or whatever.  I had some recent experiences with this at an underground that made me sort of sad actually. FWIW.  

Of course kids there are actually some creepy and bad people out there both young and old.  Be careful!

Anyway, I say there should be more old dudes and especially more old ladies at parties.  We'll all be there eventually, and there's no reason that old people should have to listen to shitty music or sit at home alone watching American Idol.  Remembering of course that in the rave scene anyone over 25 qualifies as old, aka geriatric, LOL

Regards,

Peter

P.S. See also http://www.babylovesdisco.com

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Critical Mass Bike Ride June 8th; Int'l Day of Action Against
 Climate Change & the G8

Int'l Day of Action/Solidarity with Germany Critical Mass Bike Ride
Against Climate Change & the G8.

A Better World is Possible! A Better US is Necessary! Flood the Streets
before the Sea Does!

5:30 Friday June 8, 2007
Justin Herman Plaza
(foot of Market St./Emarcadero BART)
5:30: Gather and Bike Decorating, 6pm Ride

Use pedal power to challenge oil addiction, to show solidarity with
anti-G8 mass mobilizations in Germany and resist the polluting economic
and political system of the G8. As the megalomaniac G8 leaders meet in
police-state Germany, behind fences, cops and soldiers, intent on
leading us further towards catastrophic and irreversible climate chaos,
we must shout, scream and roar 'no more'. Take action to challenge the
fossil fuelled madness of the G8 governments and their oil addicted
corporate buddies. Actions targeting the root causes of climate change
are planned in other G8 countries and around the world on this day.

We know the terrifying statistics: a million species extinct by 2050, 19
of the 20 hottest years on record since 1980, Greenland and Antarctica
melting, droughts, floods, famines ... the G8 have met for over 30 years
to further a global system that is destroying our planet and our future
while they line their pockets, and at the same time stage fake public
relations promises to confuse us. This global system is at the root of
our ecological and social problems; lack of heath care, housing and
education, war, more prisons, the rich getting richer, low wages and
lousy jobs, pollution, and attacks on immigrant, worker and civil
rights. Meanwhile, island countries disappear and hundreds of thousands
die as a result of the freak weather conditions caused by their
irrational and uncontrollable obsession with never ending economic
growth.

June 8 International Day of Action Against Climate Change and the G8 has
been called by the International Rising Tide Network.
http://risingtide.org.uk/G8

Initiated by Bay Rising; bayrising (at) gmail.com

A Better World is Possible! A Better US is Necessary!
Flood the Streets before the Sea Does!




http://www.jcthedj.com/Support.JC.php

Or we could bludgeon each other with baseball bats...

Or we could shoot each other with guns...

Or we could deploy stealth bombers loaded with precision guided munitions to destroy each other's homes...

Or we could launch nuclear first strikes...

OR, we could do none of the above and actually try to make the world a little bit better place today.  We could try to understand our anger and redirect it towards postive ends in its true nature as discriminating wisdom.

How about riding in CM and not smashing anyone's windshield?  How about driving your car only when you need to, going under the speed limit while carefully avoiding bicylists, and letting the other guy at the intersection go first?  

How about setting aside anger, hate, and fear for just one day?  

I dare you to do it.

Peace,

Peter

No one is selling rave here.   
 
This is not a cult, and it is not a religion.  We are not trying to convert you.
 
This is not an exclusive country club where only a member's referral can get you in. 
 
Do you think its important to anyone besides yourself what "crowd" you do or do not "want to be in"?  
 
What about being in a crowd of one and at the same time being connected to everyone and everything?
 
Chris, to be blunt, everything you've expressed in this email is the opposite of what raving is all about.
 
And if you aren't feeling it, why are you here?  There is no status to be gained here and there are no prizes awarded.
 
Some advice:  be true to yourself and the rest will follow.
 
Peace,
 
Peter

Subject: Re: [sfraves] party reviews?

I found magda to be the real high light of the night.

hawtin spun a pretty amazing set - very much what I
expected from him. He played that record with the
creepy guy trying to give the kid that took too many
pills a back rub ("Yeaaaaa") 3 times and kept remixing
it. He spun some crazy wattery frequencies which made
my ears pop. But he ended at on a real high point (@
about 4am), I felt like i was just getting in to his
set when he finsihed.

Magda really developed her set and came to more of a
natural finsih. Her records choice seemed to draw on
some of the more groove based production and kept a
danceable vibe hightened by her minimal selection, as
aposed to clearly the dance floor. (I had really
wished troy pierce, minus label mate, had played with
them, but I felt Magda represeneted the sound I
commonly associate to him)

Mighty did a nice job at hosting the event - the bass
was a lil muddy and highs a bit intense. However I
really apreciate the energy at mighty of the staff - a
lot of ppl whrere saying how the event should have
happend at mezzanine since the venue is bigger - but
i've always found that venue to be tad bit impersonal.
Which would really hurt the experience of seeing
hawtin since he seems to react so strongly to the vibe
of the event.

ciao,denizen
-m

----- Original Message ----
From: Morgan McCloud <mogopolis2000@yahoo.com>
To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com; Bam <invibe@gmail.com>; SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Monday, June 4, 2007 2:06:15 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] party reviews?


I found magda to be the real high light of the night.

hawtin spun a pretty amazing set - very much what I
expected from him. He played that record with the
creepy guy trying to give the kid that took too many
pills a back rub ("Yeaaaaa") 3 times and kept remixing
it. He spun some crazy wattery frequencies which made
my ears pop. But he ended at on a real high point (@
about 4am), I felt like i was just getting in to his
set when he finsihed.

Magda really developed her set and came to more of a
natural finsih. Her records choice seemed to draw on
some of the more groove based production and kept a
danceable vibe hightened by her minimal selection, as
aposed to clearly the dance floor. (I had really
wished troy pierce, minus label mate, had played with
them, but I felt Magda represeneted the sound I
commonly associate to him)

Mighty did a nice job at hosting the event - the bass
was a lil muddy and highs a bit intense. However I
really apreciate the energy at mighty of the staff - a
lot of ppl whrere saying how the event should have
happend at mezzanine since the venue is bigger - but
i've always found that venue to be tad bit impersonal.
Which would really hurt the experience of seeing
hawtin since he seems to react so strongly to the vibe
of the event.

ciao,denizen
-m

Hawtin blew the place apart.  Mighty did a good job, I thought, the place
was packed and it took a while to get drinks but I honestly didn't care, I
was having too good a time.  I liked Magda's set a lot, it was grooving
enough to keep me dancing but still had a minimal taste and didn't steal any
of Hawtin's thunder.  Hawtin just straight destroyed the place, damn that
man can play when he wants to!

The only thing I would have changed is that I personally would have booked
Hawtin until at least 8am, if not longer, instead of just to 4am.  I can
only imagine the insanity of a night like that...

-Matt

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Had fun

Actually several of us tried to be nice to him and I personally wrote him email off list. However, the truth is that "Chris" wasn't what he pretended to be on this list.  Chris is a troll and most likely a sock puppet for an existing member of the list.  To see why I think that, follow along with CHris' brief history here on sfraves...

In his very first email to the list on May 17th Chris writes "I've been into electronica since the amp tv days.. Im also trying to learn about the latest djs artists and labels.. I like djs like mark farina ltj bukem and paul van dyk.. maybe somebody can tell me about more artists.. I think im a cool guy to talk to so if anyone wants to respond just send me an email.. "

Then five hours later after receiving a warm welcome from Marc(o) he writes "I read the rave faq and they were talking about a new style of a electronica called progressive..  Im interested in checking it out and giving it a chance.. Does anyone on the list know about the genre or have any insite into this style of music? I called skills dj workshop and they said the first place to start is to look up djs like Tiesto, Armin Van Burren, and Paul Van Dyk.. What kind of parties play this kind of style.."

And then the same day he also writes "Whats the difference between prog trance and prog house? Where do djs like sasha, dubfire, and digweed spin at?"

Marc(o), myself, and several others wrote him nice enough notes suggesting progressive artists and parties and explaing the differnce between progressive house and trance.  Chris didn't respond.
 
On May 18th he writes "What makes the rave culture what it is today?"  Which I personally answer at some length incluing a number of links and historical references.  Chris responded to me privately off list saying "So it really began as an outlet for the gay community?"  When I responded to him off list to clarfiy his partial misunderstanding of this point, he didn't answer.

On May 25th Chris writes "Is CoCo still on the list? This is one of her old friends.." 
 
On May 27th Chris writes, "I wonder if the same people that think progressive trance is cheesy think raves are cheesy in general. when i play an assortment of genres the only music that reminds me of that rave vibe is that so called cheesy music. In the right place under the right circumstance that shit goes hard. "

But then on May 30th he states. "Is there really a big difference between massives and ug parties? To all those party goers what has been your experience? I used to think undergrounds were the thing to go to but now im starting to think massives might be a little safer."

So while Chris has never been to a massive and doesn't know whether undergrounds are safe, he knows an old time sfraver CoCo and he knows that "under the right circumstance that shit goes hard."

Then on the 31st he writes "How do you the people on the sfraves list feel about the whole glowstick dancing. For me I really see it as a form of dancing and expressing one self. I know some people associate it with ecstacy and visuals but i see it for more then that. For some its might be hard to dance to these rythms. But with glowsticking its more of a abstract way of dancing to the music."

He's never been to a massive, he's unclear on the safety of undergrounds, but he's an expert on the art of glowsticking?

On June 2nd he writes "Ive found that if your looking for some good progressive bedrock would be a good place to start looking."  But he doesn't know where to get any records apparently.

Will Penna correctly points out, "C'mon, even this newbie, cop, or whatever he is, can Google bedrock + rave ...just SEE what comes up! I did, and wasn't surprised....  "  to which Chris responds, "Im sorry but im really not trying to impress or prove anything to you. I dont even know you and am not really sure if i want to. If you read most of my post im not all that interested in even attending a 'rave'. I forgot about the kinda people that go to raves.. *sigh* No offence to the people with lives."

So he's never even benn to a rave apparently.

Yesterday, less than three weeks after joining the list he asks "I was wondering who on here had iPods?"

And then later the same day writes "What i was going to ask was what do most of you put on your iPods. Not everybody has an iPod. I go to progressive-sounds.com to get most of my artists to put on it. I know there are some die hard ravers but do you like the music enough to listen to it on your iPod everyday?"

So now he not only knows what progressive music is, he knows exactly where to get it?  Right.

And of course finally we have a dramatic exit in the email entitled "Had fun"

Chris = TROLL and he's almost certainly someone already on the list under another name.  

Regards,

Peter

--- dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:

> Actually several of us tried to be nice to him and I
> personally wrote him email off list. However, the truth is
> that "Chris" wasn't what he pretended to be on this list. 
> Chris is a troll and most likely a sock puppet for an
> existing member of the list.  To see why I think that, follow
> along with CHris' brief history here on sfraves...
> 
> In his very first email to the list on May 17th Chris writes
> "I've been into electronica since the amp tv days.. Im also
> trying to learn about the latest djs artists and labels.. I
> like djs like mark farina ltj bukem and paul van dyk.. maybe
> somebody can tell me about more artists.. I think im a cool
> guy to talk to so if anyone wants to respond just send me an
> email.. "
> 
> Then five hours later after receiving a warm welcome from
> Marc(o) he writes "I read the rave faq and they were talking
> about a new style of a electronica called progressive..  Im
> interested in checking it out and giving it a chance.. Does
> anyone on the list know about the genre or have any insite
> into this style of music? I called skills dj workshop and
> they said the first place to start is to look up djs like
> Tiesto, Armin Van Burren, and Paul Van Dyk.. What kind of
> parties play this kind of style.."
> 
> And then the same day he also writes "Whats the difference
> between prog trance and prog house? Where do djs like sasha,
> dubfire, and digweed spin at?"
> 
> Marc(o), myself, and several others wrote him nice enough
> notes suggesting progressive artists and parties and explaing
> the differnce between progressive house and trance.  Chris
> didn't respond.
>  
> On May 18th he writes "What makes the rave culture what it is
> today?"  Which I personally answer at some length incluing a
> number of links and historical references.  Chris responded
> to me privately off list saying "So it really began as an
> outlet for the gay community?"  When I responded to him off
> list to clarfiy his partial misunderstanding of this point,
> he didn't answer.
> 
> On May 25th Chris writes "Is CoCo still on the list? This is
> one of her old friends.." 
>  
> On May 27th Chris writes, "I wonder if the same people that
> think progressive trance is cheesy think raves are cheesy in
> general. when i play an assortment of genres the only music
> that reminds me of that rave vibe is that so called cheesy
> music. In the right place under the right circumstance that
> shit goes hard. "
> 
> But then on May 30th he states. "Is there really a big
> difference between massives and ug parties? To all those
> party goers what has been your experience? I used to think
> undergrounds were the thing to go to but now im starting to
> think massives might be a little safer."
> 
> So while Chris has never been to a massive and doesn't know
> whether undergrounds are safe, he knows an old time sfraver
> CoCo and he knows that "under the right circumstance that
> shit goes hard."
> 
> Then on the 31st he writes "How do you the people on the
> sfraves list feel about the whole glowstick dancing. For me I
> really see it as a form of dancing and expressing one self. I
> know some people associate it with ecstacy and visuals but i
> see it for more then that. For some its might be hard to
> dance to these rythms. But with glowsticking its more of a
> abstract way of dancing to the music."
> 
> He's never been to a massive, he's unclear on the safety of
> undergrounds, but he's an expert on the art of glowsticking?
> 
> On June 2nd he writes "Ive found that if your looking for
> some good progressive bedrock would be a good place to start
> looking."  But he doesn't know where to get any records
> apparently.
> 
> Will Penna correctly points out, "C'mon, even this newbie,
> cop, or whatever he is, can Google bedrock + rave ...just SEE
> what comes up! I did, and wasn't surprised....  "  to which
> Chris responds, "Im sorry but im really not trying to impress
> or prove anything to you. I dont even know you and am not
> really sure if i want to. If you read most of my post im not
> all that interested in even attending a 'rave'. I forgot
> about the kinda people that go to raves.. *sigh* No offence
> to the people with lives."
> 
> So he's never even benn to a rave apparently.
> 
> Yesterday, less than three weeks after joining the list he
> asks "I was wondering who on here had iPods?"
> 
> And then later the same day writes "What i was going to ask
> was what do most of you put on your iPods. Not everybody has
> an iPod. I go to progressive-sounds.com to get most of my
> artists to put on it. I know there are some die hard ravers
> but do you like the music enough to listen to it on your iPod
> everyday?"
> 
> So now he not only knows what progressive music is, he knows
> exactly where to get it?  Right.
> 
> And of course finally we have a dramatic exit in the email
> entitled "Had fun"
> 
> Chris = TROLL and he's almost certainly someone already on
> the list under another name.

Subject: [sfraves] cop paranoia

wtf?

first of all, that's crazy. occam's razor. you don't need cops posing
as idiots on the internet to explain the phenomenon of people
appearing to be idiots on the internet. there is a much simpler
explanation which will get the job done.

second of all, you gotta think big. why imagine cops snooping on SFR
when you can entertain delusions of the CIA bugging your apartment?

"Make no little plans. They have no magic to stir men's blood and
probably themselves will not be realized. Make big plans; aim high in
hope and work, remembering that a noble, logical diagram once recorded
will never die, but long after we are gone will be a living thing,
asserting itself with ever-growing insistency. Remember that our sons
and grandsons are going to do things that would stagger us. Let your
watchword be order and your beacon beauty. Think big."

- Daniel Burnham, Chicago architect. (1864-1912)

btw I am back in the Bay, adding my genetic and cultural uniqueness to
that of a local corporate megadroid's legion of monkey butlers. I wish
I could contribute my daily quota of inspired madness and deranged
verbiage, but I've had to trim my verbiage as it got too fuzzy. maybe
that's too much information. anyway, thought I'd say hi, in a Geri
Dahl kind of way.

by the way, speaking of Geri Dahl, I heard a rumor that she was a sex
worker, and I am in fact desperately in need of sex workers, but I
only want brilliant people who work for their passion, not for money,
so I am only offering equity. if you are a highly qualified "rockstar"
sex worker, or a team of highly qualified "rockstar" sex workers, and
you are interested in working for equity ONLY, please contact
jobs@gilesgoatboy.org. Thank you.

--

http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

       Succumb to the succulent discofunk aura of Abbeloos Olivier, chief party rocker otherwise known as C-MOS, Conga Squad, Cloud 9, Nu-matic, Bio-nic, Dynetic, Warp Factor One .. Olivier accents your all-night exercise with his turntable decknology, piping-hot primetime productions and a sizzling splash of remix duties to keep the booties on the dancefloor for good. Besides being the emphatic owner and principal producer of EPOS and Holographic in Belgium, Mr. Olivier gets the crowd wet with anticipation at several weekly club residencies, including the lively La Rocca (www.larocca.be  ). Having housed your body on Holographic for 10 years strong and rocked your retro dance days as T99 (Anasthasia) and Quadrophonia, his hot and spicy sequences have appeared on mix compilations of Hed Kandi, Ministry of Sound,  He did remixes for Paul Johnson, Baby Bumps, Soulsearcher, Tall Paul and others If the tough and tempting, yet tropical flavors of irresistable discofunk
 fascinates and flocks you to the floor, then stay tuned for upcoming C-Mos, Conga Squad and other sensations.

For more info on Conga Squad, check out:
http://www.holographicmusic.com

JOIN C-MOS, HIGH CALIBER, JENO, ERIC SPIRE, AND OTHER SPECIAL GUESTS @ BACK ON TRACK, SAT. JULY 7th, SAN FRANCISCO. FOR MORE INFO SEE: 

http://www.caligrownevents.com

peace
CKG

--- dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:

> Actually several of us tried to be nice to him and I
> personally wrote him email off list. However, the truth is
> that "Chris" wasn't what he pretended to be on this list. 
> Chris is a troll and most likely a sock puppet for an
> existing member of the list.  To see why I think that, follow
> along with CHris' brief history here on sfraves...
> 
> In his very first email to the list on May 17th Chris writes
> "I've been into electronica since the amp tv days.. Im also
> trying to learn about the latest djs artists and labels.. I
> like djs like mark farina ltj bukem and paul van dyk.. maybe
> somebody can tell me about more artists.. I think im a cool
> guy to talk to so if anyone wants to respond just send me an
> email.. "
> 
> Then five hours later after receiving a warm welcome from
> Marc(o) he writes "I read the rave faq and they were talking
> about a new style of a electronica called progressive..  Im
> interested in checking it out and giving it a chance.. Does
> anyone on the list know about the genre or have any insite
> into this style of music? I called skills dj workshop and
> they said the first place to start is to look up djs like
> Tiesto, Armin Van Burren, and Paul Van Dyk.. What kind of
> parties play this kind of style.."
> 
> And then the same day he also writes "Whats the difference
> between prog trance and prog house? Where do djs like sasha,
> dubfire, and digweed spin at?"
> 
> Marc(o), myself, and several others wrote him nice enough
> notes suggesting progressive artists and parties and explaing
> the differnce between progressive house and trance.  Chris
> didn't respond.
>  
> On May 18th he writes "What makes the rave culture what it is
> today?"  Which I personally answer at some length incluing a
> number of links and historical references.  Chris responded
> to me privately off list saying "So it really began as an
> outlet for the gay community?"  When I responded to him off
> list to clarfiy his partial misunderstanding of this point,
> he didn't answer.
> 
> On May 25th Chris writes "Is CoCo still on the list? This is
> one of her old friends.." 
>  
> On May 27th Chris writes, "I wonder if the same people that
> think progressive trance is cheesy think raves are cheesy in
> general. when i play an assortment of genres the only music
> that reminds me of that rave vibe is that so called cheesy
> music. In the right place under the right circumstance that
> shit goes hard. "
> 
> But then on May 30th he states. "Is there really a big
> difference between massives and ug parties? To all those
> party goers what has been your experience? I used to think
> undergrounds were the thing to go to but now im starting to
> think massives might be a little safer."
> 
> So while Chris has never been to a massive and doesn't know
> whether undergrounds are safe, he knows an old time sfraver
> CoCo and he knows that "under the right circumstance that
> shit goes hard."
> 
> Then on the 31st he writes "How do you the people on the
> sfraves list feel about the whole glowstick dancing. For me I
> really see it as a form of dancing and expressing one self. I
> know some people associate it with ecstacy and visuals but i
> see it for more then that. For some its might be hard to
> dance to these rythms. But with glowsticking its more of a
> abstract way of dancing to the music."
> 
> He's never been to a massive, he's unclear on the safety of
> undergrounds, but he's an expert on the art of glowsticking?
> 
> On June 2nd he writes "Ive found that if your looking for
> some good progressive bedrock would be a good place to start
> looking."  But he doesn't know where to get any records
> apparently.
> 
> Will Penna correctly points out, "C'mon, even this newbie,
> cop, or whatever he is, can Google bedrock + rave ...just SEE
> what comes up! I did, and wasn't surprised....  "  to which
> Chris responds, "Im sorry but im really not trying to impress
> or prove anything to you. I dont even know you and am not
> really sure if i want to. If you read most of my post im not
> all that interested in even attending a 'rave'. I forgot
> about the kinda people that go to raves.. *sigh* No offence
> to the people with lives."
> 
> So he's never even benn to a rave apparently.
> 
> Yesterday, less than three weeks after joining the list he
> asks "I was wondering who on here had iPods?"
> 
> And then later the same day writes "What i was going to ask
> was what do most of you put on your iPods. Not everybody has
> an iPod. I go to progressive-sounds.com to get most of my
> artists to put on it. I know there are some die hard ravers
> but do you like the music enough to listen to it on your iPod
> everyday?"
> 
> So now he not only knows what progressive music is, he knows
> exactly where to get it?  Right.
> 
> And of course finally we have a dramatic exit in the email
> entitled "Had fun"
> 
> Chris = TROLL and he's almost certainly someone already on
> the list under another name.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] cop paranoia

You're right, human idiocy is very easily explained.  It's due to cat parasites:
 http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2006-08/uoc--cpm080206.php
 
 Anyhow...you might still need to worry about who's bugging your phone, so just in case:
http://lauren.vortex.com/archive/000202.html
http://www.pimall.com/nais/countertelco.html
 
Bizzarely my home telephone randomly switched on in speaker phone last night with an open, but silent line.  Hmm...
 
Bullshit aside, I'm actually really interested in this little problem of creating provably safe email distribution lists, secure P2P networks, and so forth using public key encryption and some other related techniques.  I've been futzing around with some ideas for about a year now related to development of so called "trust" relationships between computer systems that I think is relevant here.
 
Imagine you could hand someone a party invitation with a number (or maybe a bar code) on the back.  The number is an encrypted phone number, URL, or "WiFi" map point location.  Only those that have the key can decrypt the location, URL, or phone number and find the party.  Furthermore I can also ensure that only the person I give the invitation to can decrypt it, and I can trace compromised invitations back to their distributers and authorized holders.   Perhaps this would all be accomplished via some software downloaded onto your computer, phone or PDA instead of with physical invitations.
 
If you are a math, software, or crypto type, consider these papers to get an idea of some of what I am thinking about:  
 
http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/balfanz03secret.html
http://citeseer.ist.psu.edu/balfanz02talking.html
http://paginas.terra.com.br/informatica/paulobarreto/pblounge.html#Introduction
 
Some of this gets pretty deep and is beyond my personal expertise FWIW.  
 
And of course this is all purely an academic exercise...
 
Peace,
 
Peter

asserting itself with ever-growing insistency. Remember that our sons
and grandsons are going to do things that would stagger us. Let your
watchword be order and your beacon beauty. Think big."

On Thu, 7 Jun 2007 tsheets@saturn5.com wrote:
-&e->I like psytrance... but not so sure about psytrancers.

"She thinks she's a godess
she says she talks to the spirits.
I wonder if she can talk to herself
if she can barely hear it."
 - sonic youth (eric's trip)

I've always been amazed by the smug attitude of many psytrancers, a 
combination of claimed increased awareness and this air of "I've been 
there, you're not wearing any bright colors so I'll guess you haven't", in 
many cases an almost spiritual superiority complex.

Which if you think about it, if you're annoying to spirits here in the 
simple to connect material world, the ones you're connecting with 
otherwise are probably fuckheads too.  Extra bonus points for the folks 
I'd see walking around in full on psy-warrior regalia, holding a book 
about Hinduism, shirt with Ganesh on it, saying "boom shankar" regularly 
before every toke and holding up the pipe to their foreheads after they 
hit it, totally incapable of discussing even the most basic tenets of the 
faith.  Seems weird to me, if I went out proudly wearing a Cthulu codpiece 
and yelled "fnord" everytime I lit a cigarette, I'd expect and prepare for 
questions, ya know?

But yeah, I've had a disconnect with a lot of the local techno scene here 
in a similar way.  I've had out of town producers recognize me, go way 
back with a lot of the people who put SF on the map and all that, but some 
local club regulars seem to give me dirty looks when I show up to a club 
alone cause I'm outside the current clique or whatever.

Fortunately I'm conceited enough to see it as their loss.  :)

You could also see it like those old enough to be grandparents folks 
wearing Dokken shirts, the boys with their mullets and the girls with 
their feathered hair, calling each others posers.  You can love the music 
and not fall for the retarded social machines that people build around it.

Even if it is Dokken.
andyw

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

On 7 June 2007, AndyW wrote:

>
> On Thu, 7 Jun 2007 tsheets@saturn5.com wrote:
> -&e->I like psytrance... but not so sure about psytrancers.
>
> "She thinks she's a godess
> she says she talks to the spirits.
> I wonder if she can talk to herself
> if she can barely hear it."
> - sonic youth (eric's trip)
>
> I've always been amazed by the smug attitude of many psytrancers, a
> combination of claimed increased awareness and this air of "I've been
> there, you're not wearing any bright colors so I'll guess you haven't", in
> many cases an almost spiritual superiority complex.
>
> Which if you think about it, if you're annoying to spirits here in the
> simple to connect material world, the ones you're connecting with
> otherwise are probably fuckheads too.  Extra bonus points for the folks
> I'd see walking around in full on psy-warrior regalia, holding a book
> about Hinduism, shirt with Ganesh on it, saying "boom shankar" regularly
> before every toke and holding up the pipe to their foreheads after they
> hit it, totally incapable of discussing even the most basic tenets of the
> faith.  Seems weird to me, if I went out proudly wearing a Cthulu codpiece
> and yelled "fnord" everytime I lit a cigarette, I'd expect and prepare for
> questions, ya know?
>
> But yeah, I've had a disconnect with a lot of the local techno scene here
> in a similar way.  I've had out of town producers recognize me, go way
> back with a lot of the people who put SF on the map and all that, but some
> local club regulars seem to give me dirty looks when I show up to a club
> alone cause I'm outside the current clique or whatever.
>
> Fortunately I'm conceited enough to see it as their loss.  :)
>
> You could also see it like those old enough to be grandparents folks
> wearing Dokken shirts, the boys with their mullets and the girls with
> their feathered hair, calling each others posers.  You can love the music
> and not fall for the retarded social machines that people build around it.
>
> Even if it is Dokken.
> andyw
>

Ok Bam (and others who actually "go out"), riddle me this:

I have a first official "date" tomorrow (no, I don't know how it happened 
either, she's beautiful, smart, funny, keep waiting for the other shoe to 
drop but hey, whatever, if I'm me and she likes me maybe a cottage in the 
Hamptons isn't too far off.  Or maybe driving our 11 kids to the Grand 
Canyon on summer break... but before I get ahead of myself...).

 * if I had culture, where would I take her?
 * should I wear my codpiece?
 * any recommendations on tasty veggie eats for a friday night in the east 
bay or sf area?
 * is there such a thing as a good date movie out right now that won't 
make me leave hating hollywood and cheesy endings?  somewhere between 
"happily ever after" and a film noir "everybody lives except the selfless 
forgotten who fought the hardest to save them and dies still unnoticed" 
would be swell.  Also, FF Rise of the Silver Surfer isn't out yet, and I 
don't trust myself to not go apeshit when they get the whole Norrin 
Radd/Galactus shit wrong (which I'm pretty sure they'll have to, it's an 
awful lot of backstory but essential to the SS character and why earth was 
spared).  "Knocked Up" seems like a bad start.  Ocean's will be a zoo 
opening night.  Mr. Brooks might be a touch too much.  Spiderman 3 has 
sucked by most accounts so far.  I want to see Paprika just cause it looks 
so good and have recently gotten totally into Paranoia Agent, but anime is 
like, dork city.  Like um yeah, I'm *snort* a programmer who likes anime 
and electronic music *snort*... HOW UNIQUE IS THAT MUTHAFUKKAZ?

In any case, maybe I'll just come up with some ideas and work it out with 
her.  But suggestions outside what my semi-functional and utterly 
"game"less brain might come up with would be much appreciated.  Any 
suggestion better than "show up at her house covered in sweat with a 
backpack full of lube, condoms and grilled cheese sandwiches" will be 
considered.

fnord!
andyw

Dude - just be yourself and work with what you've got. I think too many 
people put their "best face on" on a date, and don't really represent their 
true self (complete with wacky idiosynchrasies, etc.)

Don't go out of your way to impress - just make sure the young lady is comfy 
as hell, and make sure that wherever you go you can conversate. It's hard ot 
learn about someone at a movie theater, other than what sort of habits they 
have when at the movies.

possible. I still have sharp teeth and (as previously mentioned) cows create 
the majority of global warming, so it's a moral imperative to help the 
environment by eating as many cows as you can.

On Thu, 7 Jun 2007, Van Mundegaarde wrote:
-&e->Dude - just be yourself and work with what you've got. I think too many
-&e->people put their "best face on" on a date, and don't really represent their
-&e->true self (complete with wacky idiosynchrasies, etc.)

I'm pretty sure I don't have trouble being authentic, but there is the 
matter of picking the feathers you fan your tail with.  For example, one 
of the things I've realized I really want to do someday is go primitive 
hunting (spear or bow), because eating meat and not being able to deal 
with killing an animal seem at odds to me.  But... not an ideal first 
date.

-&e->Don't go out of your way to impress - just make sure the young lady is
-&e->comfy as hell, and make sure that wherever you go you can conversate. It's
-&e->hard ot learn about someone at a movie theater, other than what sort of
-&e->habits they have when at the movies.

I love the word "conversate".

I've been assured it's not real:
http://www.wsu.edu/~brians/errors/conversate.html
http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=conversate

But it's neato and I actually like it when used casually (as you did).  I 
think it actually might have stemmed from a PIL song ("Careering" off 
their second album aka second edition aka metalbox) in the form 
"Conversating".

Which is funny, cause a few weeks ago I wrote a song that had the lyric 
"Conversate, while our food prepares", which someone told me reminded them 
of a Rapture song called "Echoes" which uses the word "Conversating".  I 
finally get around to listening to that song, and sure enough, it's almost 
a perfect rip of part of PIL's Careering.  But anyways...

-&e->HAVE FUN ON YOUR DATE!

Yeah, that's the point of the question.  Can't help who I am but maybe we 
could be in some pleasant surroundings reduce the shock a bit ;)

andyw

p.s.	if anybody wants to hear the song I wrote that I mentioned above 
it's the "autoplay" pick at http://myspace.com/thelagsf

p.p.s.	i really have to go start a blog.  the slightly baked + unemployed 
+ red bull + no warcraft thing is resulting in writing a lot.

On Thu, 7 Jun 2007, Chris wrote:
-&e->I would really recomend a drum and bass group call e-z rollers for those that like that softer jazzy sound.

One and Only - by PFM

This is the track I have no defense against.  Just insanely 
chill-o-sex-o-matic.  Perhaps crude and repetitive by modern standards, 
still sends chills up my spine when it gets to that part of Logical 
Progression... which is strangely one of the oldest mixes/comps that has 
seldom been skipped from rotation in my work-time listening.

And um, yeah.  PFM, LTJ Bukem, Lamb, all that shibby is freaking gold 
every so often.  Used to do a weekly where it was all trip hop, ambient 
and dolphin jungle called slow roasted in santa clara.

And then there's the time I sprayed food all over my keyboard at work in 
a related inceident, from a simple captioned photo of LTJ Bukem & Conrad:

http://ishkur.com/captions/111.jpg

----- Original Message ----
From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>

Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Thursday, June 7, 2007 3:30:57 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] psytrancers [NRR]


On Thu, 7 Jun 2007, Van Mundegaarde wrote:
-&e->Dude - just be yourself and work with what you've got. I think too many
-&e->people put their "best face on" on a date, and don't really represent their
-&e->true self (complete with wacky idiosynchrasies, etc.)

I'm pretty sure I don't have trouble being authentic, but there is the 
matter of picking the feathers you fan your tail with.  For example, one 
of the things I've realized I really want to do someday is go primitive 
hunting (spear or bow), because eating meat and not being able to deal 
with killing an animal seem at odds to me.  But... not an ideal first 
date.

-&e->Don't go out of your way to impress - just make sure the young lady is
-&e->comfy as hell, and make sure that wherever you go you can conversate. It's
-&e->hard ot learn about someone at a movie theater, other than what sort of
-&e->habits they have when at the movies.

I love the word "conversate".

I've been assured it's not real:
http://www.wsu.edu/~brians/errors/conversate.html
http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=conversate

But it's neato and I actually like it when used casually (as you did).  I 
think it actually might have stemmed from a PIL song ("Careering" off 
their second album aka second edition aka metalbox) in the form 
"Conversating".

Which is funny, cause a few weeks ago I wrote a song that had the lyric 
"Conversate, while our food prepares", which someone told me reminded them 
of a Rapture song called "Echoes" which uses the word "Conversating".  I 
finally get around to listening to that song, and sure enough, it's almost 
a perfect rip of part of PIL's Careering.  But anyways...

-&e->HAVE FUN ON YOUR DATE!

Yeah, that's the point of the question.  Can't help who I am but maybe we 
could be in some pleasant surroundings reduce the shock a bit ;)

andyw

p.s.    if anybody wants to hear the song I wrote that I mentioned above 
it's the "autoplay" pick at http://myspace.com/thelagsf

p.p.s.    i really have to go start a blog.  the slightly baked + unemployed 
+ red bull + no warcraft thing is resulting in writing a lot.

STIMULUS at the Duplex w/ Brian Seed and a shit-ton of bitchin' locals!!!!

Friday, 6/8: STIMULUS: Excursions into Electrotech, feat. Brian Seed

Is it possible for the excesses of addiction to lend themselves to a 
positive and uplifting overstimulation of mind and body? If our past 
experiences with our own freaky electro-techy-housish musical addiction are 
any indication, the answer is a resounding, "hell mutha-fuckin'-YEAH!"

So once again, we're venturing on an excursion into electrotech, this time 
bringing one of our favorite purveyors of the sound - Brian Seed - up from 
LA to join a prime selection of local heroes, to present to you a night of 
relentless electrotech madness.

STIMULUS: Excursions into Electrotech

Featuring (in alphabetical order):

Brian Seed aka DJ Brian (Moontribe / Ritual Sounds - LA)
A Moontribe resident since '95, Brian Seed has cultured a globe-spanning 
following by spinning genre-defying sets, blending the sounds of breaks, 
acid house, trance, tribal, and progressive, exemplified by his legendary 
"Hardesertrance" releases. Currently, his sets consist of mainly his own 
material, much of which has been released on Fade, Virgin, Pacific Front, 
Desert Trax, Interscope, System, Moonshine, Six Degrees, Ball of Waxx, and 
his own label, Ritual Sounds.

...plus an all-star local lineup, including:

Dirt (Cymbalic / Omniscient Records - SF)
Evinrude (Stimulus / Space Cowboys / NetAmp - SF)
Little John (Raindance / Nexus - Santa Cruz)
Mozaic (Stimulus / Raindance / Nexus / 3WS - SF)
Satsi (Ammo - SF)

Friday, June 8th, 2007
10pm - 4am
Le Duplex, 1525 Mission St., SF
$5 all night; 21+
Call 1-888-650-6660 for more info!

Not too many events there anymore...

I've never had any problems at 550, but I know other people have.   I would advise strongly against leaving anything of any value in your car in that area.

My two biggest complaints about Barneveld are first that the main room gets too hot sometimes.  The manager there a ways back told me that this was a known problem if they didn't start cooling the space early enough in the day.  Second complaint:  there's very annoying crosstalk between the rooms in the one hallway near coat check.  Very irritating/painful sometimes!

Peace,

Peter

and the Temporary Autonomous Zone. Orbital, and before Orbital,
orbital raves. The Criminal Justice Act. The Summer of Love.

Fast forward to 2007, WMC, corporate superclubs in London, Paul
Fucking Oakenbeast.

Does that timeline make any sense?

The only way it even seems POSSIBLE is if you factor in Burning Man.

WMC = raving morphs into corporate superclubs.

Burning Man = the temporary autonomous zone morphs into a temporary
autonomous metroplex, with its own temporary autonomous economy,
temporary autonomous buildings, temporary autonomous neighborhoods,
temporary autonomous infrastructure, temporary autonomous rhythms, and
temporary autonomous DMV.

Without Burning Man, the story that begins with Chicago house and ends
with Oakenmonkey is a story of doom, corporate power, and failed
ideals. With Burning Man, it's so much simpler. It got big, and it
split in half. The inevitability of cellular osmosis, with the clear
philosophical division of ying and yang.

The Winter Music Conference only really seems cool when you remember
that there's also a Summer Chaos Festival.

And that means that the endless parties before and after Burning Man
are as sensible and obvious as the endless functioning of the music
industry before and after WMC. (The annual events are just
punctuation.)

-- 
Giles Soundwave = Giles Goat Boy
http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

> ----- Original Message ----
> From: Giles Soundwave <dj.soundwave@gmail.com>
> To: SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
> Sent: Sunday, June 10, 2007 10:49:04 PM
> Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?
>
>
>> There, I managed to post on the thread without mentioning how fucking
>> retarded half a year of pre and post burningman events are.
>
> Oh, come on, it makes perfect sense.
>
> Think back to the late 80s. The Shamen, Terrence McKenna, Hakim Bey
> and the Temporary Autonomous Zone. Orbital, and before Orbital,
> orbital raves. The Criminal Justice Act. The Summer of Love.
>
> Fast forward to 2007, WMC, corporate superclubs in London, Paul
> Fucking Oakenbeast.
>
> Does that timeline make any sense?
>
> The only way it even seems POSSIBLE is if you factor in Burning Man.
>
> WMC = raving morphs into corporate superclubs.
>
> Burning Man = the temporary autonomous zone morphs into a temporary
> autonomous metroplex, with its own temporary autonomous economy,
> temporary autonomous buildings, temporary autonomous neighborhoods,
> temporary autonomous infrastructure, temporary autonomous rhythms, and
> temporary autonomous DMV.
>
> Without Burning Man, the story that begins with Chicago house and ends
> with Oakenmonkey is a story of doom, corporate power, and failed
> ideals. With Burning Man, it's so much simpler. It got big, and it
> split in half. The inevitability of cellular osmosis, with the clear
> philosophical division of ying and yang.
>
> The Winter Music Conference only really seems cool when you remember
> that there's also a Summer Chaos Festival.
>
> And that means that the endless parties before and after Burning Man
> are as sensible and obvious as the endless functioning of the music
> industry before and after WMC. (The annual events are just
> punctuation.)
>
> -- 
> Giles Soundwave = Giles Goat Boy
> http://www.gilesgoatboy.org/

From: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
To: "Philip.X.Diaz" <st_indigo@earthlink.net>, SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ascii
Message-ID: <922203.82346.qm@web32407.mail.mud.yahoo.com>
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?

Well naturally there are good parties at Burning Man.  And there is amazing art and even the occasional miraculous happening.
 
At the same time, Burning Man is run by a corporation that benefits from controlling the brand "Burning Man" and other trademarks and properties it owns.  The corporation can and has sued people.  (http://archives.cnn.com/2002/LAW/08/26/ctv.burning.man/)  The corporation controls the event and receives all of the revenue from the sales of tickets and it sets the rules about what other entities can benefit from these properties and revenue streams. (http://www.burningman.com/press/pressRandR.html)

The counter culture goes through these cycles where "authenticity" is created through new intellectual and culturla movements (i.e. rave culture) and then subsequently exploited for commercial gain (Mitsubishi commercials).  In a way, authenticity is the currency of the counter culture.  So the question arises, is Buring Man authentic?  Or is it simply a crass commercialization of what once was authentic?
 
Never has the relationship between "authentic" counter culture and commercial entities exploiting counter cultural memes been more complex.  Think about Apple's iPod commercials.   Are they authentic?  Lots of people seem to be influenced by the appearance of "cool" at least.

To me the interesting bit here is that Burning Man is both an authentic counter cultural event AND a commercialized imitation of that same event; and it is somehow both of these at the same time.
 
See also: 
 
Thomas Frank's The Conquest of Cool http://www.tcfrank.com/conquest.html
http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1252/is_n4_v125/ai_20492654
 
Nation of Rebels http://blogcritics.org/archives/2005/06/20/130535.php
 
Counter Culture http://user.well.com/iengaged.cgi?c=inkwell.vue&f=0&t=233&q=0-
http://www.amazon.com/Counterculture-Through-Ages-Abraham-House/dp/0375507582

Peace,

Peter

> autonomous metroplex, with its own temporary autonomous economy,
> temporary autonomous buildings, temporary autonomous neighborhoods,
> temporary autonomous infrastructure, temporary autonomous rhythms, and
> temporary autonomous DMV.
>

> with Oakenmonkey is a story of doom, corporate power, and failed
> ideals. With Burning Man, it's so much simpler. It got big, and it
> split in half. The inevitability of cellular osmosis, with the clear
> philosophical division of ying and yang.

> that there's also a Summer Chaos Festival.
>

> punctuation.)

So at what point did Burning Man say they were not about making money?
=20
At the actual event they discourage commerce. There is mass debate around t=
he sale of coffee and lemonade in center camp. Center camp profits though a=
re donated to area schools.=20
=20
The thing many people cannot see past is the reason for no commerce at the =
event. These people get hung up on no commerce and scream murder when the B=
urning Man Organization makes money. No commerce is intended to help foster=
 relationships without the use of monetary transactions. This is not part o=
f a business plan but a community plan.=20
=20
Burning Man has yet to allow sponsors or outside advertising. The Burning M=
an Organization protects their logos and name as much as any company might.=
 As you could imagine there are many people who use the logo illegally to t=
ry and sell items.=20
=20
If you are going to attack Burning Man look at the pseudo religious culture=
 developing and the desecration of eastern religions. These groups are the =
same people that live in your city and mine. Then attack the fact that more=
 and more people expect the Burning Man Organization to do more for them wh=
en the event is based on self reliance. The problem isn't the business, the=
 problem is the people reading into it and trying to find flaw instead of h=
aving fun.=20
=20
Spend your money at Burning Man or elsewhere but the fact is you are still =
spending money. It is a wicked world and until we decide to make change we'=
ll just continue to be the people that scream and shout about problems with=
out action to solve them.=20

I love the diachotomy of the entity acting as both agent and body for 
experience.  It is subject object dualism as all things manifesting are.  To 
be part of something and yet be uniquely defined, to contibute something 
meaningful, or otherwise, to the experience that is Burningman is what it is 
all about.  It only works if you go.  It only matters if your a part of it.  
Art happening is as relevant today as it was in the 60s and performance art 
is what Burningman is about.  Long Burn the Man!
SFR: Ranger

art and even the occasional miraculous happening.

At the same time, Burning Man is run by a corporation that benefits from 
controlling the brand "Burning Man" and other trademarks and properties it

and it sets the rules about what other entities can benefit from these 
properties and revenue streams. 
(http://www.burningman.com/press/pressRandR.html)

and then subsequently exploited for commercial gain (Mitsubishi 
commercials).  In a way, authenticity is the currency of the counter

a crass commercialization of what once was authentic?

the death of the 'Summer of Love'. Essentially, the tale of how a
bunch of stoned-ass idealists got eaten up by predatory tweakers. I'm

culture, or any other bunch of drugged out dreamers who talk about
peace and love too loudly.

MIME-Version: 1.0

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?

Hey I'm not anti-Burning Man at all, I'm merely pointing out that the apparent dichotomy between BM as an "authentic" counter culture event versus the commercialized Winter Music Conference might not be as simple as was implied.  Burning Man is viewed as authentic (at least by some of its particpants) while still being commercialized in a limited way.  In contrast WMC is viewed as over commericalized and in-authentic.  

In fact if one looks at the history of the counter culture since the sixties, it has become increasingly difficult to find trully authentic non-commercialized cultures and events.  New cultural developments are immediately captured, commercialized, and used to market products whenever possible.  the time from cultural innovation to TV commercial soundtrack is now measured in weeks rather than months.

It used to be that people thought that rock music was "authentic"; and I recall in the late seventies that many thought of disco as being "manufactured" or fake in contrast.  Then rock became "classic rock" and it was viewed as phoney and commercial.  In the nineties it was the alternative/indie rock scene that was "authentic" while classic rock was fake corporate crap.  

But of course the alternative label itself was manufactured by a commercial entity, and lets not forget "grunge", so one can see that the whole thing is in the end a house of cards.  The dichotomy of commerical vs. authentic is false.  As both Burning Man and raves point out in fact the very nature of authenticity is itself in question once some cultural artifact or concept is separated from the moment of immediate experience as "media" that can be packaged, branded, and sold.  That's why these events can't be commercialized in some sense.

In the end, Burning Man becomes a coffee table book even if that book can't ever capture any aspect of the "real" experience. .(http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/blogs/sfgate/detail?blogid=3&entry_id=9021)  Rave music is used to sell cars and clothes, but that doesn't mean that raving is merely a commercial fashion trend.  Or does it?

See also Andy Warhol:  http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2006/01/24/bawarhol24.xml&sSheet=/arts/2006/01/25/ixartright.html

Peace,

Peter 


----- Original Message ----
From: Jason Philips <djjasonphilips@hotmail.com>
To: SFR <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Tuesday, June 12, 2007 9:57:48 AM
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?


So at what point did Burning Man say they were not about making money?

At the actual event they discourage commerce. There is mass debate around the sale of coffee and lemonade in center camp. Center camp profits though are donated to area schools. 

The thing many people cannot see past is the reason for no commerce at the event. These people get hung up on no commerce and scream murder when the Burning Man Organization makes money. No commerce is intended to help foster relationships without the use of monetary transactions. This is not part of a business plan but a community plan. 

Burning Man has yet to allow sponsors or outside advertising. The Burning Man Organization protects their logos and name as much as any company might. As you could imagine there are many people who use the logo illegally to try and sell items. 

If you are going to attack Burning Man look at the pseudo religious culture developing and the desecration of eastern religions. These groups are the same people that live in your city and mine. Then attack the fact that more and more people expect the Burning Man Organization to do more for them when the event is based on self reliance. The problem isn't the business, the problem is the people reading into it and trying to find flaw instead of having fun. 

Spend your money at Burning Man or elsewhere but the fact is you are still spending money. It is a wicked world and until we decide to make change we'll just continue to be the people that scream and shout about problems without action to solve them.

Honestly, your best bet is to hire a catering company.
Negotiate the liquor rates. They provide bartenders
and a MOBILE liquor license. The city will never grant
a one-time permit, regardless of the whether their is
an allowance for it in the law.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Single Event Liquor License?

Yeah... have done... and been involved with many OTHER
events that have done the same... Dating back to 1993.

If you are having an EVENT, you will have to
accomodate so many things from security to parking to
police in order to get a ONE-TIME LIQUOR permit...
there will be little chance you will break even let
alone make money for a fundraiser...

A catering company has a PORTABLE license. You will
make monmey off the bar if you plan correctly.

But hey... I was trying to help a brother out... Chase
your tail all you want.

E

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?

Hah... this thread reminds me of an old article jwz wrote about  
Burning Man, their brand, and the sheer hypocrisy of the corporation  
behind the event:

http://www.jwz.org/gruntle/burningman.html

What bothers me even more than the hypocrisy alone, is that they mix  
it with a good dose off elitism for good measure...  Like going to a  
week-long party in the desert (Oh, I'm sorry.  I should say "on the  
playa" or "at Black Rock City.") makes them sooo special and sooo  
much better than me and how I (Who prefers my partying and drug use  
in nice 6-10-hour chunks followed by a shower, clean clothes, and a  
good day's sleep in my own bed, thankyouverymuch.) am just totally  
incapable of ever understanding what it's like to be a "burner".

I know not everyone who goes is like that.  I've got a some very good  
friends who go every year.  But as the years go on, and they go and I  
don't, even from some of them I start to catch twinges of a "BM's not  
for you." or "You just don't understand." attitude.

One year or another, I'll probably get around to going... if only to  
see just what the big F-ing deal is.  It'll shock the living hell out  
of everyone who knows just how much I hate sunlight, being hot, and  
being dirty.  But I just can't shake the notion that it's something I  
should do at least *once* in my life.  And when you come right down  
to it, a little hypocrisy on the part of the BM corporation is small  
potatoes compared to the outright evil of corporations like  
microsoft, walmart, halliburton, texaco, enron, and their ilk.  But  
the elitist flack I've caught from "burners" when they've found out  
that I'm not part of their club doesn't exactly acquit the event in  
my mind.  I wonder if I would be made to feel as welcome, as a late- 
coming newbie were I to actually go to BM, as I was when I started  
going to raves?


cya,
john

> ready to happen, lol.
