lad I didn't write that because you'd just think I scarfed it from your fri=
end's rant.=0A=0AThe restrictions on activities at Disneyland and BM are qu=
ite similar actually.  Both prohibit commercial photography and both prohib=
it the sale of goods inside the park/event boundaries for example.  Weapons=
 are prohibited at both places.  Remember when people used to shoot up cars=
 and blow things up at Burning Man as art?  I do, it was 1995...  (http://w=
ww.weirdamerica.com/2007/05/20/weird-america-car-hunt/)=0A=0AA theme park i=
s not a revolution, even if it is fun to visit or a good place to take drug=
s.  =0A=0AHakim Bey (aka Peter Lamborn Wilson) on Burning Man:=0A=0A"I=A2ve=
 never been to Burning Man, but that=A2s just accidental, because I=A2ve gi=
ven up travel. As far as I can tell it=A2s a lovely thing. I call those thi=
ngs 'periodic autonomous zones.' The thing about the TAZ is I didn=A2t inve=
nt it, I just gave it a name. I think it=A2s a sociological reality that gr=
oups of people will come together to maximize some concept of freedom that =
they share as naturally as breathing. When all the potential for the emerge=
nce for a TAZ is maximized, either because you=A2ve helped to maximize it o=
r because your local situation has arrived at a certain point where it beco=
mes possible, you=A2ll do it. Like I=A2ve said before, a TAZ is anywhere fr=
om two to several thousand people, who for as little as two or three hours =
or for as much as a couple of years manage to keep that mood going. And it=
=A2s incredibly vital. It=A2s vital that every human being should have some=
 such experience, or else they=A2ll never know that another world is possib=
le. So Burning Man is a kind of
 periodic autonomous zone."=0A=0AHe continues, "As soon as the first hint o=
f commercialization or tiredness appears, then I would think the best thing=
 to do is to close it down. Move on, reappear somewhere else. And ultimatel=
y, I do believe that another world is possible and that permanent changes c=
ould be made. But that=A2s different. That=A2s a revolution."=0A=0Ahttp://w=
ww.thebrooklynrail.org/spotlight/july04/wilson.html=0A=0AOf course only the=
 people involved will know when "first hint of commercialization or tiredne=
ss appears" and this might be a matter of opinion or debate.  =0A=0AFrom th=
is one outsider's point of view it happened a few years ago.=0A=0APeace,=0A=

Subject: [sfraves] Ibiza in Shambles?  Authorities Close Amnesia, DC10 and Bora Bora Clubs

Diario de Ibiza, the news agency for the hottest Summer dance music location on the planet, recently reported that government officials have ordered the clubs Amnesia, DC10 and Bora Bora to shut down. Effective immediately, DC 10 will be shut down for two months, Amnesia and Bora Bora for one month each. 

A case has been brewing against these clubs related to the sale and use of illegal narcotics during the 2005 and 2006 seasons. The government has admitted that there is no legal precedent for closing clubs, but has proposed that drugs cause a safety hazard and hurt Ibiza's overall tourism industry. The government states that 450 people were arrested in possession of drugs during this year's opening weekend with one hospital handling 11 drug overdose cases. 

...

Bassdrop
Thursday, June 14th, 2007
@ Shine (1337 Mission st)
9pm-2am
FREE!!!
21+

It's our 3rd Bassdrop and once again we've got another WICKED UK
headliner. You really don't want to sleep on this one, cause it's goin
to be a bangin night.


Stabilizer
(Plastic Raygun/Boombox/Functional Breaks/Lithium Music)

As a producer Stabilizer has earned many supporters in the breaks
fraternity and beyond. A series of singles and remixes over the past
three years, on labels such as Boombox Records, Kosmo and Functional
Breaks, have gained the support of Andy Weatherall, Boy George, Annie
Nightingale (Radio 1), Hybrid, Krafty Kuts, Scanty Sandwich,
Scissorkicks, Anthony Pappa and Caspar Kedros (Headrillaz) among
others.

Stabilizer is now signed to the mighty Plastic Raygun and the first
single release, What It Takes rose to Number 5 in the DJ Mag breaks
chart as well as being described as "A Classic" by none other than
Andy Weatherall.

As well as the production, Stabilizer can be found despoiling the
world=D5s ears in a breakbeat and punky house fashion in places as
diverse as Bath, Bognor and Berlin, with a US tour planned.

Armed with a bag of records and a sampler - with an emphasis firmly on
good tunes and a good time - the Stabilizer DJ style is tight, varied
and always full of energy. With genres ranging from Hip Hip and Funk
via punky house all the way to the freshest nu-school breaks cuts.
Only two rules... it's got to be good, and it's got to be funky.


Along with:
DJ Unagi (Word of Mouth) - Special birthday set
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
Athena (Evil Breaks)

more info on this & other events: www.EvilBreaks.com

Subject: [sfraves] The Singularity Approacheth....

--------------050007030000000707090103
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

    "Is It Live, Or Is It Memorex?"

    "Skynet begins to learn at a geometric rate. It becomes self-aware
    at 2:14 a.m. Eastern time, August 29th. In a panic, they try to pull
    the plug. "

For the last several years it has been a running gag between me and 
those that know me that it's getting harder and harder to tell the 
difference between what we know as "Reality" and what passes for the 
fine reportage from "America's Finest News Source," otherwise known as 
"The Onion".


    Nation Hoping For A Windy Flag Day

    June 5, 2007 | Issue 43â€¢23

    WASHINGTON, DCâ€”With June 14 just a week away, citizens nationwide
    are hoping that brisk, windy weather is in store for this Flag Day.

    "A Flag Day without wind is like a Columbus Day with mail delivery:
    It just doesn't feel right," said Coast Guard Rear Adm. Roger
    Jessup, who is serving as this year's Flag Day grand marshal. "I
    long for the Flag Days of my youth, when the winds were always
    strong and steady. Seems like in the past few years there's barely
    been a breeze and Old Glory just droops. Except for Flag Day '02,
    when it was so blustery the flag whipped right around the flagpole."

    Jessup, whose duties include answering Flag Day mail from the
    nation's children, added that if everyone tried as hard as they
    could to be good this week, "perhaps Starry Stripes, the Flag Day
    Fairy, will blow some nice breezy air our way."

Well, I'm here to tell you that today, June 14th, 2007, at exactly 5am, 
EST, the Flag Day commemoration here in the United States Of America, 
The Weather Channel led with an item about the effects that gusty winds 
will have today.

I don't know any other way to put this....

We're seriously  in big fucking trouble.


--------------050007030000000707090103--

raves is the same reason the elites want to do away with the middle  
class and have one world corporation that everyone just works for -  
it's a threat to them.  Raves, dancing, with or without the drugs,

less about going to a party that's not "permitted" who cares about  
that shit, you're just paying someone off.  Americans of 1776 would  
have had nothing of this.

>From: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
>To: John B <SvnLyrBrto@yahoo.com>,  Van Mundegaarde 
><electrofunk138@hotmail.com>
>CC: dj.soundwave@gmail.com, sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?
>Date: Wed, 13 Jun 2007 07:36:41 -0700 (PDT)
>Now that's funny, because I was just about to sit down to write something 
>in which I was going to link Disneyland (where I was this past Christmas) 
>with Burning Man.  Specifically, I was going to point out the similarity 
>and differences between the Disneyland and BM safety and photo policies.  
>I'm glad I didn't write that because you'd just think I scarfed it from 
>your friend's rant.
>
>The restrictions on activities at Disneyland and BM are quite similar 
>actually.  Both prohibit commercial photography and both prohibit the sale 
>of goods inside the park/event boundaries for example.  Weapons are 
>prohibited at both places.  Remember when people used to shoot up cars and 
>blow things up at Burning Man as art?  I do, it was 1995...  
>(http://www.weirdamerica.com/2007/05/20/weird-america-car-hunt/)
>
>A theme park is not a revolution, even if it is fun to visit or a good 
>place to take drugs.
>
>Hakim Bey (aka Peter Lamborn Wilson) on Burning Man:
>
>"I¢ve never been to Burning Man, but that¢s just accidental, because I¢ve 
>given up travel. As far as I can tell it¢s a lovely thing. I call those 
>things 'periodic autonomous zones.' The thing about the TAZ is I didn¢t 
>invent it, I just gave it a name. I think it¢s a sociological reality that 
>groups of people will come together to maximize some concept of freedom 
>that they share as naturally as breathing. When all the potential for the 
>emergence for a TAZ is maximized, either because you¢ve helped to maximize 
>it or because your local situation has arrived at a certain point where it 
>becomes possible, you¢ll do it. Like I¢ve said before, a TAZ is anywhere 
>from two to several thousand people, who for as little as two or three 
>hours or for as much as a couple of years manage to keep that mood going. 
>And it¢s incredibly vital. It¢s vital that every human being should have 
>some such experience, or else they¢ll never know that another world is 
>possible. So Burning Man is a kind of
>  periodic autonomous zone."
>
>He continues, "As soon as the first hint of commercialization or tiredness 
>appears, then I would think the best thing to do is to close it down. Move 
>on, reappear somewhere else. And ultimately, I do believe that another 
>world is possible and that permanent changes could be made. But that¢s 
>different. That¢s a revolution."
>
>http://www.thebrooklynrail.org/spotlight/july04/wilson.html
>
>Of course only the people involved will know when "first hint of 
>commercialization or tiredness appears" and this might be a matter of 
>opinion or debate.
>
>>From this one outsider's point of view it happened a few years ago.
>
>Peace,
>
>Peter
>

>Hah... this thread reminds me of an old article jwz wrote about
>Burning Man, their brand, and the sheer hypocrisy of the corporation
>behind the event:
>
>http://www.jwz.org/gruntle/burningman.html
>
>What bothers me even more than the hypocrisy alone, is that they mix
>it with a good dose off elitism for good measure...  Like going to a
>week-long party in the desert (Oh, I'm sorry.  I should say "on the
>playa" or "at Black Rock City.") makes them sooo special and sooo
>much better than me and how I (Who prefers my partying and drug use
>in nice 6-10-hour chunks followed by a shower, clean clothes, and a
>good day's sleep in my own bed, thankyouverymuch.) am just totally
>incapable of ever understanding what it's like to be a "burner".
>
>I know not everyone who goes is like that.  I've got a some very good
>friends who go every year.  But as the years go on, and they go and I
>don't, even from some of them I start to catch twinges of a "BM's not
>for you." or "You just don't understand." attitude.
>
>One year or another, I'll probably get around to going... if only to
>see just what the big F-ing deal is.  It'll shock the living hell out
>of everyone who knows just how much I hate sunlight, being hot, and
>being dirty.  But I just can't shake the notion that it's something I
>should do at least *once* in my life.  And when you come right down
>to it, a little hypocrisy on the part of the BM corporation is small
>potatoes compared to the outright evil of corporations like
>microsoft, walmart, halliburton, texaco, enron, and their ilk.  But
>the elitist flack I've caught from "burners" when they've found out
>that I'm not part of their club doesn't exactly acquit the event in
>my mind.  I wonder if I would be made to feel as welcome, as a late-
>coming newbie were I to actually go to BM, as I was when I started
>going to raves?

>----- Original Message ----
>From: "dangrsmind@yahoo.com" <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
>To: John B <SvnLyrBrto@yahoo.com>; Van Mundegaarde 
><electrofunk138@hotmail.com>
>Cc: dj.soundwave@gmail.com; sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Sent: Wednesday, June 13, 2007 7:36:41 AM
>Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?
>
>
>Now that's funny, because I was just about to sit down to write something 
>in which I was going to link Disneyland (where I was this past Christmas) 
>with Burning Man.  Specifically, I was going to point out the similarity 
>and differences between the Disneyland and BM safety and photo policies.  
>I'm glad I didn't write that because you'd just think I scarfed it from 
>your friend's rant.
>
>The restrictions on activities at Disneyland and BM are quite similar 
>actually.  Both prohibit commercial photography and both prohibit the sale 
>of goods inside the park/event boundaries for example.  Weapons are 
>prohibited at both places.  Remember when people used to shoot up cars and 
>blow things up at Burning Man as art?  I do, it was 1995...  
>(http://www.weirdamerica.com/2007/05/20/weird-america-car-hunt/)
>
>A theme park is not a revolution, even if it is fun to visit or a good 
>place to take drugs.
>
>Hakim Bey (aka Peter Lamborn Wilson) on Burning Man:
>
>"I¢ve never been to Burning Man, but that¢s just accidental, because I¢ve 
>given up travel. As far as I can tell it¢s a lovely thing. I call those 
>things 'periodic autonomous zones.' The thing about the TAZ is I didn¢t 
>invent it, I just gave it a name. I think it¢s a sociological reality that 
>groups of people will come together to maximize some concept of freedom 
>that they share as naturally as breathing. When all the potential for the 
>emergence for a TAZ is maximized, either because you¢ve helped to maximize 
>it or because your local situation has arrived at a certain point where it 
>becomes possible, you¢ll do it. Like I¢ve said before, a TAZ is anywhere 
>from two to several thousand people, who for as little as two or three 
>hours or for as much as a couple of years manage to keep that mood going. 
>And it¢s incredibly vital. It¢s vital that every human being should have 
>some such experience, or else they¢ll never know that another world is 
>possible. So Burning Man is a kind of
>periodic autonomous zone."
>
>He continues, "As soon as the first hint of commercialization or tiredness 
>appears, then I would think the best thing to do is to close it down. Move 
>on, reappear somewhere else. And ultimately, I do believe that another 
>world is possible and that permanent changes could be made. But that¢s 
>different. That¢s a revolution."
>
>http://www.thebrooklynrail.org/spotlight/july04/wilson.html
>
>Of course only the people involved will know when "first hint of 
>commercialization or tiredness appears" and this might be a matter of 
>opinion or debate.
>
>>From this one outsider's point of view it happened a few years ago.
>
>Peace,
>
>Peter
>

>From: Bam <invibe@gmail.com>
>To: "The Twilight Laser Outpost" <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>Subject: Stabilizer on Netamp - Tonight!
>Date: Wed, 13 Jun 2007 18:50:44 -0700
>Stabilizer will be rocking it live tonight on Netamp, SF's own online
>breakbeat radio station hosted on Nuskoolbreaks.co.uk. Local support
>from Aaron Jae, Evinrude and Robb Green.
>
>Tune in from 8pm-10pm at:
>www.netamp.com


>It's our 3rd Bassdrop and once again we've got another WICKED UK
>headliner. You really don't want to sleep on this one, cause it's goin
>to be a bangin night.
>
>
>Stabilizer
>(Plastic Raygun/Boombox/Functional Breaks/Lithium Music)
>
>As a producer Stabilizer has earned many supporters in the breaks
>fraternity and beyond. A series of singles and remixes over the past
>three years, on labels such as Boombox Records, Kosmo and Functional
>Breaks, have gained the support of Andy Weatherall, Boy George, Annie
>Nightingale (Radio 1), Hybrid, Krafty Kuts, Scanty Sandwich,
>Scissorkicks, Anthony Pappa and Caspar Kedros (Headrillaz) among
>others.
>
>Stabilizer is now signed to the mighty Plastic Raygun and the first
>single release, What It Takes rose to Number 5 in the DJ Mag breaks
>chart as well as being described as "A Classic" by none other than
>Andy Weatherall.
>
>As well as the production, Stabilizer can be found despoiling the
>world=D5s ears in a breakbeat and punky house fashion in places as
>diverse as Bath, Bognor and Berlin, with a US tour planned.
>
>Armed with a bag of records and a sampler - with an emphasis firmly on
>good tunes and a good time - the Stabilizer DJ style is tight, varied
>and always full of energy. With genres ranging from Hip Hip and Funk
>via punky house all the way to the freshest nu-school breaks cuts.
>Only two rules... it's got to be good, and it's got to be funky.
>
>
>Along with:
>DJ Unagi (Word of Mouth) - Special birthday set
>M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
>Athena (Evil Breaks)
>
>more info on this & other events: www.EvilBreaks.com

>http://www.getbammed.com
>http://www.evilbreaks.com

>From: "Nyc W. Alberts" <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>
>To: SFRaves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: The Singularity Approacheth....
>Date: Thu, 14 Jun 2007 06:58:10 -0400
>    "Is It Live, Or Is It Memorex?"
>
>    "Skynet begins to learn at a geometric rate. It becomes self-aware
>    at 2:14 a.m. Eastern time, August 29th. In a panic, they try to pull
>    the plug. "
>
>For the last several years it has been a running gag between me and those 
>that know me that it's getting harder and harder to tell the difference 
>between what we know as "Reality" and what passes for the fine reportage 
>from "America's Finest News Source," otherwise known as "The Onion".
>
>
>    Nation Hoping For A Windy Flag Day
>
>    June 5, 2007 | Issue 43â€¢23
>
>    WASHINGTON, DCâ€”With June 14 just a week away, citizens nationwide
>    are hoping that brisk, windy weather is in store for this Flag Day.
>
>    "A Flag Day without wind is like a Columbus Day with mail delivery:
>    It just doesn't feel right," said Coast Guard Rear Adm. Roger
>    Jessup, who is serving as this year's Flag Day grand marshal. "I
>    long for the Flag Days of my youth, when the winds were always
>    strong and steady. Seems like in the past few years there's barely
>    been a breeze and Old Glory just droops. Except for Flag Day '02,
>    when it was so blustery the flag whipped right around the flagpole."
>
>    Jessup, whose duties include answering Flag Day mail from the
>    nation's children, added that if everyone tried as hard as they
>    could to be good this week, "perhaps Starry Stripes, the Flag Day
>    Fairy, will blow some nice breezy air our way."
>
>Well, I'm here to tell you that today, June 14th, 2007, at exactly 5am, 
>EST, the Flag Day commemoration here in the United States Of America, The 
>Weather Channel led with an item about the effects that gusty winds will 
>have today.
>
>I don't know any other way to put this....
>
>We're seriously  in big fucking trouble.
>

>> From: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
>> To: John B <SvnLyrBrto@yahoo.com>,  Van Mundegaarde 
>> <electrofunk138@hotmail.com>
>> CC: dj.soundwave@gmail.com, sfraves@hyperreal.org
>> Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?
>> Date: Wed, 13 Jun 2007 07:36:41 -0700 (PDT)
>> Now that's funny, because I was just about to sit down to write something 
>> in which I was going to link Disneyland (where I was this past Christmas) 
>> with Burning Man.  Specifically, I was going to point out the similarity 
>> and differences between the Disneyland and BM safety and photo policies. 
>> I'm glad I didn't write that because you'd just think I scarfed it from 
>> your friend's rant.
>> 
>> The restrictions on activities at Disneyland and BM are quite similar 
>> actually.  Both prohibit commercial photography and both prohibit the sale 
>> of goods inside the park/event boundaries for example.  Weapons are 
>> prohibited at both places.  Remember when people used to shoot up cars and 
>> blow things up at Burning Man as art?  I do, it was 1995... 
>> (http://www.weirdamerica.com/2007/05/20/weird-america-car-hunt/)
>> 
>> A theme park is not a revolution, even if it is fun to visit or a good 
>> place to take drugs.
>> 
>> Hakim Bey (aka Peter Lamborn Wilson) on Burning Man:
>> 
>> "I¢ve never been to Burning Man, but that¢s just accidental, because I¢ve 
>> given up travel. As far as I can tell it¢s a lovely thing. I call those 
>> things 'periodic autonomous zones.' The thing about the TAZ is I didn¢t 
>> invent it, I just gave it a name. I think it¢s a sociological reality that 
>> groups of people will come together to maximize some concept of freedom 
>> that they share as naturally as breathing. When all the potential for the 
>> emergence for a TAZ is maximized, either because you¢ve helped to maximize 
>> it or because your local situation has arrived at a certain point where it 
>> becomes possible, you¢ll do it. Like I¢ve said before, a TAZ is anywhere 
>> from two to several thousand people, who for as little as two or three 
>> hours or for as much as a couple of years manage to keep that mood going. 
>> And it¢s incredibly vital. It¢s vital that every human being should have 
>> some such experience, or else they¢ll never know that another world is 
>> possible. So Burning Man is a kind of
>>  periodic autonomous zone."
>> 
>> He continues, "As soon as the first hint of commercialization or tiredness 
>> appears, then I would think the best thing to do is to close it down. Move 
>> on, reappear somewhere else. And ultimately, I do believe that another 
>> world is possible and that permanent changes could be made. But that¢s 
>> different. That¢s a revolution."
>> 
>> http://www.thebrooklynrail.org/spotlight/july04/wilson.html
>> 
>> Of course only the people involved will know when "first hint of 
>> commercialization or tiredness appears" and this might be a matter of 
>> opinion or debate.
>> 
>> From this one outsider's point of view it happened a few years ago.
>> 
>> Peace,
>> 
>> Peter
>> 
>> ----- Original Message ----
>> From: John B <SvnLyrBrto@yahoo.com>
>> To: Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com>
>> Cc: dj.soundwave@gmail.com; sfraves@hyperreal.org
>> Sent: Tuesday, June 12, 2007 11:50:44 PM
>> Subject: Re: [sfraves] Burning Man Re-Compression?
>> 
>> 
>> Hah... this thread reminds me of an old article jwz wrote about
>> Burning Man, their brand, and the sheer hypocrisy of the corporation
>> behind the event:
>> 
>> http://www.jwz.org/gruntle/burningman.html
>> 
>> What bothers me even more than the hypocrisy alone, is that they mix
>> it with a good dose off elitism for good measure...  Like going to a
>> week-long party in the desert (Oh, I'm sorry.  I should say "on the
>> playa" or "at Black Rock City.") makes them sooo special and sooo
>> much better than me and how I (Who prefers my partying and drug use
>> in nice 6-10-hour chunks followed by a shower, clean clothes, and a
>> good day's sleep in my own bed, thankyouverymuch.) am just totally
>> incapable of ever understanding what it's like to be a "burner".
>> 
>> I know not everyone who goes is like that.  I've got a some very good
>> friends who go every year.  But as the years go on, and they go and I
>> don't, even from some of them I start to catch twinges of a "BM's not
>> for you." or "You just don't understand." attitude.
>> 
>> One year or another, I'll probably get around to going... if only to
>> see just what the big F-ing deal is.  It'll shock the living hell out
>> of everyone who knows just how much I hate sunlight, being hot, and
>> being dirty.  But I just can't shake the notion that it's something I
>> should do at least *once* in my life.  And when you come right down
>> to it, a little hypocrisy on the part of the BM corporation is small
>> potatoes compared to the outright evil of corporations like
>> microsoft, walmart, halliburton, texaco, enron, and their ilk.  But
>> the elitist flack I've caught from "burners" when they've found out
>> that I'm not part of their club doesn't exactly acquit the event in
>> my mind.  I wonder if I would be made to feel as welcome, as a late-
>> coming newbie were I to actually go to BM, as I was when I started
>> going to raves?
>> 
>> 
>> cya,
>> john
>> 
>>

>> To: "The Twilight Laser Outpost" <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>> Subject: Stabilizer on Netamp - Tonight!
>> Date: Wed, 13 Jun 2007 18:50:44 -0700
>> Stabilizer will be rocking it live tonight on Netamp, SF's own online
>> breakbeat radio station hosted on Nuskoolbreaks.co.uk. Local support
>> from Aaron Jae, Evinrude and Robb Green.
>> 
>> Tune in from 8pm-10pm at:
>> www.netamp.com
>
>
>> It's our 3rd Bassdrop and once again we've got another WICKED UK
>> headliner. You really don't want to sleep on this one, cause it's goin
>> to be a bangin night.
>> 
>> 
>> Stabilizer
>> (Plastic Raygun/Boombox/Functional Breaks/Lithium Music)
>> 
>> As a producer Stabilizer has earned many supporters in the breaks
>> fraternity and beyond. A series of singles and remixes over the past
>> three years, on labels such as Boombox Records, Kosmo and Functional
>> Breaks, have gained the support of Andy Weatherall, Boy George, Annie
>> Nightingale (Radio 1), Hybrid, Krafty Kuts, Scanty Sandwich,
>> Scissorkicks, Anthony Pappa and Caspar Kedros (Headrillaz) among
>> others.
>> 
>> Stabilizer is now signed to the mighty Plastic Raygun and the first
>> single release, What It Takes rose to Number 5 in the DJ Mag breaks
>> chart as well as being described as "A Classic" by none other than
>> Andy Weatherall.
>> 
>> As well as the production, Stabilizer can be found despoiling the
>> world=D5s ears in a breakbeat and punky house fashion in places as
>> diverse as Bath, Bognor and Berlin, with a US tour planned.
>> 
>> Armed with a bag of records and a sampler - with an emphasis firmly on
>> good tunes and a good time - the Stabilizer DJ style is tight, varied
>> and always full of energy. With genres ranging from Hip Hip and Funk
>> via punky house all the way to the freshest nu-school breaks cuts.
>> Only two rules... it's got to be good, and it's got to be funky.
>> 
>> 
>> Along with:
>> DJ Unagi (Word of Mouth) - Special birthday set
>> M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
>> Athena (Evil Breaks)
>> 
>> more info on this & other events: www.EvilBreaks.com

>> From: "Nyc W. Alberts" <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>
>> To: SFRaves@hyperreal.org
>> Subject: The Singularity Approacheth....
>> Date: Thu, 14 Jun 2007 06:58:10 -0400
>>    "Is It Live, Or Is It Memorex?"
>>
>>    "Skynet begins to learn at a geometric rate. It becomes self-aware
>>    at 2:14 a.m. Eastern time, August 29th. In a panic, they try to pull
>>    the plug. "
>> 
>> For the last several years it has been a running gag between me and those 
>> that know me that it's getting harder and harder to tell the difference 
>> between what we know as "Reality" and what passes for the fine reportage 
>> from "America's Finest News Source," otherwise known as "The Onion".
>> 
>>
>>    Nation Hoping For A Windy Flag Day
>>
>>    June 5, 2007 | Issue 43â€¢23
>>
>>    WASHINGTON, DCâ€”With June 14 just a week away, citizens nationwide
>>    are hoping that brisk, windy weather is in store for this Flag Day.
>>
>>    "A Flag Day without wind is like a Columbus Day with mail delivery:
>>    It just doesn't feel right," said Coast Guard Rear Adm. Roger
>>    Jessup, who is serving as this year's Flag Day grand marshal. "I
>>    long for the Flag Days of my youth, when the winds were always
>>    strong and steady. Seems like in the past few years there's barely
>>    been a breeze and Old Glory just droops. Except for Flag Day '02,
>>    when it was so blustery the flag whipped right around the flagpole."
>>
>>    Jessup, whose duties include answering Flag Day mail from the
>>    nation's children, added that if everyone tried as hard as they
>>    could to be good this week, "perhaps Starry Stripes, the Flag Day
>>    Fairy, will blow some nice breezy air our way."
>> 
>> Well, I'm here to tell you that today, June 14th, 2007, at exactly 5am, 
>> EST, the Flag Day commemoration here in the United States Of America, The 
>> Weather Channel led with an item about the effects that gusty winds will 
>> have today.
>> 
>> I don't know any other way to put this....
>> 
>> We're seriously  in big fucking trouble.

From: "Osby Oi Oi Jamz" <osby@viberation.com>

  t411b0y@jungletrain.net, geisha@gmail.com

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] WR: My 48 hour adventure to LA & Back home


OK.. Hola SF RAvers!!!! Like so in an effort to get back into the mondo
like swing of things again & stuff on here & do my Weekend Reviews
regularly again & to catch up w/ what i've been up to these past few
months 'cause i only been posting up like hella BSPs & replies instead of
reporting my yummy outings on here & feel sooo mondo like guilty,
serioulsy, for not keeping up, & also so stretch my creativity & in an
effort to motivate mysefl to finish my homework 'casuse i gotta finish two
more papers for my current class @ UOP... i"m gonna do a WR now &
hopefully catch up b4 this next coming weekend ;)

(oh yeah.. i'm gonna try writing this a different way & since most of this
trip was on a time table, i kinda remember pretty much all the times i
looked @ my watch... yeeeah i know...i have a really weird memory!!!)  Oh
yeah.. in the way i'm writing this.. it may be like mondo long to read...
so when u got the time... read away ;)

Friday June 15th, 2007

6:36PM: Got off the phone w/ Mom to see how the weather is in LA since
they took off earlier in the morn to go w/ Tita & Tito for Kriten's Grad
from Irvine!  I told her to tell all the relatives I send my Love &
Congrats to Kristen for Graduating!  Hello 2Day... me & Mom & Dad are
gonna be in LA at the same time, b ut not together, how funny!!!  Left
HOuse, waited for 13.

6:52PM: On the JX at the HTC, on the way to El Cerrito Del Norte BART station

8:15-8:25PM: Sol picks me up in the Bayfair BART Station pick up/ drop off
area, we totally laugh at each other and are totally happy to see each
other! Drive to his house, carried my stuff in, played w/ animals! Katie
(Sol's GF) is late!

9:40-10:02PM: Eating dinner @ Round Table... Sol got a veggie pizza, so i
got (real cooked) bacon bits @ salad bar & put all over my slices!  Get
Got gas... On the 238/ 580/ 680/ then finally the 5 & on our way to LA..
Hello 2Day...

11:04PM: Stopped off random exit to go gas station so Katie could buy cigs

Saturday June 16th, 2007

12:06-12:20AM: We're in Santa Nella 'cause Katie needed a light clip
thingie to read her book, so we drove to 2 gas stations to find one.

1:37AM: Sol stops for gas at a random exit.  I finally figured out how to
sit comfortabely in the back sit!  Car Sickness feeling went away

4:32AM: got to Marriot in Torrance, checked in, went to room, brushed
teeth, went to bed

5:30-6AM: started watching this HBO documentary about Crackheads & Crack
whores trespassing in apartment buildings & getting high in stairwells &
evevators then leaving!  "Oh shit, that guy's getting a blowjob on TV for
crack money from another guy!" i thought as I driffted off & fell asleep.

10AM: Someone's phone alarm goes off & I wake up & start getting ready for
the wedding!  I'm the first one to take a shower & get ready.  Fuck, I
need coffee!

11:55AM:  I sit down in 1 of the lobby seats while Sol checks out.  Katie
is getting coffee at the inhouse Starbucks shop in the back of the lobby.
I talk to the manager of the hotel if I'd be able to work at his hotle
lookig the way i look & he said i'd have to take out all my visible
peircings & I tol dhim for Religous reason i can't do that & I don't bite
& I would be perfect to work for him 'cause i've had over 4 years
experience workin' in Hotels & know the dealie.  then he asked if i was
really looking to work for him & i said i wasn't, i was just curious if
he'd hire based on what we talked about ;)  He said i made some good
points & he probably would of if i lived in LA!!!

12:45PM: Eating a Sushi Brunch @ Paradise Sushi on the Hermosa Beach/
Boardwalk...

1:30PM:  Hanging out @ this bar on the boardwalk still... it got too hot
to stay in the sun to watch the beach vball tournie, so Sol wanted to
drink!  Alota people are trippin' 'cause I'm hella dressed & got my top
hat on... well.. some people have complimented me w/ the top hat! :)  Some
guy asked me to pull a rabbit outta my hat!

2:10PM:  Leaving Hermosa Beach!  Sol says his tolerance to drinking is
like so high that he doesn't get drunk... then why the fuck is he driving
hella rekless right now man??

2:45PM  Sol just drove over a HUGE pot hole & started laughing!  I was
takin' a nap kinda got woken by it & my neck hella did something funny & I
can't turn it or anything.. FUCK!  We pull in to the wrong part of the
Bread Of Life Church & Sol runs out & takes a piss in the bushes!

3:17PM:  I smoke a cig in the parking lot & see Hoj!  We talk & catch up! 
He has like that hella long but not too long Fabio hair!!  He's a big DJ
now in the house scene... Sweet!  I'm proud of him!  We start walking back
to the Church & I"m only 1/2 way done, oh well!

3:20PM: I finish wrapping my gift inside the church... the sound guy let
me use some tape!  Fuck.. i should bought stickers!

3:30PM:  The wedding ceremony starts!  Vin & Tash look sooo Awesome!!!

5:25PM:  IN Rose & Anthony's room have pre-partying before the reception! 
I drink a glass of red wine.  Cindy's telling us how to tell if it's aged
by looking @ the ring of the wine in the glass!

6:15-10:45PM:  Recepetion- Empress Of The Chinese Resturaunt.  10 course
meal, I only made it to course 4 'cause i ate way too much yummy shrimp! 
Wedding DJ was funny!  I requested Janet Jackson & he played Escapade &
Control!  Couldn't dance 'cause of the kinda whiplash from Sol's driving! 
Sol got reeeeeally more like totally drunk!  It was Dope seeing like all
the old skool ravers & the old DTB crew all together again!!  I got into
an arguement w/ Ian 'cause he was self misinformed about the Jungle scene
in SF & didn't know what he was talking about!  Vin's Dad was hyper &
drunk & was totally awesome during the reception & hella danced &
socialized w/ us!

11PM:  IN Rose & Anthony's room again @ Hilton.. drinking more, talkin' to
old Homies again!  Me & Jack catch up on everything, we haven't spoken in
like 5 years!  Brian is goin' around everywhere huggin' people telling us
that he Loves us!  Ingriad give me a massage on my neck... kinda helps,
but not really!  I hella bond w/ this dude Lance while we watch Showtime
At The Apollo!  We're all drunk!

Sunday - June 17th 2007

2AM:  Me & Lance decided we wanted Milkshakes from Denny's across the
street.  Sol & Katie come with us & we end up getting a table!  They order
food.  Lance told me that Ingrid wasn't drunk, she just acted the way she
did 'cause she was tryin' to get her bf (Vin's Brother) jealous or
something by acting flity?!  I dunno man... but man... my Strawberry from
Denny's that i been fantasizing about for the past 2 months was just soo
Damn Yummy!!!

2:40AM:  Said out goodbyes to Lance & I told him to tell the rest of the
crew that i Love them!  Back on the road again!!!  I miss my Pheobe!!  I
hope she's doin' alrigth home alone!

5AM: get a room @ Best Western Motel off aome random exit off 5... as soon
as we all lie down, we all instantly pass out!

10AM:  We get up to the alarm of Mexican Samba music playhing on the alarm
clock in the room!!  I swear, i feel like I"m dreaming right now!  Brushed
my teeth & packed up whatever i had, then we took off!

2:15PM:  Sol pulls over some random exit off 5, pulls into the shade of a
tree in a parking lot & sleeps... I go out into the grass area & write in
my song book while Sol & Katie sleeps in car!

5:34PM: HOME!!!!  Get my shit outta the car, give hugs, offer them to use
bathroom, they refuse, they leave, I go in house, pick up Pheobe & hug,
then let her go outside!

6PM:  After unpacking a lil' & looking in fridge for food & seeing none...
i go across the street to the Mexican Family's pad.. talk to Big Brother
for a while, tell him the dealie, then Lil' Brother goes in house & gets
food for me!  Beef Mole, Rice, Beans, & Mini Tortillas!!!  YUM!!!

6:30PM:  Somewhat decompressed from traveling.. talking to Homies
online... still eating food from across the street!  Talked to Mom,
they're in Gaudalupe/ Santa Maria right now to visit Auntie Julie when
they left LA w/ Tita Marie & Tito ... they'll be home later tonight!
----------
That was my weekend :)



-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Cross Fading or Volume Controlling?

Depends on the track/format. I switched over primarily to using CD's, and 
anything lower bitrate than 320 Kbps can be janky as far as volume is 
concerned. SOmetimes you can adjust volume just using the EQ's, but other 
times the gain is what is necessary. I have never really played on a mixer 
where it's set up to max out before the fader is all the way at the top of 
the fader channel - I tend to reduce the overall volume so I can slam the 
faders to the hilt. So other than using the faders to do exactly what they 
are meant to do, which is fade the track volume in and out for smooth 
transitions, I tend to primarily do all my fine tuning with the EQ & gains. 
If you work shit properly, you can avoid stuff like bass cancellation and 
huge volume differences like that...or at least, in my experience thus far.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Cross Fading or Volume Controlling?

i started off DJing using the cross fader, primarily.  now, i almost
always use the volume faders.

the reason being:

- one, i scratch (poorly) on occasion.  in those circumstances, i
adjust the crossfader to have a steep curve.  that is, if the mixer
has a fader adjust.

- too many times mixing on a rave/club mixer where the crossfader is
shoddy and/or bleeds


really, your best bet is to be comfortable using both.  depending on
the type of music being played and how you prefer to mix, both have
advantages and their own time and place.

Word! On those dam faders that are bad at some venues. Depending on the track 
and the mixer would prompt me on what to do. I still like using a combination 
of both the channel volume and cross fader I also like to eq my mixes but 
some venues have people on mix boards or preset volume threshold that are set 
when all your eq knobs are in the middle and that is were it usually sounds best. 
If u are at venues like this all u have to worry about is your mixing. As for 
using the crossfader, it is fun to use when it is working properly, otherwise 
just use the channel volumes with some eq-ing and u should be all good. MY 
recommended mixers are the rotary rane for seamless mixing but, if u like to do 
some trick and effects I recommend the pioneer600 and or the equivalent allen&
heath xone mixers.

--

The shift to climate change being a focal point came about for two
very distinct reasons.  The first reason was, by the mid 80's, a
majority of people now agreed with all the reasonable things we in the
environmental movement were saying they should do.  Now when a
majority of people agree with you, it's pretty hard to remain
confrontational with them.  And so the only way to remain
anti-establishment was to adopt ever more extreme positions.  When I
left Greenpeace, it was in the midst of them adopting a campaign to
ban chlorine worldwide.  Like I said, "you guys, this is one of the
elements in the periodic table, you know, I'm not sure if that's in
our juridstiction to be banning a whole element."

- Patrick Moore, co-founder of Greenpeace

   HIGH CALIBER aka BRYAN JONES & MIKE GILLENWATER (Nocturnal / Olive / Moody / Carizma / Nine / Control, Chicago) 
 Wrapping up his international Step Back 2007 Tour, DJ Bryan Jones joins Mike Gillenwater as High Caliber, originally formed in late 2002. Both artists hail from Chicago where they’ve independently established themselves as icons in the Funky House scene. Five years and nearly 20 chart-busting EPs later, High Caliber is releasing their biggest project to date: 

“Old School Sessions,” a four-part all-digital mix series that was too long to condense into one album. Catch tracks from this new groundbreaking series along with other HC classics for a floor-rocking experience San Francisco will surely not forget!

CHUCK G <chuckg_421@yahoo.com> wrote:BACK ON TRACK, Saturday July 7th, San Francisco

CaliGrown Events serves you:
   
   HIGH CALIBER aka BRYAN JONES & MIKE GILLENWATER (Nocturnal / Olive / Moody / Carizma / Nine / Control, Chicago) 
 Wrapping up his international Step Back 2007 Tour, DJ Bryan Jones joins Mike Gillenwater as High Caliber, originally formed in late 2002. Both artists hail from Chicago where they’ve independently established themselves as icons in the Funky House scene. Five years and nearly 20 chart-busting EPs later, High Caliber is releasing their biggest project to date: 

“Old School Sessions,” a four-part all-digital mix series that was too long to condense into one album. Catch tracks from this new groundbreaking series along with other HC classics for a floor-rocking experience San Francisco will surely not forget! 

MORE INFO: 
http://www.myspace.com/highcaliberchicago
http://stompy.com/Label/Control?resultpage=3&ob=date

http://www.caligrownevents.com
http://www.myspace.com/caligrownevents

<B>Saturday 7-7-7 (SF)

WARNING: F*7K!N6 INCREDIBLE LINEUP!!!!!</B>

Saturday, July 7th 2007 (7-7-7):
CaliGrown Events proudly presents BACK ON TRACK, featuring world-class acts 
from Belgium,
Chicago, Las Vegas, and San Francisco. Enjoy all night drink specials while 
grooving to:

<B>CONGA SQUAD aka C-MOS (Holographic Music, Belgium) </B>
Known to many as Conga Squad, Olivier Abbeloos also produces under names 
such as C-Mos,
Goldbumpers, Dynetic, Bio-nic, Inferno, Quadrophonia, T99, and Kretek. Over 
the past 15
years, this Disco House master has developed a signature sound that is like 
no other in
House music. His style of pumpin, steppy, driving Disco House has made 
Olivier a huge
success with many of the most influential DJ's from around the world. Not 
only a successful
music producer, Mr. Abbeloos is also a successful DJ with over 18 years of 
experience.
Olivier Abbeloos performs all over the world, and has several residencies in 
his home
country of Belgium including La Rocca. Abbeloos is also the founder & 
primary artist of
legendary House labels Holographic Music & E.P.O.S, and has released over 
fifty (50) tracks
to date! DO NOT UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCES MISS CONGA SQUAD!
MORE INFO: WWW.HOLOGRAPHICMUSIC.COM
http://www.myspace.com/abbeloosolivier

<B>HIGH CALIBER aka BRYAN JONES & MIKE GILLENWATER (Nocturnal / Olive / 
Moody / Carizma / Nine
/ Control, Chicago) </B>
Wrapping up his international Step Back 2007 Tour, DJ Bryan Jones joins Mike 
Gillenwater as
High Caliber, originally formed in late 2002. Both artists hail from Chicago 
where they’ve
independently established themselves as icons in the Funky House scene. Five 
years and
nearly 20 chart-busting EPs later, High Caliber is releasing their biggest 
project to date:
“Old School Sessions,” a four-part all-digital mix series that was too long 
to condense into
one album. Catch tracks from this new groundbreaking series along with other 
HC classics for
a floor-rocking experience San Francisco will surely not forget!
MORE INFO: WWW.MYSPACE.COM/HIGHCALIBERCHICAGO

<B>JENO (WICKED,SF) </B>
A name that needs no introduction in SF House Music, Jeno has been 
organizing legendary
underground parties and rocking dance floors around the world since the 
mid-eighties. As one
of the “Wicked” DJ’s, Jeno helped define an eclectic and soulful musical 
style that was the
original sound of San Francisco.
MORE INFO: WWW.DJJENO.COM
http://www.myspace.com/jeno

<B>ERIC SPIRE (Silver Pearl Records / Sony Records / QUEST , Bay Area & Las 
Vegas) </B>
The owner & founder of Silver Pearl records, world-famous DJ, and founding 
father of Quest;
Eric Spire has spent the past 7 years in the studio producing major label 
acts, television
themes, movie soundtracks, video game sound bytes, and quite of bit of Dance 
Music. Missing
the excitement of the crowd, Eric is returning to the decks to grace his 
fans with another
masterful & soul-moving set that they have been craving since 2000!
MORE INFO: WWW.SILVERPEARL.COM
http://www.myspace.com/silverprl1

WITH SPECIAL GUESTS:

<B>THE MARIO BROS. - TAG SET (OtherWorld / Tech Funk Alliance / Midnight 
Sons / Essential
Breaks West, SF)</B>
What can we say about these guys? They're fucking awesome! The Mario Bros. 
is made up of one
part "daniella downs", one part "Marc(O)" and a whole lot of pimp juice. 
They are best
served straight up in a highball glass...
http://www.myspace.com/the_mario_bros
http://www.themidnightsons.com

<B>THE FINGERMONSTERS - LIVE PA (SHAZBOT, ORIGAMI, ANDREW PHELAN, and CUBIK 
, SF) </B>
The Fingermonsters create maximal floor-magnet tracks with tongue firmly in 
cheek and hands
firmly on knobs. They’ve been tearing San Francisco and the Bay Area a new 
one with a
4-person live laptop/drum machine PA assault that is not to be missed!

<B>DJ HEADCASE - LIVE PA - CD RELEASE PARTY (CaliGrown , SF)</B>

<B>JAYSON KINCAID (Grooves-in-the-Park / Culture / Om Records , SF)</B>
http://www.myspace.com/jaysonkincaid

<B>DEAN KROH (Seedless Music, Liquid Graf-X-209)</B>

<B>SF's own SPACE COWBOY DJ’S:</B>
AARON JAE (Space Cowboys/XM/Evil Breaks)
KAPT’N KIRK (Space Cowboys/Panda Rejects)
EVINRUDE (Space Cowboys/NetAmp)

<B>CHILL HOURS HOSTED BY: THE AMBIENT MAFIA (www.ambientmafia.com)</B>
MO CORLEONE (Want It/:am)
SQUELCHY (The Extra Credit/:am)
OLDE NASTY (Butterzone/:am)
REDSTICKMAN (BCC:/:am)


Additional Attractions:
Set & Atmosphere by Eyezmind.
Sexy GoGo Dancers
Intelligent Lighting
and a specially-contracted rockin’ Sound System by Know Audio!
Free CD & Shirt giveaways!

General Info:

VENUE:
FAT CITY (formerly Studio Z)
314 11th St.
San Francisco, CA

AGES:
21+ ID Required

ENTRY:
LIMITED PRESALES & BEFORE 11:00 PM: $15.00

DRESS CODE STRICTLY NOT ENFORCED!

More Info:
www.myspace.com/backontrack
www.caligrownevents.com

“WTF are CaliGrown Events?”

We’re a spin-off of a former Central Valley UG rave crew called Elysium from 
the
late 90’s - early 00’s. Elysium produced several events in the Central 
Valley, and
some in the Bay Area including a residence at the now infamous Hotel Ibiza 
in
2001. CaliGrown is based out of San Jose. We produce events out of love for 
the
music and the vibe its followers carry.




Marc(O)
The Mario Bros.//OtherWorld//Ill Behavior//The MidnightSons (DC/SF)
www.themidnightsons.com
www.myspace.com/the_mario_bros
www.myspace.com/illectrofunk


7/7/07: Back On Track w/ Conga Squad & more (SF)
9/1/07: Annual Island Party w/ Carbon Community & more (Central PA)

"Olde English 800 'cause that's my brand; Take it in a
bottle, 40, quart or can"

I decided to drink a 32 of St. Ides at a friend's
place in LA once.  I remember getting to the bottom of
the bottle and setting the empty on the table in front
of the couch.  I closed my eyes and when I opened them
up again, it was about 4 hours later, everyone had
left, the lights were out and I was laying on my side
on the couch.  I have no idea what happened during the
time between.  I never drank St. Ides again.

>I decided to drink a 32 of St. Ides at a friend's
>place in LA once.  I remember getting to the bottom of
>the bottle and setting the empty on the table in front
>of the couch.  I closed my eyes and when I opened them
>up again, it was about 4 hours later, everyone had
>left, the lights were out and I was laying on my side
>on the couch.  I have no idea what happened during the
>time between.  I never drank St. Ides again.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP - Tonal: Poppin' Pink this Saturday with NYC's Troydon!

Saturday, June 23rd
10 PM 'til very late
Rock It Science and Prismatic Tracks present:

Tonal: Poppin' Pink

SF Location: call 888-482-9281 or 415-412-0406, or visit prismatictracks.com
$5 before 10:30 PM, $10 before midnight, $15 after
Free mix CD for dressing in Poppin' Pink (make some serious effort people!)
Happy Birthdays: Alida and Barry!

With special guest DJs:

Troydon--NYC (Om Records, Drop Music, Freerange)--2 Hour Set--Premier San
Francisco Underground Appearance!

Troydon has rocked a Stompy party, thrown down a killer set on one of last
year's Sunset Boat Parties, and most recently tore the roof off of the
Endup.  A transplant from South Africa to NYC, Troydon's production skills
have brought him releases on some of the hottest labels in the world,
including a smash release on SF's flagship label Om.  Behind the decks you
can expect a flawless blend of crowd rocking tracks ranging from funk
inspired to dirty techy grinders.  Don't miss SF's premier underground
appearance of one of the hottest up and coming DJ/producers to hit the
scene!

Still Rob G (Om Records, Ankle Breakers)

Rob Grega, A&R kingpin for the esteemed SF-based label Om Records, has a
musical taste that runs the gamut - and a collection that says the same!
His sets are comprised of downtempo, funk, jazz, soul, broken-beat, house,
and minimal tech at any given performance. As a music compiler at Om, Rob
gets his hands on some of the newest, fresh-out-the-studio productions out
there today.  Regularly experimenting with this music in his sets, he is one
of the most up-to-date DJ's on the block.  

Homero Espinosa (Yerba Buena Discos, Control, Detour) -- Special Old School
Set!

Homero Espinosa began spinning records as DJ Huey in the Bay Area in the
early 90's, quickly finding a niche in the underground rave scene.  He has
since dropped the DJ Huey moniker and founded Yerba Buena Discos, showcasing
his own production along with other serious local SF talent.  YBD has been
charted by legends like DJ Sneak, and Homero's production appeared on Mark
Farina's most recent Ministry of Sound mixed CD.  Behind the 1s and 2's
Homero represents the SF sound well, with recent guest spots across the US.
Watch closely this night...you might catch a glimpse of DJ Huey coming out
of hiding!

Plus:

Andrew Phelan & Origami (Prismatic, Drop Music, So Sound)

Eric Sharp (Rock It Science)

Jimmy B. (Green Gorilla Lounge, rxfx)

Greg Yuen (Motion, Hawt, Primal)

Greg Logan (Motion, Hawt)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] beer favorites?

I like beer, but I don't like getting drunk or hung over on beer.

So when I'm out and about and in a beery mood, I usually go with a  
good stout.  Guinness is always a good choice and is pretty  
ubiquitous, so that's what I usually get.  But I'm always up to try  
new kinds.

The advantage being:  Not only do I just like them better than  
lighter beers; but (getting back to my initial point) when you're  
drinking a nice thick stout, no one thinks you're a killjoy when you  
nurse it along for a good while.  It's just too thick to drink  
quickly anyway.  So I can still go and be beery and sociable, but  
actually wind up drinking much less and not getting drunk or hung over.


cya,
john

Subject: [sfraves] MLWRs: January/ Feb 2007

Like said... i need to like mondo reactivate my reactivity on here again..
so let's start things off w/ my WR for Jan since that's when i kinda
stopped posting 'cause i was goin' through like all kindsa yucky upstairs
& didn't have the  <3 or motivation to like really yeah.. as lame as it
sounds... I dunno if it's a writters thing or what.. but i'm back again :)
YAAAAY!  Hello 2Day!  I promise i won't make this like 10 million pages
long, but give my best summary of like each event & stuff :)
------
In January.. the only event i went to was Evil Breaks: Dirty @ Fat City! 
I remember on the way there, I was on BART w/ these group of people
dressed up & they wre kinda lost & didn't know what stop to get off, so i
helped then! Anywaze... it was a Groovy night!!!  It was Awesome kickin'
it w/ FFS & i kept teasing him calling him General Midi. LoL!  Needless to
say his set ROCKED!!!  I'm always happy to see him & Groovy hard to his
Yummy Choonz!!  Fine Young Cannables.. his set rocked to!  Wait.. i mean..
Fine Cut Bodies, right???  Oooh... & Lobudg... they wre YUmmy too!!!  Like
from memory... I recall the sets being (by order of DJs mentioned
a;lready) Buzzy Electric, Smooth Groovy, & Crazy Mad wooohooo!!  When
MODdie opened up, i remember, he threw down hard for an opening set, went
housey a bit, & threw in like 2 80s tracks that night.. So YUm!!  The rest
of the EB Ressies threw down Crazy to that the whole club was Illin'! 
Ambiant Mafia had the side room & man... it was fuckin' Crazy in there!! 
There wwere a few DJs who like played these strait mellow hip hop/ trip
hop/ down tempo sets that had me just Groovin' hard on well.. it's hard
getting down on carpet like that.. but managable!  Oh yeah... this was the
night that i started wearing a Cape!  So Fun!!!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Cross Fading or Volume Controlling?


On Mon, 18 Jun 2007, D D wrote:
-&e->What do yall use to mix? I keep getting different responses from 
-&e->people about this. I was wondering what everyone on here thought.

Level faders work better than cross faders for bringing stuff in, and 
fading stuff out.  Your basic mixing should be going on here.  The 
cleanest, smoothest DJs usually bring in one channel with the fader while 
starting to roll off the EQ on the "already playing" record to start 
taking it out as they approach equivalent volume.

Crossfaders are good for slamming between the two channels, cutting, etc.  
Your chaotic spazzery should go on here.  Note, there are so many 
crossfaders out there, with anywhere from a 6db dip in the crossfader to 
no dip at all in the crossfader, and travel of all varieties.  They're 
also usually the first thing to break.  Relying on them is a not-so-good 
idea.

The comments about using the EQs to mix are useful, but I've been on this 
kick lately where I am getting away from using them when possible.  If you 
go back to the tapes from the early 90s, they didn't *have* per channel 
EQs in most cases... and in many cases the stuff just sounded better.  The 
cheap fixed freq EQs used on most mixer channel EQs don't sound all that 
good, and heavy cutting of the bass isn't the best thing to do to get two 
records to play along nicely (of course it works better than getting bass 
soup, but in most cases there's another way... waiting for a break, using 
a tool record, etc to get those two things butted up nicely).

One of the funnest things about DJing is never knowing what you're gonna 
get when you get to a booking.  I remember one time, Siphon and I showed 
up at a house party (paid booking I think, it was kinda funny) with a 
Realistic 2 channel mixer and 1 Belt drive deck and a 1200.  We followed a 
really bad wedding DJ level skills dude, with a tagteam breaks set.  It 
wasn't ninja clean, but being able to rock it given any set of tools goes 
a lot further than clearing the dancefloor and grumbling about the mixer 
not being what you use at home.  The only way to learn to do that is get a 
chance to play on every kind of setup you can, even if it "sucks".

There's something kinda almost fun about doing your best on what you're 
given and still managing to sound like yourself without the effects, eqs, 
scratch faders, gains, rotary levels, beatkeeper (ROFL), per channel level 
meters, good (or even "seperate") monitors, effects, kaos pads, filters, 
headphone cue/master mix knob, etc that we tend to get hooked on.  Hell, I 
was only playing bug parties till about 2001, but even then it wasn't 
uncommon to walk up to the decks and be eye to eye with a pre-historic 
Rane mp-24 (they were many a sound company's choice, because the very 
simple gain structure and EQ sounded great out of enormous sound systems 
and made it virtually impossible for DJs to distort within the mixer or 
present ludicrously high levels).

Nothing says "pwned" like following a DJ who is whining about the gear as 
an excuse for a bad set and wiping the floor with their ass.  Extra points 
if you're drinking a 40oz or smoking a blunt while you do it.  And oh, 
have fun.  People can hear fun coming through.

MIME-Version: 1.0

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Cross Fading or Volume Controlling?


--- AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> wrote a bunch of stuff,
including:


> There's something kinda almost fun about doing your
> best on what you're 
> given and still managing to sound like yourself
> without the effects, eqs, 
> scratch faders, gains, rotary levels, beatkeeper
> (ROFL), per channel level 
> meters, good (or even "seperate") monitors, effects,
> kaos pads, filters, 
> headphone cue/master mix knob, etc that we tend to
> get hooked on...

Amen, brother!

For the longest time, my home setup consisted of two
plasticer-than-plastic belt-drive turntables that I
got for about $8 each at a Salvation Army store, a
pair of Radio Shack needles, a Gemini PMX-15 Scratch
Master mixer, and the whole thing ran through my 1976
Sony tuner and a pair of self-refurbished speakers. 
Now, that setup drove me absolutely insane.  It was
more frustrating than you'd believe.

But -- I'd show up to gigs where they'd have two
1200's and some fairly nice Vestax mixer, and DJ's
would be bitching and whining because there were
Stanton AL-500's on the tonearms instead of Ortofons
and the crossfader didn't have a curve adjustment and
the decks weren't modded to have blue LEDs in them and
how are they supposed to even possibly play a set like
this... And I'd step up and breeze through my set with
no problem at all.

I've long said that any rave DJ worth their salt
should be able to beatmatch bicycle wheels with paper
cones with seweing needles taped to them.  All the
trick equipment in the world won't compensate for you
not taking the time to learn the basics of
beatmatching, track construction, listening to the
breaks, effective fading, etc.

> channel level
> meters, good (or even "seperate") monitors, effects, kaos pads,  
> filters,
> headphone cue/master mix knob, etc that we tend to get hooked on.   
> Hell, I
> was only playing bug parties till about 2001, but even then it wasn't
> uncommon to walk up to the decks and be eye to eye with a pre-historic
> Rane mp-24 (they were many a sound company's choice, because the very
> simple gain structure and EQ sounded great out of enormous sound  
> systems
> and made it virtually impossible for DJs to distort within the  
> mixer or
> present ludicrously high levels).
>
> Nothing says "pwned" like following a DJ who is whining about the  
> gear as
> an excuse for a bad set and wiping the floor with their ass.  Extra  
> points
> if you're drinking a 40oz or smoking a blunt while you do it.  And oh,
> have fun.  People can hear fun coming through.
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Cross Fading or Volume Controlling?

------=_Part_97074_31624643.1182375928465
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed

Content-Disposition: inline

just play only records with strong highs on the 1 beat and you're set :).

On 6/20/07, Philip.X.Diaz <st_indigo@earthlink.net> wrote:
>
> reminds me - one of these days, i've got to do a beat-matched set
> without headphones.
>
> why?  just to do it, of course. :-)
>
>
>
> On Jun 20, 2007, at 12:47 PM, AndyW wrote:
>
> >
> > On Mon, 18 Jun 2007, D D wrote:
> > -&e->What do yall use to mix? I keep getting different responses from
> > -&e->people about this. I was wondering what everyone on here thought.
> >
> > Level faders work better than cross faders for bringing stuff in, and
> > fading stuff out.  Your basic mixing should be going on here.  The
> > cleanest, smoothest DJs usually bring in one channel with the fader
> > while
> > starting to roll off the EQ on the "already playing" record to start
> > taking it out as they approach equivalent volume.
> >
> > Crossfaders are good for slamming between the two channels,
> > cutting, etc.
> > Your chaotic spazzery should go on here.  Note, there are so many
> > crossfaders out there, with anywhere from a 6db dip in the
> > crossfader to
> > no dip at all in the crossfader, and travel of all varieties.  They're
> > also usually the first thing to break.  Relying on them is a not-so-
> > good
> > idea.
> >
> > The comments about using the EQs to mix are useful, but I've been
> > on this
> > kick lately where I am getting away from using them when possible.
> > If you
> > go back to the tapes from the early 90s, they didn't *have* per
> > channel
> > EQs in most cases... and in many cases the stuff just sounded
> > better.  The
> > cheap fixed freq EQs used on most mixer channel EQs don't sound all
> > that
> > good, and heavy cutting of the bass isn't the best thing to do to
> > get two
> > records to play along nicely (of course it works better than
> > getting bass
> > soup, but in most cases there's another way... waiting for a break,
> > using
> > a tool record, etc to get those two things butted up nicely).
> >
> > One of the funnest things about DJing is never knowing what you're
> > gonna
> > get when you get to a booking.  I remember one time, Siphon and I
> > showed
> > up at a house party (paid booking I think, it was kinda funny) with a
> > Realistic 2 channel mixer and 1 Belt drive deck and a 1200.  We
> > followed a
> > really bad wedding DJ level skills dude, with a tagteam breaks
> > set.  It
> > wasn't ninja clean, but being able to rock it given any set of
> > tools goes
> > a lot further than clearing the dancefloor and grumbling about the
> > mixer
> > not being what you use at home.  The only way to learn to do that
> > is get a
> > chance to play on every kind of setup you can, even if it "sucks".
> >
> > There's something kinda almost fun about doing your best on what
> > you're
> > given and still managing to sound like yourself without the
> > effects, eqs,
> > scratch faders, gains, rotary levels, beatkeeper (ROFL), per
> > channel level
> > meters, good (or even "seperate") monitors, effects, kaos pads,
> > filters,
> > headphone cue/master mix knob, etc that we tend to get hooked on.
> > Hell, I
> > was only playing bug parties till about 2001, but even then it wasn't
> > uncommon to walk up to the decks and be eye to eye with a pre-historic
> > Rane mp-24 (they were many a sound company's choice, because the very
> > simple gain structure and EQ sounded great out of enormous sound
> > systems
> > and made it virtually impossible for DJs to distort within the
> > mixer or
> > present ludicrously high levels).
> >
> > Nothing says "pwned" like following a DJ who is whining about the
> > gear as
> > an excuse for a bad set and wiping the floor with their ass.  Extra
> > points
> > if you're drinking a 40oz or smoking a blunt while you do it.  And oh,
> > have fun.  People can hear fun coming through.
> >
> > ---------------------------------------------------------------------
> > To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
> > For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Hello jaded raver friends!  We (Chelsea & Sean) just moved into an awesome
loft space in Alameda, which we have dubbed Bliss Factory Studios.  Please
come join us on July 6 for our housewarming party. We have some great DJs
and live acts lined up, the wonderfully loud DEF sound system, a sweet
rooftop smoking lounge, a bar, plenty of parking, and on top of all that
we're right upstairs from a pinball arcade!  There's no cover charge and
we'll be going from 9pm until late.

Love Chelsea Faith
& Sean Ocean

*************************************************

::::Friday, July 6 2007
::::::::Loftwarming Party at the Bliss Factory

::Music provided by::

Red Stickman (Ambient Mafia)
Compulse (a.k.a. Shazbot)
Caltrop (Tokyo Electric)
Ganucheau (Extra Credit) *Live P.A.
Chel-C Faith (DEF, Bliss Factory) * Live P.A.
Disconnect (DEF, Bliss Factory)

FREE!
9pm until.....?
Cozy East Bay Location
Sound by DEF Audio
Blacklight art by Parallaxia
For more info call 415.289.6886
or RSVP with chelcfaith at gmail dot com

Come early and play pinball at the Lucky Juju vintage pinball arcade right
downstairs from us! 6pm-12am with $10 donation.

**Please don't post this to other lists, but feel free to tell your
friends**  :)

Subject: [sfraves] MLWRs: March - April


Oh yeah... MLWR =  Mondo Late Weekend Reveiws btw ;)  Oh oh oh, yeah like
i realized from the last WR i wrote, this might take a long time to read,
so print out & read when u lunch or something ;)

March was another like not dull month, but I just didn't go out as much
really... my parents like also were away on a 2 week cruise goin' like
around the world or something, & when their gone, i just wanna stay home
as much as possible... it also woulda been kinda hard to go out on the
weekends 'cause it woulda been hard to get home kinda when they ain't home
& i'm like butt fuckin' tired from the night & walking home from the bus
stop in Hercules is just not gonna happen... I also spent most of the
month on the phone almost everyday w/ alota my counselors from school on
when i can go back & start again & getting that school shit sorted!

In March though, i did catch my Hollywood Homies back again in the
Richmond in Rockit Room & they performed w/ Pea Soup again! Oh yeah..
lol.. that night, after RR, I did end up @ BAGG @ Glass Cat :)  LoL...
that was fun 'cause I did hang out w/ Big Bro Chazz & see a few Family
there!!!  I also remember waiting for BART that morning to open was killer
'cause i waited @ Jack In The Box on Mission & actually made friends w/
the workers there & got a free refill on my drink & also got extra fries
;)

http://s131.photobucket.com/albums/p314/OsbyWonka/warnerdrive-BAGG-3-14-07/

Ooooooooooooooh yeah.. there was also the Evil Breaks 3 Year Anniversary @
Whisper that month.. LoL.. on the way there, i made friends w/ this group
of people goin' to Pac Bell Park for the game & lol.. it was fun.. they
were fun!  But oh my gosh.. ED 3 YR.. oooooooooh... Whisper was fuckin'
ALIVE that night!!  Well wait, like i was there early enough for like
Deekline to do a sound check for the room upstairs.. ooooooh.. he spun
hella Ghetto Tech & I was in Heaven!!  Anywaze, yeah, the vibe that night
was Dope!!! Komega played a live techno/ breaks set, Sticky & Rafiq
ooooh.. all the DJs played yummy shit... I swear i lost 10- pounds that
night dancing my ass off!!!  After, went to an after party & didn't get
home 'til the next day in the early afternoon :)  So Fun!  Oh yeah.. & the
vibe @ the club.. soooo off the hook like totally mondo man!!!

http://s203.photobucket.com/albums/aa170/osbyjamz/EB3YR33007/
-- 

Now the Loco of Spring time fun came in April!  Things started off in a
big way w/ BUNNYJAM 2007!!!!  NeonBunny, who throws it, like has been
asking me for yeeeeears to go check it out & stuff, but there was always
another event that i went to on the same night BJ would go down!  But
there year, i made it & I'm sooooo glad that i did!!  It was help @ Porn
Palace this year & ooh my gosh.. so much fun!!  Like I went early & helped
out, then when the party got into full swing & started.... my 1st duty was
to be a human catcher.. 'cause people who showed up to BJ were wither full
bunny, 1/2 bunny, or no bunny... so it was my job to catch the humans in a
net, bring them to the Bunnification Modification Station, & the Bunny
Modifers would make the Human into a bunny!!! :)

I just gotta say, i don't know why i waited so fuckikn' long to go to
BunnyJam!!!  I swear.. this annual event is sooo FUN!!!  The music is all
like Breaks, Techno, Electro, Blue Grass, Folk, Rock, House, Disco, 80's,
just everything Yummy!!  I even heard a jungle set in 1 of the rooms! 
There wre 3 rooms of music!  All kinds of Bunnies were there: Sexy,
Playboy, Strippers, Doctor, Nurse, Hobo, Geek, Hippy, Clown, Monster,
Leather, oh my goodness man... all kindsa Bunnies!!!  There were even
Carrots & Girrafes @ the party!  At like some point during the night, I
gave a Bunny Puppet show in the puppet room! Oooh.. & lemme tell you,
there were heeeeeeella horny bunnies!!  I saw alota thumpin, humpin, &
bumpin goin' on!!  Hello 2day!

I also spent some time @ Anu that night 'cause it was also Still Doin
it... the jungle monthly they have there!  Pretty much all the residents
were on the decks that night & ooooooh... so much fun dancing there & just
seein' my Jungle Familia!  Anywaze... after we striked Sunday Morn & the
Chinese guy workin' @ All Star Donuts kinda got well... annoyed with me
just sitting there drinking coffee, i kinda took off & started like just
walking!  Then the gas tanker dude @ Shell on 5th & Folsum like he worked
graveyard & wasn't sure if he was actually seein' a Easter Bunny actaully
walking up the street or just a normal person (I totally forgot i had my
bunny face & ears on still).. then we ended up hangin out for like 45
mintues while he filled up that station w/ gas & said he'd gimme a ride
ome to Hercules, but his truck was GPSed & stuff... so I just walked down
Folsum & like well.. i ran into a crack head from Chicago who was lost or
something.. so we hung out until bart opened up... I even ran into Big J
from Butter @ some point that morning :)

http://s203.photobucket.com/albums/aa170/osbyjamz/bunnyjamSDI-4-7-07/

The next weekend, Friday, was the Yuri 40 Yrs ago Flight Anniversary
Cel... well.. the Rave @ Nasa :)  that night was soooooo fun!!  I
seriously wasn't expecting to go, honestly, but i got a call from the
producer of :codeTV & he wanted to do segments @ the party... so me,
Bruce, the other Camera person, Veronica, went!  I have to say, it was
soooo Dope partying down in a fuckin' hanger @ fuckin' NASA... Musically,
it was alota Breaks, house, down Tempo, trip hop, & dub step!  In the VIP
rooms up stairs, there were NASA officials, astronuats, FOOD!, oooh...
Chocolate, & this space suit from that space place in Berkley hills,
what's it called again?  The Unimog was Dope!!  Like when the party was @
peak, there was probably over like 1500-2000 people there!  Unfortunately,
the party ended 2 hours ahead of schedule 'cause of "the rain".. i mean..
it was a hella light drizzle, but "NASA officials were scared of a
electrical shortage" yada yada yada!  It was all pretty conspericy (sp) as
to who really shut down the party & there was even a fist fight between 2
dudes in the crew.  Anywaze, after NASA, we packed up & went to an
afterparty down the street & chilled there for a while, ate food, drank,
socialized w/ more Awesome People, saw hella naked people, then went home

The next night, see, like i mean.. i just started my new class & juat got
back in school again & i was kinda set on doing homework that day/night
(since i also just got back like from the NASA after party @ like 10AM),
so i planned on staying in Toooooooooooootally!  Anywaze, i get this call
from Unka telling me that we're goin' to Evil Breaks @ Jelly's!  Heeeeello
2Day.. i was hella buggin' 'cause well.. YAAY, i mean.. i didn't get to
finish my homework, but it was sooo FUN & I got down & DIRTY!!!!  All the
DJs rocked it ofcourse & Kid Blue & BLIM played their yummy sets & music!!
I mean... SubScience even make it more Yummy 'cause they had the Jungle in
the back patio place & ooooh... so Groovy, So Dope!! I just like remember
like it was a mondo fight for me to like decide what room to stay in
'cause they were both sooo YUMMY!!!  It was Awesome 'cause alota more
Familia showed up as the night went on & we jsut fuckin' brocked outon the
dance floor man!!!  I knowq there was a dub step event that night @ Club 6
& alota people from there like came to Jellys!! But yeah... Groovy, Yummy,
So Dope!!  Loved It!

http://s203.photobucket.com/albums/aa170/osbyjamz/evilbreaksdirty41407/

ok... so the next friday after that was 4-20!  A few of us got together w/
Unka in this Sushi joint in Oakland by the lake for her Bday!! 
YAAAAAAAAY... & SO YUMMY!!!  Then after, we went to OW for their 1st
shindig in liike forever... Hello 2Day.. it was soooooooo damn fuckin'
Good to be home again!!!  It was Pretty Ill 'cause i mean.. Music was all
TEchno Electro Breaks & Proggy Yada yada in th3 main room & in the side
room it was all like Breaks Jungle & hmmm.. alota Experimental Electric
Hippy stuff!!  WOW!!!  It was nice being w/ Familia that night & seein
familiar faces aaaaaall night long & like i said, being home again!  Small
crowd for OW, but so much damn energy, Yummy vibes, & just WOW!!!

http://s203.photobucket.com/albums/aa170/osbyjamz/evilbreaksdirty41407/

i also went  to a Birthday party @ a comic book store in the City this
month for Chris & SuzyTek... from the Dub Step Familia:)  No music, just
alota drunk, snacks, Carot Cake, & ooooooh.. it was such a good night :) 
So like what happen was b4 i even got to the City, like when i hoped on
the bus, an old Homie from while back pops up & told me he was in jail for
like 8-9 months, jsut got released, & had no where to go... So he ended up
taggin' along w/ me & came to the bday party in the comic book store too
w/ me!  It was kinda funny 'cause well.. him & me together, his name is
Giovani btw, are like both kindsa intense... he's was the creepy WTF & i
guess i'm the more hyper Hello 2day... & all the Homies kinda got freaked
out by him... LoL.. Hello 2Day :P

http://s131.photobucket.com/albums/p314/OsbyWonka/isetopebday4-25-07/


ok.. so i think that's it for March & April :n)


Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

In April I was struck down with spinal meningitis. Nearly killed me  
There was one of those "should we pull the cord" moments.

My partner decided not to so here I am: after 2 1/2 months in  
hospital; diminished hearing and sight; and, most important, loss of  
20 lbs muscle and the ability to walk...for now. Need much PT, I hear  
a year, to walk again:(

So I'll get about in a wheelchair and lower my decks to spin. Maybe I  
can dance in my chair?:)

LOVE,

----- Original Message ----
From: Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org>
To: SFRaves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Friday, June 22, 2007 2:18:09 PM
Subject: [sfraves] SPINAL INVASION


In April I was struck down with spinal meningitis. Nearly killed me  
There was one of those "should we pull the cord" moments.

My partner decided not to so here I am: after 2 1/2 months in  
hospital; diminished hearing and sight; and, most important, loss of  
20 lbs muscle and the ability to walk...for now. Need much PT, I hear  
a year, to walk again:(

So I'll get about in a wheelchair and lower my decks to spin. Maybe I  
can dance in my chair?:)

LOVE,
APOLLO



apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No wonder kids grow up crazy," the midget says. "A cat's cradle is  
nothing but a bunch of X's between somebody's hands, and little kids  
look and look and look at all those X's..."
"And?"
"No damn cat, and no damn cradle."
-Kurt Vonnegut

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Dear Apollo,

I have been a member of this list for about a year but have never posted.  =
I grew up in Salinas and spent my high school and early college days raving=
 in San Fran (91-95).  I am now a young adult of 32.  I moved to Mammoth La=
kes after graduating from USC in 98 and became an avid skier, rock climber,=
 etc.  Three years ago, I broke my back skiing here at Mammoth and just wen=
t through my third surgery at UCSF 7 weeks ago.  I joined SF-Raves to keep =
up with my old passion as Mammoth is almost completely lacking in our favor=
ite music (a few super secret full moon parties now and then.)  Anyway,  I =
just spent 6 weeks in bed for 22 hours per day.  I completely empathize wit=
h what you are going through!!!  I snuck away 2 years ago to the "Power to =
the Peaceful" 9/11 after hours in SF.  I could barely  walk but somehow pul=
led out the strength to dance the night away until 4am.  The secret lies wi=
thin.  The soul is  more powerful than the body.  The gifts and lessons we =
learn from being struck down are infinitely divine.  You may learn that you=
 are an artist, love reading or you may just grow to savor every single exp=
erience infinitely more.  I look forward to dancing with you, Apollo, in a =
year when our backs our healed, the physical therapy is behind us and we ar=
e up on our feet again ;).....

Much love from the High Sierra,
Christina
