Laptop running Traktor!

[Synch] button for stands Paul Oakenfold mode.


Speaking of Paul...

After Die Maschinen Saturday I got asked by somebody "Paul Oakenfold?  
You heard of him?"

"Ya"

"Is he Industrial?"

"What?"

"His music, is it Industrial?"

"Dude.  That's Techno."

Now, anyone who has heard me bitch about recent "industrial" music 
releases will understand why this conversation is rather funny.  'have I 
heard of Oakenfold though...  that made me label him "Douchebag".

Philip.X.Diaz wrote:
> reminds me - one of these days, i've got to do a beat-matched set 
> without headphones.
>
> why?  just to do it, of course. :-)
>
>
>
> On Jun 20, 2007, at 12:47 PM, AndyW wrote:
>
>>
>> On Mon, 18 Jun 2007, D D wrote:
>> -&e->What do yall use to mix? I keep getting different responses from
>> -&e->people about this. I was wondering what everyone on here thought.
>>
>> Level faders work better than cross faders for bringing stuff in, and
>> fading stuff out.  Your basic mixing should be going on here.  The
>> cleanest, smoothest DJs usually bring in one channel with the fader 
>> while
>> starting to roll off the EQ on the "already playing" record to start
>> taking it out as they approach equivalent volume.
>>
>> Crossfaders are good for slamming between the two channels, cutting, 
>> etc.
>> Your chaotic spazzery should go on here.  Note, there are so many
>> crossfaders out there, with anywhere from a 6db dip in the crossfader to
>> no dip at all in the crossfader, and travel of all varieties.  They're
>> also usually the first thing to break.  Relying on them is a not-so-good
>> idea.
>>
>> The comments about using the EQs to mix are useful, but I've been on 
>> this
>> kick lately where I am getting away from using them when possible.  
>> If you
>> go back to the tapes from the early 90s, they didn't *have* per channel
>> EQs in most cases... and in many cases the stuff just sounded 
>> better.  The
>> cheap fixed freq EQs used on most mixer channel EQs don't sound all that
>> good, and heavy cutting of the bass isn't the best thing to do to get 
>> two
>> records to play along nicely (of course it works better than getting 
>> bass
>> soup, but in most cases there's another way... waiting for a break, 
>> using
>> a tool record, etc to get those two things butted up nicely).
>>
>> One of the funnest things about DJing is never knowing what you're gonna
>> get when you get to a booking.  I remember one time, Siphon and I showed
>> up at a house party (paid booking I think, it was kinda funny) with a
>> Realistic 2 channel mixer and 1 Belt drive deck and a 1200.  We 
>> followed a
>> really bad wedding DJ level skills dude, with a tagteam breaks set.  It
>> wasn't ninja clean, but being able to rock it given any set of tools 
>> goes
>> a lot further than clearing the dancefloor and grumbling about the mixer
>> not being what you use at home.  The only way to learn to do that is 
>> get a
>> chance to play on every kind of setup you can, even if it "sucks".
>>
>> There's something kinda almost fun about doing your best on what you're
>> given and still managing to sound like yourself without the effects, 
>> eqs,
>> scratch faders, gains, rotary levels, beatkeeper (ROFL), per channel 
>> level
>> meters, good (or even "seperate") monitors, effects, kaos pads, filters,
>> headphone cue/master mix knob, etc that we tend to get hooked on.  
>> Hell, I
>> was only playing bug parties till about 2001, but even then it wasn't
>> uncommon to walk up to the decks and be eye to eye with a pre-historic
>> Rane mp-24 (they were many a sound company's choice, because the very
>> simple gain structure and EQ sounded great out of enormous sound systems
>> and made it virtually impossible for DJs to distort within the mixer or
>> present ludicrously high levels).
>>
>> Nothing says "pwned" like following a DJ who is whining about the 
>> gear as
>> an excuse for a bad set and wiping the floor with their ass.  Extra 
>> points
>> if you're drinking a 40oz or smoking a blunt while you do it.  And oh,
>> have fun.  People can hear fun coming through.
>>
>> ---------------------------------------------------------------------
>> To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
>> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
>>

and me from you loving ravers during my hospitalization.  I'm feeling  
like a real weight around the world's neck right now.  Your comments  
made me realize that I have people to live for.

nothing but a bunch of X's between somebody's hands, and little kids  
look and look and look at all those X's..."

the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."

On Mon, Jun 25, 2007 at 02:58:06PM -0700, tsheets@saturn5.com wrote:
>
>
>Speaking of DJ tech talk.
>
>Check out this dirt cheap $200 Behringer laptop DJ controller.  I mean,
>for that price, just buy it for the toy value.  It even includes a copy
>of Tractor LE:
>
>http://www.behringer.com/BCD3000/index.cfm?lang=eng

Behringer doesn't have the best reputation, and that controller in
particular has gotten less than optimal reviews in forums and magazines.

Better controllers (in no particular order):

Controllers from Faderfox (http://www.faderfox.com)
M-Audio (http://www.m-audio.com):
    * Trigger Finger
    * X-Session Pro
    * Connectiv
Kontrol-DJ (http://www.kontrol-dj.com/):
Novation Music (http://www.novationmusic.com/):
    * Remote SL Zero (or one of the bigger models w/ keys)
Allen & Heath X:One 3D
Korg Zero8

and there are others...

To get some hands on experience and talk shop, you should stop by
robotspeak on haight:
http://www.robotspeak.com/

Checking Traktor[1] and Ableton Live[2] forums is also a good idea.
The Kontrol DJ[3] site above has some decent forum chatter from time
to time, and there is also the Ableton Live DJ[4] forum that has
forums dedicated to controllers and an Ableton Live Wiki[5]
that probably has some controller infos.

[1] http://www.native-instruments.com/index.php?id=forum_us
[2] http://www.ableton.com/forum/index.php
[3] http://kontrolprodj.com/component/option,com_wrapper/Itemid,23/
[4] http://www.abletonlivedj.com/
[5] http://www.teragon.org/wiki/index.php?title=Main_Page

If you happen to be using live, there is also a local (bay area) list
that doesn't get much traffic that you can join:
https://www.quicklists.net/mailman/listinfo/baablive

-- 
Holt Sorenson
hso@hsomusic.com
http://www.hsomusic.com/

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Cross Fading or Volume Controlling?



Okay, well, just for the record...

I currently own 3 peices of Behringer gear.. a slider MIDI controller,
a small mixer, and a multiband compression box.  All of these are rock
solid.  I use them in the studio, take them to gigs, etc, and I have
yet to have a single problem.

I own one little Vestax mixer and it is a peice of crap.  the cue bleeds
right through to the main mix.  

You can dismiss Behringer all you want on features.  But I am quite happy
with the quality and especially value of their gear.

-troy

Yeah, but I don't have just a laptop. My rig is
out-of-control big, right now I'm using matched laptops and
midi controllers for video. I've used some really cool MIDI
controllers, but it just seems the DJ-oriented ones (with jog
wheels) are unecessarily large, well for me they are.

I'd love a simplified compact model with jog wheels where I
could fit 2 in my existing VJ coffin. But I don't think that's
gonna happen for a long while.

-terry

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Internet Radio "Day of Silence"

FWIW, when I was at Live365.com I had the displeasure of meeting with their chief counsel Steve marks in the RIAA's DC offices.  This was maybe seven years ago now. It was clear then that the RIAA was interested in killing Internet radio.  At that time their angle was "stream ripping" which in case you don't know is the (possibly illegal) recording of an Internet streaming broadcast.

The RIAA wants to kill Internet radio for one simple reason: control.  They want to be able to control what music people hear, so they can influence what they buy.  With terrestrial (AM/FM) radio the recorning industry felt they had lost control of their content, allowing broadcasting companies such as ClearChannel to benefit from their properties without paying the RIAA.  The law in the U.S. requires radio stations to pay only the songwriter not the performing artists, hence the radio stations pay ASCAP/BMI but not the RIAA.

The RIAA has been determined from day one not to let the same scenario happen with respect to Internet radio, and hence has sought ways to force Internet radio to pay even when AM/FM broadcasters wouldn't have to.  And the rates set where 

The punch line to the whole story is the establishment of SoundExchange, originally as part of the RIAA and now operating as a "independent" entity (the RIAA and its member companies still control a large group of SX board seats).  SoundExchange is the entity that collects and "distributes" the money from the various Internet radio broadcasters and satellite boradcasters to the labels and artists supposedly under a 50/50 split.  

The thing is, that really something like 70% the money distributed is distributed to the labels and only 30% goes to the artists, because SX claims they can't find many of the artists in order to pay them (http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20060921/192446.shtml) Former SX counsel told me that they only find and pay 40% of the artists, while (of course) they *can* find the labels and pay them over 90% of the time.  

Many artists getting Internet play just aren't getting paid at all.  But SoundExchange collects money for these broadcasts anyway and holds it for three years when it "escheats" to SX to offset costs.  Note that since the labels get the bulk of the distributions from SX, that decreasing SX's costs benefits the labels most.  There there are those "administrative fees" (http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20070607/092053.shtml) that the broadcasters somehow forgot to oppose, but that's another story I guess.

The problem is that the Internet radio business is just isn't that great of a business.  None of these operations are making much money and certainly not enough to pay these new rates.  In the end many may be forced to shut down and therefore will pay SX zero.  And yet the head of SoundExchange and the RIAA continues to promote the higher rates.  Why? Because control over what people hear is more important than the measily revenues they are getting from Internet radio today.  Consider how much the industry has paid in payola and "independent marketing" fees (http://www.theregister.co.uk/2004/10/22/spitzer_targets_musiclabels/ and http://www.daveyd.com/lettertofcc.html)

The RIAA wants to silence independent Internet radio once and for all.  That's been the agenda since the founding of SoundExchange and has been obvious since the early demands for ridiculous and even impossible listener reporting requirements (http://www.futureofmusic.org/news/CARPreplycomments.cfm)  

Why? They don't want you to be able to choose from 50 channels of techno, Tuvan throat singing, or the latest Bulgarian death metal whenever you want.  Too much choice makes it much harder to get the consumer's attention and that means higher marketing costs and lower profits.

So while I support the broadcasters, I feel that a day (or week, or month, etc.) of silence is just exactly what the RIAA wants.   Why give them what they want?  Instead of a day of silence, how about a day of music sharing links to broadcasts (for example) that originate outside the U.S. and do not pay the RIAA or SX?

Here's some non-RIAA funding radio from Germany for example: http://www.infectedradio.com/content/

Peace,

Peter

P.S. Apollo, keep the fedora, lose the scarf. ;)

Subject: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

Sometimes Techno mixes sound to be off measure wise to
me. I can do the math on a single, and sometimes they
seem "normal" and sometimes odd... Like high-hats
coming in on the down beats, kicks later, and patterns
that seem off. Whats the deal? I know there is numbers
difference betroit6 Detroit/Chicago vs German/Euro

Enlighten me please....

Part of this goes back to a time when I had Mattski
play at our room at the first Mega-Buzz... One of
biggest systems I had ever played on. It was so loud,
the reverb off the walls so gnarly, and I was so
stoked to have pulled off the main room at home bass
for the $2000 budget I was given... Anyhow, at times I
seriously could not tell if it was a train wreck or
perfectly ordered kaos. I believe it was the latter. I
just remember hard beats with an off shuffle, with one
elastic tweaker sound on each track that just made it
all melt into craziness.

E

Subject: [sfraves] [BSP] Filter :: this SAT:: Joel Mull + Seth Troxler

On Saturday June 30, Sweden's Joel Mull makes a long-awaited return to
the Bay Area. Also, don't miss a chance to catch Detroit's reputed
party DJ par-excellence Seth Troxler before he moves to Berlin.

Take advantage of limited $10 entry before 10:30 PM.
RSVP to info@babd.org

Filter.SF.1.3
Saturday June 30, 2007
10 PM till 4:00 AM

Fat City
314 11th Street at Folsom, S.F.

Filter.SF.1.3 features Joel Mull [Railyard Recordings/Inside Records,
Stockholm] and Seth Troxler [BerettaMusic, Detroit]

Plus Filter residents: Kontakt, Saya and Solekandi

Joel Mull [Railyard Recordings, Inside Records, Stockholm]:
Mull, together with contemporary, Adam Beyer, has entered into the top
ranks of techno Djs in the world for his superior technical skill,
melodic sensibility and trendsetting production. With over 40 releases
and apperances on another several dozen compilations - including John
Digweed's Fabric 20 - Mull has established staying power in a sea of
ever-changing electronic music trends.

More info:
http://www.insiderecords.net/
http://www.railyardrecordings.com/


Seth Troxler [BerettaMusic, Detroit]:
With a DJ style ranging from jazz & rare groove to minimal funk &
percussive techno, Troxler, together with Detroit fellows Ryan Crosson
and Lee Curtiss, has helped define the new face of Detroit techno.
Seth's steady stream of releases have earned kudos for their
syncopated percussive elements, dark basslines and vocal elements.

More info:
http://www.berettamusic.com


-- 
filter.sf.all night techno monthlies
every last saturday
fat city, san francisco
www.myspace.com/filtersf

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Is EVERYBODY on coke now? WTF?

I think it's just due to the drop in prices (I've seen blow go for $30/gram of late!), a shift in the focus of the city's party people from happy huggy raving to dirty techy parties, and, like JC says, a not-exactly-celebratory near-decade in our country's history.

I met some australians that were used to $200+ prices per gram in their native land.  They bought 6 or 8 grams here, out of sheer novelty- and subsequently went batshit.

Personally, I hate the shit.  I just wish it were easier for people to turn away.  There's a reason they call it "candy".  That said, I don't like E much lately either.  

Or weed.

..so I guess I'm sort of disqualified from the proceedings.
-G

dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
> FWIW, when I was at Live365.com I had the displeasure of meeting with their chief counsel Steve marks in the RIAA's DC offices.  This was maybe seven years ago now. It was clear then that the RIAA was interested in killing Internet radio.  At that time their angle was "stream ripping" which in case you don't know is the (possibly illegal) recording of an Internet streaming broadcast.
>
> The RIAA wants to kill Internet radio for one simple reason: control.  They want to be able to control what music people hear, so they can influence what they buy.  With terrestrial (AM/FM) radio the recorning industry felt they had lost control of their content, allowing broadcasting companies such as ClearChannel to benefit from their properties without paying the RIAA.  The law in the U.S. requires radio stations to pay only the songwriter not the performing artists, hence the radio stations pay ASCAP/BMI but not the RIAA.
>
> The RIAA has been determined from day one not to let the same scenario happen with respect to Internet radio, and hence has sought ways to force Internet radio to pay even when AM/FM broadcasters wouldn't have to.  And the rates set where 
>
> The punch line to the whole story is the establishment of SoundExchange, originally as part of the RIAA and now operating as a "independent" entity (the RIAA and its member companies still control a large group of SX board seats).  SoundExchange is the entity that collects and "distributes" the money from the various Internet radio broadcasters and satellite boradcasters to the labels and artists supposedly under a 50/50 split.  
>
> The thing is, that really something like 70% the money distributed is distributed to the labels and only 30% goes to the artists, because SX claims they can't find many of the artists in order to pay them (http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20060921/192446.shtml) Former SX counsel told me that they only find and pay 40% of the artists, while (of course) they *can* find the labels and pay them over 90% of the time.  
>
> Many artists getting Internet play just aren't getting paid at all.  But SoundExchange collects money for these broadcasts anyway and holds it for three years when it "escheats" to SX to offset costs.  Note that since the labels get the bulk of the distributions from SX, that decreasing SX's costs benefits the labels most.  There there are those "administrative fees" (http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20070607/092053.shtml) that the broadcasters somehow forgot to oppose, but that's another story I guess.
>
> The problem is that the Internet radio business is just isn't that great of a business.  None of these operations are making much money and certainly not enough to pay these new rates.  In the end many may be forced to shut down and therefore will pay SX zero.  And yet the head of SoundExchange and the RIAA continues to promote the higher rates.  Why? Because control over what people hear is more important than the measily revenues they are getting from Internet radio today.  Consider how much the industry has paid in payola and "independent marketing" fees (http://www.theregister.co.uk/2004/10/22/spitzer_targets_musiclabels/ and http://www.daveyd.com/lettertofcc.html)
>
> The RIAA wants to silence independent Internet radio once and for all.  That's been the agenda since the founding of SoundExchange and has been obvious since the early demands for ridiculous and even impossible listener reporting requirements (http://www.futureofmusic.org/news/CARPreplycomments.cfm)  
>
> Why? They don't want you to be able to choose from 50 channels of techno, Tuvan throat singing, or the latest Bulgarian death metal whenever you want.  Too much choice makes it much harder to get the consumer's attention and that means higher marketing costs and lower profits.
>
> So while I support the broadcasters, I feel that a day (or week, or month, etc.) of silence is just exactly what the RIAA wants.   Why give them what they want?  Instead of a day of silence, how about a day of music sharing links to broadcasts (for example) that originate outside the U.S. and do not pay the RIAA or SX?
>
> Here's some non-RIAA funding radio from Germany for example: http://www.infectedradio.com/content/
>
> Peace,
>
> Peter
>
> P.S. Apollo, keep the fedora, lose the scarf. ;) 
>
>

Is it common for raves to have a house dealer set up in back? Some babe was
cutting lines under a little blacklight setup when I went to a rave promoted
on bayraves. It was pretty easy to discrimate who was rolling at that party
and who was on coke.

I'm pretty new to the rave scene, but it's upsetting to see people at a rave
doing an ego-hardening drug. It gave the night a dirty edge (some asshole
borrowed my weed pipe and smoked coke bowls with it, tasted awful
afterward).

It made me feel more inclined to be around candy kids. At least they're
rolling balls, and even if it just involves giving away ugly bracelets, it's
nice to feel empathy at a party. That's why I went.

Coke sucks, I demand molly.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....


On Tue, 26 Jun 2007, Eric Spire wrote:
-&e->Sometimes Techno mixes sound to be off measure wise to
-&e->me. I can do the math on a single, and sometimes they
-&e->seem "normal" and sometimes odd... Like high-hats

ok.

-&e->coming in on the down beats, kicks later, and patterns
-&e->that seem off. Whats the deal? I know there is numbers
-&e->difference betroit6 Detroit/Chicago vs German/Euro

ok.

-&e->Enlighten me please....

ok.

-&e->Part of this goes back to a time when I had Mattski

ah ha!

Think I figured it out...

MATTSKI IS FUCKING INSANE/RETARDED/AHEAD OF HIS TIME/ON ANOTHER PLANE.

He has records that are so incredibly rhythmically nutty, that fall in 
line with a genre usually referred to as "Jack" (usually associated with 
Chicago, but people from Japan to Sweden have released stuff in that 
vibe).  While a few of us in the San Jose techno cabal had a love for this 
(it *is* funky as all hell, and fun to mix, sorta), Mattski and Derek 
Scott could and would play whole sets of this stuff.  Think weird DJ Rush 
stuff, it's something some people just love and others not so much.  It's 
also about twice as hard to mix as something with a more stable count, a 
big part of that genre is setting up swing/shuffle/groove templates that 
are so whack that the snare or hi hats will seem noticably behind.  This 
element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but it's pushed to the 
foreground with Jack.  It's also extra fun to mix with a very minimal 
straighter sounding record (really the only way to get in/out of those 
kinds of records).

Rolling basslines, hypnotic repetition, a penchant for almost cartoony 
accents using bits of voice or quirky synth lines, and snare/hihat stuff 
all over the place.  Just really another direction to explore in breaking 
some of the shackles that bind dance music.  Compounding this, a lot of 
these records are genuinely fuckign weird in other ways and have to be 
thrown on a beat other than the one, have strange-count breaks, etc (I 
would actually put star stickers on these records to avoid grabbing them 
when I literally can't see, which also used to happen to me from time to 
time... I have very light sensitive eyes and a good pass across my face 
from a cyberlight or goldenscan would just cripple me for 20 seconds or 
so).

-&e->play at our room at the first Mega-Buzz... One of
-&e->biggest systems I had ever played on. It was so loud,
-&e->the reverb off the walls so gnarly, and I was so
-&e->stoked to have pulled off the main room at home bass
-&e->for the $2000 budget I was given... Anyhow, at times I
-&e->seriously could not tell if it was a train wreck or
-&e->perfectly ordered kaos. I believe it was the latter. I
-&e->just remember hard beats with an off shuffle, with one
-&e->elastic tweaker sound on each track that just made it
-&e->all melt into craziness.

Exactly!  Sounds like you had an open mind about it, but the sound in that 
place was probably a mess.  And another thing about massives, after a 
couple hours of crap at that volume, your hearing just smears anyway.  
It's why I always used to go for a walk right before a set, just give my 
ears a chance to relax and be fresh.

And to be honest, it's a bear to mix on loud systems, especially with back 
wall reverb or a lack of proper monitors (you can't trust the kick, or 
basslines, or snare or hihats exclusively, the "true 1" depends on the 
record).  If anybody has audio of that Moksha party where Chris Jackson 
and I did a 2x4 set, parts of that were Jackin as all hell and I recall 
both of us were in it pretty good (and we were in a damn good mood, Moksha 
Krooo had set us up with a Schmoke and a Pancake and good monitors and a 
12 pack of the olde Nut Brown... although I recall one deck being on the 
fritz), but given that I don't have that set anywhere... (does anyone?).

Here's a set I did for Neulight that should be sorta what you're talking 
about (at least at the start and finish... the middle is more standard 
fare funky techage):
http://saturn5.com/andy/djandyw-live-neulight.mp3

Lemme know if that's kinda what you meant,
andyw

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

I am NOT a fan of techno that sounds like it is off. In fact, I wanna 
cockslap the producers who make stuff like that for wanking off on their 
gear a bit too hard for their own good.

Dance music should be danceable. Period. If it is "off time" or 
"experimental" it is not "dance music". Unless it's made for those who are 
afflicted with the dreaded "no rhythm" disease. In which case, it makes 
sense.





>From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>
>To: Eric Spire <ericspire@yahoo.com>
>CC: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....
>Date: Wed, 27 Jun 2007 13:51:06 -0700 (PDT)
>
>
>On Tue, 26 Jun 2007, Eric Spire wrote:
>-&e->Sometimes Techno mixes sound to be off measure wise to
>-&e->me. I can do the math on a single, and sometimes they
>-&e->seem "normal" and sometimes odd... Like high-hats
>
>ok.
>
>-&e->coming in on the down beats, kicks later, and patterns
>-&e->that seem off. Whats the deal? I know there is numbers
>-&e->difference betroit6 Detroit/Chicago vs German/Euro
>
>ok.
>
>-&e->Enlighten me please....
>
>ok.
>
>-&e->Part of this goes back to a time when I had Mattski
>
>ah ha!
>
>Think I figured it out...
>
>MATTSKI IS FUCKING INSANE/RETARDED/AHEAD OF HIS TIME/ON ANOTHER PLANE.
>
>He has records that are so incredibly rhythmically nutty, that fall in
>line with a genre usually referred to as "Jack" (usually associated with
>Chicago, but people from Japan to Sweden have released stuff in that
>vibe).  While a few of us in the San Jose techno cabal had a love for this
>(it *is* funky as all hell, and fun to mix, sorta), Mattski and Derek
>Scott could and would play whole sets of this stuff.  Think weird DJ Rush
>stuff, it's something some people just love and others not so much.  It's
>also about twice as hard to mix as something with a more stable count, a
>big part of that genre is setting up swing/shuffle/groove templates that
>are so whack that the snare or hi hats will seem noticably behind.  This
>element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but it's pushed to the
>foreground with Jack.  It's also extra fun to mix with a very minimal
>straighter sounding record (really the only way to get in/out of those
>kinds of records).
>
>Rolling basslines, hypnotic repetition, a penchant for almost cartoony
>accents using bits of voice or quirky synth lines, and snare/hihat stuff
>all over the place.  Just really another direction to explore in breaking
>some of the shackles that bind dance music.  Compounding this, a lot of
>these records are genuinely fuckign weird in other ways and have to be
>thrown on a beat other than the one, have strange-count breaks, etc (I
>would actually put star stickers on these records to avoid grabbing them
>when I literally can't see, which also used to happen to me from time to
>time... I have very light sensitive eyes and a good pass across my face
>from a cyberlight or goldenscan would just cripple me for 20 seconds or
>so).
>
>-&e->play at our room at the first Mega-Buzz... One of
>-&e->biggest systems I had ever played on. It was so loud,
>-&e->the reverb off the walls so gnarly, and I was so
>-&e->stoked to have pulled off the main room at home bass
>-&e->for the $2000 budget I was given... Anyhow, at times I
>-&e->seriously could not tell if it was a train wreck or
>-&e->perfectly ordered kaos. I believe it was the latter. I
>-&e->just remember hard beats with an off shuffle, with one
>-&e->elastic tweaker sound on each track that just made it
>-&e->all melt into craziness.
>
>Exactly!  Sounds like you had an open mind about it, but the sound in that
>place was probably a mess.  And another thing about massives, after a
>couple hours of crap at that volume, your hearing just smears anyway.
>It's why I always used to go for a walk right before a set, just give my
>ears a chance to relax and be fresh.
>
>And to be honest, it's a bear to mix on loud systems, especially with back
>wall reverb or a lack of proper monitors (you can't trust the kick, or
>basslines, or snare or hihats exclusively, the "true 1" depends on the
>record).  If anybody has audio of that Moksha party where Chris Jackson
>and I did a 2x4 set, parts of that were Jackin as all hell and I recall
>both of us were in it pretty good (and we were in a damn good mood, Moksha
>Krooo had set us up with a Schmoke and a Pancake and good monitors and a
>12 pack of the olde Nut Brown... although I recall one deck being on the
>fritz), but given that I don't have that set anywhere... (does anyone?).
>
>Here's a set I did for Neulight that should be sorta what you're talking
>about (at least at the start and finish... the middle is more standard
>fare funky techage):
>http://saturn5.com/andy/djandyw-live-neulight.mp3
>
>Lemme know if that's kinda what you meant,
>andyw
>

>For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

Mind you...all of this music Eric and Andy are talking about IS =20
quantized, ad is most certainly "dance music".  Actually, it's a hell =20=

of a lot more danceable than most shit I hear now-a-days.  The =20
shuffle is heavy, but the tracks are "on time".  They're just swingy =20
and shuffly as all hell.  Which I think sounds funkier than a =20
straight forward "funky" techno track ala Ben Simms/ Samuel L. =20
Sessions etc.  I rarely made a track that didn't have some sort of =20
shuffle or swing to it.  In most case a pretty think shuffle.  =20
Straight 4/4 quantized 1/16  notes sound a bit too "white" to me.  No =20=

soul.  Just straight forward and lame.


CJ

Shuffley music is one thing, but there are some techno tracks I have heard 
that straight up sound OFF. That shit is not cool, danceable, or any more 
funky than anything else. In fact, I find things that sound off time to be 
counter-funk, as it ruins any good, steady groove.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

James Brown may not be "on" all the time, but his music never throws you off 
a solid groove. I am definitely not saying "all techno" has this affilction 
- but there are some records floating around that are just plain 
off-sounding, and they (at least for ME) fuck the flow up of a set if not 
PERFECTLY dropped into place.

As someone who doesn't just like to mix breakbeat after breakbeat (I play 
4x4 and toss in half-time stuff as well), I understand how to quirk out a 
set a bit - but some of my more "off" sounding tracks just plain sound like 
shit if not dropped in the proper context.  Maybe it's just been my 
misfortune and personal experience that I have heard these wack techno 
tracks, and they have sullied the sets I heard them in.

>metronomic perfection.  Anyone can quantize a sequence- few can do what it

>dance music!  Sure isn't "on" all the time though.
>

>body's imperfect, impulsive, freaky movements.
>

>of techno would fade into featureless monotony all too quickly.

> >element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but it's pushed to the

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

Techno refers to the philosophical concept of
technique, a key contributor to the development of IT
and virtual machines (computers).  I think Jacques
Ellul put it best "...when technique enters into every
area of life, including the human [including the
human's music] it ceases to be external to man and
becomes his very substance."

That we see best with dave clarke, who has repeatedly
reminded us that Underground anthems are techno, which
go to a core of the collective desire and transform
electronics (experimental, minimal) into something
inate, a vibe. And thus, techno is the ultimate rebel
music, desireing no more to jack (thieve, mercelessly)
the house, fuck u w/ liquid layers of 303, and get
darker than sweedish anarchy death metal, to build-up
driven melody that sounds so sickly sweet it created a
particular type of scenester - candy.

technique applied to dance music has the goal of
making everyone dance. (which may not be simoltaneous)
And by dance, i mean dance to the music, not the
sexual ego demaning attention which represents the
typical house/club atmosphere. Techno is to lose
oneself, an outter body experience that fucks me up
intellectually, physically, and retrospectively more
so than any substance.

as is written in graffiti of aphex twin's windowlicker
music video (an artist who's technique surpassed the
goal and "warped" it into a cd friendly
post-psychadelia product).

TECHNO IS GOD (really)

much love, Morgan Trueblood, Denizen ConeXus

((anyone got a sharpie))

> understand how to quirk out a 
> set a bit - but some of my more "off" sounding
> tracks just plain sound like 
> shit if not dropped in the proper context.  Maybe
> it's just been my 
> misfortune and personal experience that I have heard
> these wack techno 
> tracks, and they have sullied the sets I heard them
> in.
> 
> 
> >From: georgeC | origami <newstylesound@yahoo.com>

> >
> >I often find the opposite to be true.  If somebody
> refuses to get down to 
> >music that's not dead-on beat, then they've got a
> pretty narrow window to 
> >peer through.  I get some of my most fun moments on
> the dancefloor when 
> >somebody with a musical sense of humor causes me to
> recalibrate my brain a 
> >little to feel their beat.  Especially in techno,
> man- that shit that 
> >tweaks your melon is exactly the point.
> >
> >The true core of a music maker's sound often lies a
> good distance away from 
> >metronomic perfection.  Anyone can quantize a
> sequence- few can do what it 
> >takes to churn people's shit up.  Take James Brown-
> that's some serious 
> >dance music!  Sure isn't "on" all the time though.
> >
> >...and that's why people love to dance to it.  It
> corresponds to your 
> >body's imperfect, impulsive, freaky movements.
> >
> >Plus, without those off-kilter moments, the
> razor-sharp grid that is a lot 
> >of techno would fade into featureless monotony all
> too quickly.
> >
> >(Andy will back me up on that'un)
> >
> >2 pesos,
> >-George

> > >-&e->Sometimes Techno mixes sound to be off
> measure wise to

> high-hats

> > >-&e->coming in on the down beats, kicks later,

> > >-&e->that seem off. Whats the deal? I know there

> German/Euro
> > >

> > >-&e->Enlighten me please....
> > >
> > >ok.
> > >
> > >-&e->Part of this goes back to a time when I had
> Mattski
> > >
> > >ah ha!
> > >
> > >Think I figured it out...
> > >
> > >MATTSKI IS FUCKING INSANE/RETARDED/AHEAD OF HIS
> TIME/ON ANOTHER PLANE.
> > >
> > >He has records that are so incredibly
> rhythmically nutty, that fall in
> > >line with a genre usually referred to as "Jack"
> (usually associated with
> > >Chicago, but people from Japan to Sweden have
> released stuff in that
> > >vibe).  While a few of us in the San Jose techno
> cabal had a love for 
> >this
> > >(it *is* funky as all hell, and fun to mix,
> sorta), Mattski and Derek
> > >Scott could and would play whole sets of this
> stuff.  Think weird DJ Rush
> > >stuff, it's something some people just love and
> others not so much.  It's
> > >also about twice as hard to mix as something with
> a more stable count, a
> > >big part of that genre is setting up
> swing/shuffle/groove templates that
> > >are so whack that the snare or hi hats will seem
> noticably behind.  This
> > >element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but
> it's pushed to the
> > >foreground with Jack.  It's also extra fun to mix
> with a very minimal
> > >straighter sounding record (really the only way
> to get in/out of those
> > >kinds of records).
> > >
> > >Rolling basslines, hypnotic repetition, a
> penchant for almost cartoony
> > >accents using bits of voice or quirky synth
> lines, and snare/hihat stuff
> > >all over the place.  Just really another
> direction to explore in breaking
> > >some of the shackles that bind dance music. 
> Compounding this, a lot of
> > >these records are genuinely fuckign weird in
> other ways and have to be
> > >thrown on a beat other than the one, have
> strange-count breaks, etc (I
> > >would actually put star stickers on these records
> to avoid grabbing them
> > >when I literally can't see, which also used to
> happen to me from time to
> > >time... I have very light sensitive eyes and a
> good pass across my face
> > >from a cyberlight or goldenscan would just
> cripple me for 20 seconds or
> > >so).
> > >
> > >-&e->play at our room at the first Mega-Buzz...
> One of
> > >-&e->biggest systems I had ever played on. It was
> so loud,
> > >-&e->the reverb off the walls so gnarly, and I
> was so
> > >-&e->stoked to have pulled off the main room at
> home bass
> > >-&e->for the $2000 budget I was given... Anyhow,
> at times I
> > >-&e->seriously could not tell if it was a train
> wreck or
> > >-&e->perfectly ordered kaos. I believe it was the
> latter. I
> > >-&e->just remember hard beats with an off
> shuffle, with one
>

>From: Morgan McCloud <mogopolis2000@yahoo.com>

>Techno refers to the philosophical concept of
>technique, a key contributor to the development of IT
>and virtual machines (computers).  I think Jacques
>Ellul put it best "...when technique enters into every
>area of life, including the human [including the
>human's music] it ceases to be external to man and
>becomes his very substance."
>
>That we see best with dave clarke, who has repeatedly
>reminded us that Underground anthems are techno, which
>go to a core of the collective desire and transform
>electronics (experimental, minimal) into something
>inate, a vibe. And thus, techno is the ultimate rebel
>music, desireing no more to jack (thieve, mercelessly)
>the house, fuck u w/ liquid layers of 303, and get
>darker than sweedish anarchy death metal, to build-up
>driven melody that sounds so sickly sweet it created a
>particular type of scenester - candy.
>
>technique applied to dance music has the goal of
>making everyone dance. (which may not be simoltaneous)
>And by dance, i mean dance to the music, not the
>sexual ego demaning attention which represents the
>typical house/club atmosphere. Techno is to lose
>oneself, an outter body experience that fucks me up
>intellectually, physically, and retrospectively more
>so than any substance.
>
>as is written in graffiti of aphex twin's windowlicker
>music video (an artist who's technique surpassed the
>goal and "warped" it into a cd friendly
>post-psychadelia product).
>
>TECHNO IS GOD (really)
>
>much love, Morgan Trueblood, Denizen ConeXus
>
>((anyone got a sharpie))
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....


On Wed, 27 Jun 2007, Van Mundegaarde wrote:
-&e->I am NOT a fan of techno that sounds like it is off. In fact, I wanna
-&e->cockslap the producers who make stuff like that for wanking off on their
-&e->gear a bit too hard for their own good.

Well, I gave an example of what I was talking about... not sure if you're 
referring specifically to that or some piece of alien math rock or what... 
if someone can find that set I was referring to by me and Chris @ Moksha, 
the whole room (househeads, breakshead, etc) was going apeshit... plenty 
of SFravers were there, it went off despite some deep shuffled jack-style 
stuff.  Ironically, the DJ after us played "straighter" Belgian/German 
minimal style techno and lost most of the dance floor in short order.  
Ooops, looks like someone left out the "fun" in that set, bing bong!  EZ 
to dance to, sure, but why...

Referring to the original post from Eric, Mattski is a damn good DJ, one 
of the best in town.  He can play house that will totally fucking drop 
science on your head.  He can also drop some techno that is pretty 
fucking out there with this wickedly swung groove.  I support him as an 
artist, he's brave and soulful and visceral and fun and he's had me 
dancing like my feet are on fire on many occasions.

-&e->Dance music should be danceable. Period. If it is "off time" or
-&e->"experimental" it is not "dance music". Unless it's made for those who are
-&e->afflicted with the dreaded "no rhythm" disease. In which case, it makes
-&e->sense.

It's called funk, it's called soul, it's called flavor, and yes, it's fun 
to make and creative and can go too far for some people.  It's called 
pushing the art form, and it is the life force of all creative movements.  
Without this element of music we'd all be playing Amazing Grace and 
Gregorian chants.  I'm not saying everything that's weird is good, far 
from it... but when someone can make/play effective compelling dance music 
that's well outside the same old shit, I for one tend to be STOKED.

I would way rather hear a DJ take 20 risks and have a couple land wrong 
and a couple just be insanely good than some fucking douchebag playing a 
pre-picked set of sleepily similar garbage.  It's the difference between 
experiencing a performing musician who happens to use other people's 
records as their real time collage, and some uptight dork taking a test 
where there's a "right" and "wrong" answer for each "mix here point".  
It's like a lot of the "techno" I keep hearing at clubs around town... 
wake me up when you do something for a change instead of mixing soulless 
tech-house garbage I've heard a thousand times before.  Just like when I 
see a live band, I don't want perfection, i want jamming, improv, fun, and 
not exactly what I heard on the record.  In the digital age, making a 
perfect Xerox is *way* easy, it's coming up with some whammy on things, 
flexing a bit that makes it fun.

As long as we've got our cocks out ready to slap, I wanna fucking 
schlongpummel anybody who makes boring formulaic shit that's been done a 
thousand times over and has the nerve to call it "progressive" or new in 
any way.  32 beat cliches abound in almost every genre nowadays, the 
builds and breakdowns are all kinda the same lately, who's making the real 
shit?  Where the fucking artists at?  As we move more and more towards 
tools like Ableton Live, "beat" tools that "fix" loops so the beats are 
right on the 16s... music is getting further and further from a 
manifestation of human rhythm with shuffle and accents and becoming 
metronomic and cold preset- punching genre correct commodity crap.  
Seriously, modern dance music with little exception is in a state of this 
morbid manifestation of the addage "those who cannot remember the past are 
condemned to repeat it".

over and over and over again
andyw

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

I dunno - some amount of formula to dance music doesn't bother me that bad. 
It's when I hear a sound or style formula go ape-shit and rampant that I 
tend to get bored a bit more easily. (read - I don't wanna hear the same 
fucking "style" being mirrored and repeated till it's beat to death and you 
can no longer distinguish between artists)

I don't mind some experimentation and risk with production or performance - 
I agree it helps in some situations. But, I have heard some bands/DJ's go a 
bit too far with warping their material, and some who could've stood to do 
something a bit less (or more) than an exact copy of the original.

It all really boils down to how the artist works the material. Either they 
will work what they have, or they won't. Just because a track is "different" 
than the norm doesn't make it any good. and just because a track is very 
"the norm" doesn't make it bad. Some people can just execute the idea better 
than others.

Sorta like the Ramones - they played music that is EASY copied/ripped off. A 
billion bands (like Green Day for instance) have capitalized on their idea 
to some success, but you know damn well that NO ONE has done it to the 
perfection the Ramones did. (and no, just because Green Day has sold a 
billion albums does not mean what they have done with that style is 
innovative or interesting - it just means people are fucking sheep and will 
buy what is forcefed them). They (the Ramones) knew how to execute that 
sound/style/vibe to perfection whereas others can try and can even be 
technically "perfect", but they will never get that "it" factor into the 
music.

>On Wed, 27 Jun 2007, Van Mundegaarde wrote:
>-&e->I am NOT a fan of techno that sounds like it is off. In fact, I wanna
>-&e->cockslap the producers who make stuff like that for wanking off on 
>their
>-&e->gear a bit too hard for their own good.
>
>Well, I gave an example of what I was talking about... not sure if you're
>referring specifically to that or some piece of alien math rock or what...
>if someone can find that set I was referring to by me and Chris @ Moksha,
>the whole room (househeads, breakshead, etc) was going apeshit... plenty
>of SFravers were there, it went off despite some deep shuffled jack-style
>stuff.  Ironically, the DJ after us played "straighter" Belgian/German
>minimal style techno and lost most of the dance floor in short order.
>Ooops, looks like someone left out the "fun" in that set, bing bong!  EZ
>to dance to, sure, but why...
>
>Referring to the original post from Eric, Mattski is a damn good DJ, one
>of the best in town.  He can play house that will totally fucking drop
>science on your head.  He can also drop some techno that is pretty
>fucking out there with this wickedly swung groove.  I support him as an
>artist, he's brave and soulful and visceral and fun and he's had me
>dancing like my feet are on fire on many occasions.
>
>-&e->Dance music should be danceable. Period. If it is "off time" or
>-&e->"experimental" it is not "dance music". Unless it's made for those who 
>are
>-&e->afflicted with the dreaded "no rhythm" disease. In which case, it 
>makes
>-&e->sense.
>
>It's called funk, it's called soul, it's called flavor, and yes, it's fun
>to make and creative and can go too far for some people.  It's called
>pushing the art form, and it is the life force of all creative movements.
>Without this element of music we'd all be playing Amazing Grace and
>Gregorian chants.  I'm not saying everything that's weird is good, far
>from it... but when someone can make/play effective compelling dance music
>that's well outside the same old shit, I for one tend to be STOKED.
>
>I would way rather hear a DJ take 20 risks and have a couple land wrong
>and a couple just be insanely good than some fucking douchebag playing a
>pre-picked set of sleepily similar garbage.  It's the difference between
>experiencing a performing musician who happens to use other people's
>records as their real time collage, and some uptight dork taking a test
>where there's a "right" and "wrong" answer for each "mix here point".
>It's like a lot of the "techno" I keep hearing at clubs around town...
>wake me up when you do something for a change instead of mixing soulless
>tech-house garbage I've heard a thousand times before.  Just like when I
>see a live band, I don't want perfection, i want jamming, improv, fun, and
>not exactly what I heard on the record.  In the digital age, making a
>perfect Xerox is *way* easy, it's coming up with some whammy on things,
>flexing a bit that makes it fun.
>
>As long as we've got our cocks out ready to slap, I wanna fucking
>schlongpummel anybody who makes boring formulaic shit that's been done a
>thousand times over and has the nerve to call it "progressive" or new in
>any way.  32 beat cliches abound in almost every genre nowadays, the
>builds and breakdowns are all kinda the same lately, who's making the real
>shit?  Where the fucking artists at?  As we move more and more towards
>tools like Ableton Live, "beat" tools that "fix" loops so the beats are
>right on the 16s... music is getting further and further from a
>manifestation of human rhythm with shuffle and accents and becoming
>metronomic and cold preset- punching genre correct commodity crap.
>Seriously, modern dance music with little exception is in a state of this
>morbid manifestation of the addage "those who cannot remember the past are
>condemned to repeat it".
>
>over and over and over again
>andyw

>>Techno refers to the philosophical concept of
>>technique, a key contributor to the development of IT
>>and virtual machines (computers).  I think Jacques
>>Ellul put it best "...when technique enters into every
>>area of life, including the human [including the
>>human's music] it ceases to be external to man and
>>becomes his very substance."
>>
>>That we see best with dave clarke, who has repeatedly
>>reminded us that Underground anthems are techno, which
>>go to a core of the collective desire and transform
>>electronics (experimental, minimal) into something
>>inate, a vibe. And thus, techno is the ultimate rebel
>>music, desireing no more to jack (thieve, mercelessly)
>>the house, fuck u w/ liquid layers of 303, and get
>>darker than sweedish anarchy death metal, to build-up
>>driven melody that sounds so sickly sweet it created a
>>particular type of scenester - candy.
>>
>>technique applied to dance music has the goal of
>>making everyone dance. (which may not be simoltaneous)
>>And by dance, i mean dance to the music, not the
>>sexual ego demaning attention which represents the
>>typical house/club atmosphere. Techno is to lose
>>oneself, an outter body experience that fucks me up
>>intellectually, physically, and retrospectively more
>>so than any substance.
>>
>>as is written in graffiti of aphex twin's windowlicker
>>music video (an artist who's technique surpassed the
>>goal and "warped" it into a cd friendly
>>post-psychadelia product).
>>
>>TECHNO IS GOD (really)
>>
>>much love, Morgan Trueblood, Denizen ConeXus
>>
>>((anyone got a sharpie))

>> > > >Scott could and would play whole sets of this

>> > > >also about twice as hard to mix as something with
>> > a more stable count, a
>> > > >big part of that genre is setting up
>> > swing/shuffle/groove templates that
>> > > >are so whack that the snare or hi hats will seem
>> > noticably behind.  This
>> > > >element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but
>> > it's pushed to the
>> > > >foreground with Jack.  It's also extra fun to mix
>> > with a very minimal
>> > > >straighter sounding record (really the only way
>> > to get in/out of those
>> > > >kinds of records).
>> > > >
>> > > >Rolling basslines, hypnotic repetition, a
>> > penchant for almost cartoony
>> > > >accents using bits of voice or quirky synth
>> > lines, and snare/hihat stuff
>> > > >all over the place.  Just really another
>> > direction to explore in breaking
>> > > >some of the shackles that bind dance music.
>> > Compounding this, a lot of
>> > > >these records are genuinely fuckign weird in
>> > other ways and have to be
>> > > >thrown on a beat other than the one, have

>> > > >would actually put star stickers on these records

>>> > recalibrate my brain a

>>> > >tweaks your melon is exactly the point.
>>> > >

>>> > good distance away from
>>> > >metronomic perfection.  Anyone can quantize a
>>> > sequence- few can do what it
>>> > >takes to churn people's shit up.  Take James Brown-
>>> > that's some serious
>>> > >dance music!  Sure isn't "on" all the time though.
>>> > >
>>> > >...and that's why people love to dance to it.  It
>>> > corresponds to your
>>> > >body's imperfect, impulsive, freaky movements.
>>> > >

>>> > razor-sharp grid that is a lot
>>> > >of techno would fade into featureless monotony all

>>> > > >
>>> > > >-&e->Part of this goes back to a time when I had
>>> > Mattski
>>> > > >
>>> > > >ah ha!
>>> > > >
>>> > > >Think I figured it out...
>>> > > >
>>> > > >MATTSKI IS FUCKING INSANE/RETARDED/AHEAD OF HIS
>>> > TIME/ON ANOTHER PLANE.
>>> > > >
>>> > > >He has records that are so incredibly
>>> > rhythmically nutty, that fall in
>>> > > >line with a genre usually referred to as "Jack"
>>> > (usually associated with
>>> > > >Chicago, but people from Japan to Sweden have
>>> > released stuff in that
>>> > > >vibe).  While a few of us in the San Jose techno
>>> > cabal had a love for
>>> > >this
>>> > > >(it *is* funky as all hell, and fun to mix,
>>> > sorta), Mattski and Derek
>>> > > >Scott could and would play whole sets of this
>>> > stuff.  Think weird DJ Rush
>>> > > >stuff, it's something some people just love and
>>> > others not so much.  It's
>>> > > >also about twice as hard to mix as something with
>>> > a more stable count, a
>>> > > >big part of that genre is setting up
>>> > swing/shuffle/groove templates that
>>> > > >are so whack that the snare or hi hats will seem
>>> > noticably behind.  This
>>> > > >element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but
>>> > it's pushed to the
>>> > > >foreground with Jack.  It's also extra fun to mix
>>> > with a very minimal
>>> > > >straighter sounding record (really the only way
>>> > to get in/out of those
>>> > > >kinds of records).
>>> > > >
>>> > > >Rolling basslines, hypnotic repetition, a
>>> > penchant for almost cartoony
>>> > > >accents using bits of voice or quirky synth
>>> > lines, and snare/hihat stuff
>>> > > >all over the place.  Just really another
>>> > direction to explore in breaking
>>> > > >some of the shackles that bind dance music.
>>> > Compounding this, a lot of
>>> > > >these records are genuinely fuckign weird in
>>> > other ways and have to be
>>> > > >thrown on a beat other than the one, have
>>> > strange-count breaks, etc (I
>>> > > >would actually put star stickers on these records
>>> > to avoid grabbing them
>>> > > >when I literally can't see, which also used to
>>> > happen to me from time to
>>> > > >time... I have very light sensitive eyes and a
>>> > good pass across my face
>>> > > >from a cyberlight or goldenscan would just
>>> > cripple me for 20 seconds or
>>> > > >so).
>>> > > >
>>> > > >-&e->play at our room at the first Mega-Buzz...
>>> > One of
>>> > > >-&e->biggest systems I had ever played on. It was
>>> > so loud,
>>> > > >-&e->the reverb off the walls so gnarly, and I
>>> > was so
>>> > > >-&e->stoked to have pulled off the main room at
>>> > home bass
>>> > > >-&e->for the $2000 budget I was given... Anyhow,

>>> > > >-&e->seriously could not tell if it was a train

>>> > > >-&e->perfectly ordered kaos. I believe it was the

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Is EVERYBODY on coke now? WTF?

LOL I was a bit older than that at the time. ;)

Actually I lived in LA for most of the eighties.  It was a really weird time for me personally.

We went to the Palace a lot, some underground punk parties, the Cat and Fiddle pub (and many other bars, pubs, etc.) and we also sometimes frequented this super snotty club in Beverly Hills.  I got invited to join by this girl I knew that was friends with Cher's PA or something stupid like that.  In LA it seems like everyone knows someone famous.  The club's name was a number, but damn if I can remember it.  Rod Stewart was a member and also some other famous type people.  They had a dance floor that changed colors and was lit from below.  Lots of blow.  Everywhere.  People snorted right at the tables.

But I was already really down on coke by then because of the damage I had seen done during my college years and so I did not partake.  

But I sure drank a lot during the eighties.  Phew.  

Peace,

Peter

P.S. I'll take bad hair over NO hair!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Is EVERYBODY on coke now? WTF?

I do drink on occasion- I find it to be a low-commitment social lubricant, and fun, as long as I don't overdo it.  I was mainly speaking to the fact that my zeal for inebriants in general has faded significantly of late.  I still dig a good hard party night now and again, but I find I value a clear head a lot more these days.  

I've been to a number of parties lately, that start out great great great, friendly, everyone smiling and laughing and dancing...  ...until somebody shows up with blow or gets a bug up their butt about finding some, and then people descend into shady, secretive, fiendy BS.  It's so sad!  It's like "oh great, we have to do this now, awesome.", like somebody changing the channel from Discovery to QVC.  Cellphones come out, people lock themselves in bedrooms, etc.

I love plenty of people that love coke, but it sure sucks to see them metamorphose on it.  Or to feel compelled to jump in myself so I can be on the same wavelength.
-G

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Is EVERYBODY on coke now? WTF?

I've noticed a lot of this too. It probably has a lot to do with
'thizz' and the steep decline and stepping-on of thizz pills.
Ghettonomics has determined that people in a crowd can't tell what's
in your pills, and if you put just a taste of mdma in there, it will
have people coming back to find you and hand over more $10 bills.
Meanwhile, the meth kicks in and it suddenly makes sense to pop a few
more in hopes of catching the ecstatic euphoria. Eventually, your
customers don't even mind that there's no E in your Es, because now
they /want/ the tweak.

My point being, here, that the decline in quality in raves' #1 drug
means all those kids that 'just want to have fun' are going to search
out drugs with a more reliable effect. The interest in cocaine will
probably wane as the coked out dealers get greedier and step on THEIR
shit more and more

...and then we'll all be on OCs, because the drug companies are the
only ones pushing fixed dose reliable crack! Buy Pfizer.

Acid's great, but I can't picture tripping at a rave, unless it had the
perfect vibe. I've been rolling and seen shit where I've been glad I wasn't
on acid/shrooms at the time...When you find stuff like people shaking from
amphetamine overload and looking nervous at a rave, it's great to feel
empathy in your blood so you can go up, talk to them and offer to smoke them
out. I think if I were tripping, that would freak me out and I wouldn't be
able to add anything to the experience.

And fuck methy pills! Maybe this shit went out the window years ago, I saw
some video about it in high school, but why isn't there anything like
DanceSafe tents at raves? Some of their kits just tell you "there's e in
this pill" but other kits can breakdown fairly well the contents of a pill.
Does this just not gel with promoters/venues, as if it confirms there are
drugs in the building? My next roll is at Space Girls, hopefully Santa Cruz
throws down the molly...

On 6/28/07, georgeC | origami <newstylesound@yahoo.com> wrote:
>
> I do drink on occasion- I find it to be a low-commitment social lubricant,
> and fun, as long as I don't overdo it.  I was mainly speaking to the fact
> that my zeal for inebriants in general has faded significantly of late.  I
> still dig a good hard party night now and again, but I find I value a clear
> head a lot more these days.
>
> I've been to a number of parties lately, that start out great great great,
> friendly, everyone smiling and laughing and dancing...  ...until somebody
> shows up with blow or gets a bug up their butt about finding some, and then
> people descend into shady, secretive, fiendy BS.  It's so sad!  It's like
> "oh great, we have to do this now, awesome.", like somebody changing the
> channel from Discovery to QVC.  Cellphones come out, people lock themselves
> in bedrooms, etc.
>
> I love plenty of people that love coke, but it sure sucks to see them
> metamorphose on it.  Or to feel compelled to jump in myself so I can be on
> the same wavelength.
> -G
>

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: IsEVERYBODY on coke now? WTF?

Personally, I think it is retarded to talk about your
drug use on a public list. It might be ok to talk
about the effects of drugs on the scene, a particular
incident, etc... But from a personal standpoint, you
should always think twice about documenting your
debauchery... You never know when it might come from
nowhere to bite you in the ass...

Think not? What about getting a DUI, or Drunk in
Public, or possession charge under an overzealous new
DA trying to make a point... and they "happen" to know
about list-serves on the internet... and after they
confiscate your comupter find you are on sfr, read the
logged messages, and have your personal account of
behavior...

Think i'm crazy? I've seen it happen... in the last
year... fortunately to a scumbag GHB, coke, K, meth
dealer that tried to crash his way into our group of
friends. Luckily, I politely excused him from our
group 18 months before he went down, as he was way
sketchy, overt, braggered, and pushing NASTY stuff
like GHB on everyone...

Just a thought...

E

Subject: [sfraves] Wanna buy vinyl??? READ ME


This is only gonna apply to those that can *physically* come see/hear shit, 
cuz I just don't have time to catalog my records and give a list.

I am moving this weekend and wanna lighten my load, plus I need money bad as 
hell right now (moving is muy expensivo).

Now before people freak out and tell me not to sell my vinyl...I am only 
selling stuff I can get on MP3 (cuz I can play CD's and Final Scratch/Serato 
now). Mainly breaks and tech-funk, but there is some techno, tech-house, and 
other assorted crap in there as well. Preferrably people who wanna come hear 
this shit either tonight or tomorrow will scooby on this ASAP....

I will be selling most titles for around $2 - $3 a record.

Stuff *not* for sale (i.e. rare/white labels/booties/etc.)  MAY be bartered 
for, but it's not gonna be nearly as cheap in all honesty (there's a reason 
it's not in the normal "for sale" list). Tons of this stuff is fairly new 
condition, and relatively recent - so maybe you missed getting some titles 
on vinyl and don't have the ability to rock MP3's (or just plain prefer 
vinyl). This sale is FOR YOU :)

Message me off list to schedule time to come sift/needle drop...I live at 
3rd Avenue & Geary in SF.


Marc(O)
The Mario Bros.//OtherWorld//Ill Behavior//The MidnightSons (DC/SF)
www.themidnightsons.com
www.myspace.com/the_mario_bros
www.myspace.com/illectrofunk

Who not? It's not cool? I admit it. Who fucking cares? Even when I had a 
love affair with vinyl I never would hate on a jock for playing CDs, so 
long as he/she was actually deejaying.

Am I less of a deejay because I play CDs now after 10 years of 
collecting records? I say no. The only people that care are record nerds 
anyways. And I've always hated those people for the most part. Usually 
working at the record stores and hording anything remotely rare so that 
it never makes its way to the sales floor where us "normal people" can 
buy them. But it's just not that, they usually are the WORST deejays.  
Fucking record nerds.

I haven't bought a record in about 11 months now and I'm proud of it. 
I'll still play some old records when there are 1200s at a party, only 
old stuff I haven't sold yet though. Anyone want any records? I've got 
about 3,000 to go!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Techno Question for Andy W....

That pretty much answered my question. Some of it came
to mind as I was going through records for "BACK ON
TRACK" this weekend. I have a lot of techno records
that I like, but never play. Lots from the late 90's
and early 00's. When I was listening to them, many had
production oddities, some written in 12 bar fashion,
some 8, some 16, and some seemingly without any
numerical resolution at all. Just got me thinking
back, whether this was a trend to be "different", a
visit to the world of musically ignorant but sonically
cool, etc... 

The "I put a sticker on some records" was really the
answer for me... lets me know that yes, some shit is
just wrong... but sounds cool anyhow.

E

--- AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> wrote:

> 
> On Tue, 26 Jun 2007, Eric Spire wrote:
> -&e->Sometimes Techno mixes sound to be off measure
> wise to
> -&e->me. I can do the math on a single, and
> sometimes they
> -&e->seem "normal" and sometimes odd... Like
> high-hats
> 
> ok.
> 
> -&e->coming in on the down beats, kicks later, and
> patterns
> -&e->that seem off. Whats the deal? I know there is
> numbers
> -&e->difference betroit6 Detroit/Chicago vs
> German/Euro
> 
> ok.
> 
> -&e->Enlighten me please....
> 
> ok.
> 
> -&e->Part of this goes back to a time when I had
> Mattski
> 
> ah ha!
> 
> Think I figured it out...
> 
> MATTSKI IS FUCKING INSANE/RETARDED/AHEAD OF HIS
> TIME/ON ANOTHER PLANE.
> 
> He has records that are so incredibly rhythmically
> nutty, that fall in 
> line with a genre usually referred to as "Jack"
> (usually associated with 
> Chicago, but people from Japan to Sweden have
> released stuff in that 
> vibe).  While a few of us in the San Jose techno
> cabal had a love for this 
> (it *is* funky as all hell, and fun to mix, sorta),
> Mattski and Derek 
> Scott could and would play whole sets of this stuff.
>  Think weird DJ Rush 
> stuff, it's something some people just love and
> others not so much.  It's 
> also about twice as hard to mix as something with a
> more stable count, a 
> big part of that genre is setting up
> swing/shuffle/groove templates that 
> are so whack that the snare or hi hats will seem
> noticably behind.  This 
> element exists in a lot of Latin rhythms, but it's
> pushed to the 
> foreground with Jack.  It's also extra fun to mix
> with a very minimal 
> straighter sounding record (really the only way to
> get in/out of those 
> kinds of records).
> 
> Rolling basslines, hypnotic repetition, a penchant
> for almost cartoony 
> accents using bits of voice or quirky synth lines,
> and snare/hihat stuff 
> all over the place.  Just really another direction
> to explore in breaking 
> some of the shackles that bind dance music. 
> Compounding this, a lot of 
> these records are genuinely fuckign weird in other
> ways and have to be 
> thrown on a beat other than the one, have
> strange-count breaks, etc (I 
> would actually put star stickers on these records to
> avoid grabbing them 
> when I literally can't see, which also used to
> happen to me from time to 
> time... I have very light sensitive eyes and a good
> pass across my face 
> from a cyberlight or goldenscan would just cripple
> me for 20 seconds or 
> so).
> 
> -&e->play at our room at the first Mega-Buzz... One
> of
> -&e->biggest systems I had ever played on. It was so
> loud,
> -&e->the reverb off the walls so gnarly, and I was
> so
> -&e->stoked to have pulled off the main room at home
> bass
> -&e->for the $2000 budget I was given... Anyhow, at
> times I
> -&e->seriously could not tell if it was a train
> wreck or
> -&e->perfectly ordered kaos. I believe it was the
> latter. I
> -&e->just remember hard beats with an off shuffle,
> with one
> -&e->elastic tweaker sound on each track that just
> made it
> -&e->all melt into craziness.
> 
> Exactly!  Sounds like you had an open mind about it,
> but the sound in that 
> place was probably a mess.  And another thing about
> massives, after a 
> couple hours of crap at that volume, your hearing
> just smears anyway.  
> It's why I always used to go for a walk right before
> a set, just give my 
> ears a chance to relax and be fresh.
> 
> And to be honest, it's a bear to mix on loud
> systems, especially with back 
> wall reverb or a lack of proper monitors (you can't
> trust the kick, or 
> basslines, or snare or hihats exclusively, the "true
> 1" depends on the 
> record).  If anybody has audio of that Moksha party
> where Chris Jackson 
> and I did a 2x4 set, parts of that were Jackin as
> all hell and I recall 
> both of us were in it pretty good (and we were in a
> damn good mood, Moksha 
> Krooo had set us up with a Schmoke and a Pancake and
> good monitors and a 
> 12 pack of the olde Nut Brown... although I recall

BRUNO PRONSATO

Seattle via Berlin producer Bruno Pronsato (aka Steven Ford) took several
giant steps in 2005 toward the peak of the experimental techno mountain.
Both on vinyl and onstage, Pronsato kept up a hectic pace of production and
performance, catalyzing listeners and crowds in Germany, Switzerland,
Turkey, Mexico, throughout the United States, and a triumphant set at
Montreal's MUTEK festival. Twelve-inches on esteemed labels like Orac,
Musique Risqu=E9e, Milnor Modern, Philpot, and Telegraph further elevated h=
is
stature and built his international fan base.

A sound scientist whose work is equally playful and rigorous, Pronsato
deploys a canny use of space and idiosyncratically fashioned rhythms to
disorient and build suspense=97like some 21st-century Miles Davis or Eric
Dolphy of the laptop. Despite being a minimal-techno artist, Pronsato offer=
s
a palette that's as full of unexpected patterns and meticulously rendered
textures as a Wassily Kandinsky painting.

Pronsato's compositions unsettle in original ways, yet they also slyly
tickle funnybones. Often both humorous and erotic, his cuts are the wild
cards that adventurous DJs pull out when they want to take the dance floor
to strange new levels of motion. Therefore, Pronsato's releases have become
elite selectors' secret weapons of beguilingly baffling quirkiness that
still move asses.

Unsurprisingly, 2006 is promising to be as eventful as last year. As demand
for his music has waxed, Pronsato has accordingly increased his productivit=
y
while maintaining his usual exacting quality control standards. March will
bring Pronsato's debut 12 for Hello? Repeat while summer 2006 will see EPs
issued by Orac and Telegraph (watch for the last two editions of the
four-part Limeworks series), plus another collaboration with Argentinean
Franco Cinelli for Milnor Modern (Picaro, their first joint effort from lat=
e
'05, contains some of Pronsato's most flavorful club bangers). A temporary
residence in Holland will enable Pronsato to spend even more time in 2006
devastating European audiences with his uniquely psychedelic and funky
techno live sets.


Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Bruno%20Pronsato

Website:
http://www.undosounds.com/

Exclusive interview w/ Bruno on mnml.nl:
http://www.mnml.nl/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=3D7908


________________________________________________


DRUMCELL

Founder of Droid Recordings and co-founder of Droid Behavior, Drumcell (aka
Mohamed "Moe" Espinosa) has been one of techno's greatest allies in Souther=
n
California in recent times. A graduate of the Musician's Institute and a
long-time performer at parties in Southern California, Drumcell has been
influenced by music from his earliest years. After being exposed to raves i=
n
the early 90s, He grew addicted to the sounds of acid house, techno, in its
many forms, and industrial.

It was not long before he was copping turntables to satisfy his vinyl
fetish. By the early age of 14 he was playing in various local bands, and
through out the rest of his teenage years, cut his teeth-producing hip hop
records, dub and various forms of electronic music on Los Angeles based
underground labels. By combining his production, DJing and networking skill=
s
and focusing in on his more mature musical tastes he soon established
himself as one of the major players in LA's growing techno scene.

Associating with the members of Acid Circus to form Droid Behavior as an
event production group and record label was the next logical step to raise
awareness for techno in the city and to help expose local Artists,
established djs, and performers from around the country.

Over the last 5 years Drumcell has rocked parties from big to small on a
weekly basis in LA as well as gigs all over the U.S alongside such names as
Kenny Larkin, John Tejada, Tim Xavier, Daniel Bell, Ben Sims, Adam Beyer,
Jeff Mills, Speedy J, Ritchie Hawtin, Mathew Dear, etc. and has also
released quite a few heavy tracks on labels Omniscient, Remains, Heavy
Industries, and his own DROID Recordings imprint.

Drumcell has been known to keep on the edge of technology and continuously
pushing the limits to what the future has to offer.He is always in the
process of developing homebrew software as well as cutting edge hardware
solution to bring a fresh innovative taste to his production and
performances. When performing, Drumcell can be seen blurring the lines
between a live and a DJ set by utilizing tools such as FX processors,
samplers, drum machines and other devices  to weave a thick blend of acidic
techno and aggressive but funky minimalist groove to ensure a frenzy amongs=
t
his listeners.

With the state of electronic music in North America leaning towards strippe=
d
down funk rather then progressive fluff these days, Droid has become the
center for LA techno and Drumcell remains steadfast in his mission of
putting this city on the global map.


Website:
http://www.droidbehavior.com/drumcell.html

Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Drumcell

MySpace:
http://www.mypsace.com/drumcell

Live Recording:
http://www.rotfest.com/droid/mp3/Drumcell_Live@Avalon_R.Hawtin-J.Mills.mp3

Most Recent Studio mix :
http://www.rotfest.com/droid/mp3/drumcell%20mix%202.mp3


_____________________________________________________


JAMESPATRICK

JamesPatrick promotes and plays detail oriented dance music for the feet an=
d
the mind.  Directing a movement of minimal/dub techno in the Midwest, JP
pushes the definitions of "forward thinking media" into new realms.
"Improvising with music and technology" has become the manifesto of his
lifelong journey.

JamesPatrick has enjoyed 10+ years of playing music around the world, and
throwing parties with, and playing alongside likewise innovators in the
genre;  Bruno Pronsato, Someone Else, Miskate, Ezekiel Honig, Sutekh, Sammy
Dee, Jay Haze, Magda, Richie Hawtin, Algorithm, Ben Nevile, Randy Jones,
Jake Fairley, Dapayk, Baby Ford, Mike Shannon, Deadbeat/Crackhaus, Barem,
Butane, Richard Devine, and many more.

JP has for the last few years also been one half of the Klikmusik project
with fellow Minneapolis techno afficionado Mike G.  Their two man extended
cooperative dj+laptop+fx sets have captivated listeners throughout the
Midwest while pushing the boundaries of a traditional DJ set to new levels.

Currently, JP teaches software music production at Minneapolis' Institute o=
f
Production and Recording, and he directs the websites www.microphono.com,
www.vitalvinyl.com, and www.secrettechno.com.


MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/microhouseminneapolis

DJ sets:
http://secrettechno.com/jamespatrick/geologic1.15.05/jamespatrick-geologic7=
.17.2005.mp3

http://secrettechno.com/jamespatrick/natspill1.27.07/jamespatrick@natspill1=
.27.07.mp3

More DJ sets:
www.secrettechno.com/jamespatrick

sixty4k (Mirai Kanai, Ambient Mafia)
Omino (The Extra Credit, WOMSF)
Peek (Thump Chill, Ambient Mafia, Below Zero / 92.7FM)
Redstickman (Ambient Mafia, FnF)
Squelchy (The Extra Credit, Ambient Mafia)
Hickory (The Extra Credit, Ambient Mafia)
Cubik & Origami (Dinner Party, The Extra Credit, Ambient Mafia)
Cumulus (The Extra Credit, WOMSF)
Ganucheau (The Extra Credit, Native States)
Mo Corleone vs. DJ Chai (Ambient Mafia, Want It)

B.Y.O.B. to use at our Mixer Bar (you bring the booze, our lovely
assistants will mix your drink!)

$5-$10 suggested donation

See you there in yer jammies!!
